<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British PM Announces Policies to Transform Poor Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair on Tuesday Pledged radical policies to transform Britain's
poorest communities where crime, drugs, poverty and unemployment
have been rampant.
</P>
<P>
Blair unveiled the new measures in Hackney district in London,
promising a new "joined-up" approach which would give local
communities more power to solve their own problems.
</P>
<P>
Blair promised that 800 million pounds (1.3 billion U.S.
dollars) would be spent on a "New Deal for Communities" to reverse
this trend. But the key to the new scheme is not just cash but
better coordination between different parts of the government
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
He said there were "no instant solutions or quick fixes" but
promised a concerted effort over the next 10 or 20 years,
beginning with 17 pilot area schemes.
</P>
<P>
A report published on Tuesday by the Social Exclusion Unit, set
up by Blair last year, estimates Britain may have up to 4,000 such
problem neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
The report says net incomes after housing costs of the richest
tenth of the British population rose by 68 percent between 1979
and 1995.
</P>
<P>
Government ministries and local authorities will work together
rather than separately in 18 "action teams" to tackle the problems
-- crime, health, jobs, schools, transport and housing, Blair
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
