<HEADLINE> Singapore Senior Minister on His Memoirs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Senior Minister
Lee Kuan Yew told a press conference Tuesday evening that he wrote
his memoirs for the purpose to let young Singaporeans know
Singapore's history and to make a contribution to the history
records of his country.
</P>
<P>
He held the press conference one day before his million-word
memoirs is published on his 75th birthday that falls on September
16.
</P>
<P>
Quoting Malaysian Prime Minister Mahathir as saying that
Singapore has used the weakness of its neighbors to achieve
economic prosperity and the publication of Lee's memoirs "will
bring about bad effect on Malaysia,", Lee Kuan Yew argued that the
book "is my personal account of the events that had shaped my
life, and when I was prime minister (1959-90), which also affected
Singapore's history."
</P>
<P>
"I set out to give young Singaporeans an objective account of
why and how Singapore sought merger with Malaya but in two years
was asked to leave," he said.
</P>
<P>
Dismissing the criticism that he has chosen to publish his book
when Malaysia is in difficulties to take advantage of it, the
senior minister said he started writing in 1995 and the timing to
publish was settled last year.
</P>
<P>
He stated that "what I have written, I have checked against the
records, especially when recounting the race riots of 1964."
</P>
<P>
"I expected my book to be scrutinized and criticized," he said.
"if there are false or untrue statements, I will stand
contradicted and my credibility demolished," he added
</P>
<P>
Answering a question about what made Singapore successful, he
said the decisive factor is the human being.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Singapore is an island that has no large land area
and rich resources, he underlined that "the people became the
critical factor when we came across the strategic field."
</P>
<P>
"That meant diligent, strong, arduous leadership, well
educated, well organized, productive workforce," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Without that we could not succeed," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
He also said the circumstances forced Singapore to look at the
world and to seek outside market.
</P>
<P>
The history of Singapore indicates that the development of
Singapore is closely linked to the development of the world, he
noted, saying "When the world developed, Singapore would
develop."
</P>
<P>
"Without that world economy, Singapore will go back to a
fishing village and we will never forget that lesson," he
stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
