<HEADLINE> No Pakistani Army Involvement in Afghan Conflict: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
During a meeting with Iranian Ambassador in Islamabad Mehdi
Akoundzadeh who called on him at the Prime Minister House, Sharif
rejected "baseless" allegations regarding the involvement of
Pakistan's armed forces in the recent fighting in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the Iranian leadership would view
the current development with their wisdom.
</P>
<P>
Sharif's remarks came one day after Iran alleged that some
Pakistani army personnel were involved in the recent Afghan
fighting. Tension between Pakistan and Iran heightened following
the Taliban victories in northern Afghanistan and the killing of
nine Iranian nationals by the Taliban.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister reiterated that Pakistan gives high priority
to its relations with Iran and would like to take all necessary
steps to remove any misgiving or misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
Noting that Pakistan has extended full support to efforts which
led to the release of five Iranian prisoners and the return of the
bodies of the Iranian personnel killed in Afghanistan, Sharif
stressed that Pakistan will spare no effort to preserve and
nurture its abiding relationship with Iran.
</P>
<P>
He also called upon both Iran and Afghanistan to defuse the
present tension between them and pursue a path of restraint,
mutual understanding, reconciliation and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Sharif said that Pakistan has made most sincere efforts in the
past and would continue to offer all assistance in order to defuse
the tension between the two neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
He offered to support all efforts at the United Nations and the
Organization of Islamic Conference to defuse the tension and all
political initiatives to resolve the outstanding problems.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Sharif and Akoundzadeh discussed matters
of mutual concern, including the regional situation with special
reference to Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
