<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Opposition Demands Referendum on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Zambian opposition party
Agenda for Zambia (AZ) has demanded a referendum to allow people
a chance of deciding whether Barotseland, now Western Province,
should reclaim independence from Zambia.
</P>
<P>
In a statement released here Monday, AZ president Akashambatwa
Mbikusita-Lweanika (Aka) said that his party leaders met ten days
ago in Barotseland and the majority view was that integration
based on real political freedom, with honest power sharing and
equal justice was impossible under Zambia.
</P>
<P>
"For this reason, participants demanded Barotse
self-determination through referendum," The Post newspaper
Tuesday quoted Aka as saying.
</P>
<P>
Aka, a member of the Barotse Royal Establishment and son of
late King of Barotseland, Mbikusita Lewanika, said: "The idea is
to give people a chance to say if they want to continue living as
a captive nation under Zambian tribal domination, or to reclaim
independence as a free state."
</P>
<P>
The opposition leader noted that his party members would have
preferred a government system under which national leadership
alternated between regions to prevent one group ruling forever.
</P>
<P>
He added that the proposed referendum would be a "peaceful and
democratic solution."
</P>
<P>
Government-owned Times of Zambia newspaper reported last month
that seditious materials on the status of Barotseland emerged in
Lusaka, prompting the government to threaten to deal with those
distributing them ruthlessly.
</P>
<P>
The brochures circulated by a group calling itself the Barotse
Patriotic Front on Self-Determination demanded independence of
Western Province from the Zambian central government.
</P>
<P>
Barotseland enjoyed half independence under British colonial
rule and strove to become an independent country before it became
part of Zambia soon after the country won its dependence from
Britain in 1964. The land got its present name in 1969. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
