<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus, Greece Sign Cultural Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Cyprus and Greece Signed
here Tuesday a cultural cooperation program for the years
1998-2000.
</P>
<P>
The agreement, signed by Cyprus' Culture Minister Lycourgos
Kappas and his visiting Greek counterpart Evangleos Venizelos,
provides for upgraded Greek participation in the annual Cyprus
festival "Ta Kypria", now underway, the furthering of cooperation
in theater, music, cinema and archaeology, as well as exchanges
and cooperation in the international art and music fields.
</P>
<P>
It also provides for Cyprus' participation in the Cultural
Olympiad to take place in Greece from the year 2000 to 2004.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the signing ceremony, Kappas said that "as we
believe closer cultural cooperation is our national duty, the two
ministries have developed close ties aiming at safeguarding the
historical identity of the Greek nation."
</P>
<P>
He added that meetings between delegations of the two
ministries will be held every six months and there will be a
constant exchange of information and views.
</P>
<P>
Venizelos underlined the importance of cultural cooperation
between the two countries, saying that never before had it been
set out in such a formal way as in the agreement signed Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Greek minister, meanwhile, expressed disappointment with
the European Union (EU)'s stance toward the destruction of the
cultural heritage in the Turkish-controlled northern part of the
island.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and the Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkey
landed its troops and took over the northern third of the island
in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
<P>
Venizelos said the EU should show more sensitivity as it
believes in the common European cultural heritage.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that over 500 churches in northern Cyprus are
estimated to have been looted, destructed or used for other
purposes, while archaeological sites are not given the necessary
attention for their protection. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
