<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Availability of Materials Delays Railway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A senior Nigerian official
Tuesday said that no availability of materials had delayed the
completion of the Nigerian Railway Rehabilitation Project (NRRP)
on time, hence no blames on contractor.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference held here, Greg Icukwe, Sole
Administrator of the Nigerian Railway Corporation (NRC), noted
that materials such as steel rails, sleepers, turnouts and
fastenings are supposed to be provided by Nigerian side under a
contract.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria can not produce such things and has to order from
abroad, he said. However, he added that majority of the
materials ordered for the project did not come until now.
</P>
<P>
The Nigerian official stressed that the delay "is beyond our
control" and the contractor, China Civil Engineering Construction
Corporation (CCECC), had to wait because of the delay.
</P>
<P>
The NRRP project is being undertaken by CCECC under the contract
signed by Nigerian Federal Ministry of Transport and Chinese
Ministry of Railways in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract, the Chinese side is responsible for survey
and design for 4,200 km of railway lines, track rehabilitation of
3,500 km and supply of locomotives, coaches, wagons and rail
cars, and the project should be completed within 30 months, in
another word, is scheduled to be completed by September 30 this
year.
</P>
<P>
It was believed that survey and design had been completed, 83
percent of track rehabilitation done and 80 percent of
locomotives and rolling stock delivered to NRC and put into
operation before the end of March.
</P>
<P>
Icukwe noted at the press conference that if the momentum
keeps on, the Chinese company can finish the remaining work
within one month.
</P>
<P>
For instance, he said, they brought in signal equipment for
the project, but signal houses which the Nigerian side is
supposed to build under the contract are not available.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Chen Xiaoxin, Deputy General Manager of
CCECC, told reporters that after two years of the rehabilitation,
great changes have taken place to the Nigerian railways with the
annual goods tonnage increasing from 137,000 tons to 566,000 tons
last year.
</P>
<P>
Up to August this year, he noted, the goods tonnage has
already reached 872,000 tons and are expected to be well over a
million tons, double what was last year.
</P>
<P>
The chinese official stressed that all the locomotives and
rolling stock supplied to Nigeria are manufactured in strict
conformity with the technical specifications agreed upon by both
sides.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the rumours that locomotives delivered to Nigeria
are second hand, he said, since the gauge of Chinese railways is
1435 mm while that of Nigerian railways is 1067 mm, it is
impossible for the Chinese side to renovate their standard
locomotives by tailoring to the narrow gauge.
</P>
<P>
The cost of renovation would be more than the manufacturing of
brand new ones, Chen Xiaoxin said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
