<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Prime Minister Calls Russian Counterpart on Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony
Blair called his new Russian counterpart Yevgeny Primakov on
Tuesday, saying that the world's major developed countries were
willing to help Moscow if reform continued.
</P>
<P>
Blair gave Primakov the message in a telephone conversation
following Monday's meeting of senior officials of the G7 group of
countries in London on Monday, a Blair aide said.
</P>
<P>
The 15-minute call was the first time Blair has spoken to
Primakov since he became Russia's prime minister last week.
</P>
<P>
Primakov told Blair there would be no backtracking on reform,
which he would carry forward with a new cabinet, according to the
aide.
</P>
<P>
"Blair told Primakov that G7 deputies had agreed to the
importance of staying engaged with Russia. He explained the
meeting had not been about taking decisions, but the G7 was
willing to provide help and advice on reform if Russia wanted it,"
the aide said, adding that Primakov briefed Blair on the situation
in Russia.
</P>
<P>
"Primakov said the new government would want to act vigorously.
He also said there would be no retreat from basic reform policies
which would continue," the aide said.
</P>
<P>
Primakov said he would be having talks with the International
Monetary Fund (IMF) and World Bank to discuss Moscow's funding
needs over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
Monday's meeting brought together senior officials from the G7
-- the United States, Britain, Canada, France, Germany, Italy and
Japan, and representatives from the IMF.
</P>
<P>
However, western efforts to end the current crisis have
achieved little and the IMF is under fire from critics who say its
solutions are too inflexible, Reuters said today.
</P>
<P>
Blair would call President Boris Yeltsin soon, according to the
official. 
</P>
</TEXT>
