<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Issue Deeply Understood at SADC Summit: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Angolan President Eduardo dos
Santos said here Tuesday that "Angolan issue has won deep
understanding in southern Africa."
</P>
<P>
The president said this upon returning home from the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) summit in Mauritius.
</P>
<P>
"This stance (of the southern African countries) will
contribute to the efforts by the government and all political
parties to build up the peace in Angola," Dos Santos stressed.
</P>
<P>
In response to the SADC recognition of the "UNITA Renovation
Committee", the Angolan president said that "all countries in the
region have shown their great unity for the sake of the Angolan
people and the peace cause in the country."
</P>
<P>
The SADC summit released a statement in Grande Baie of north
Mauritius Tuesday, strongly condemning the United Union for Total
Independence of Angola (UNITA) for its failure to implement the
1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol, accusing UNITA President Jonas
Savimbi for his chief crime in the civil war and expressing
support for the breakaway "UNITA Renovation Committee."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, local media said that President Dos Santos sent a
message to the United Nations General Assembly on September 10,
asking the U.N. Security Council to recognize the "UNITA
Renovation Committee" as the "only lawful dialogist" in the
Angolan peace process.
</P>
<P>
In his message, Dos Santos also called upon U.N. to withdraw
its recognition of Savimbi, citing that the UNITA president has
proven himself to be unable to lead the party in the peace
process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
