<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hezbollah Vows Continued Attacks on Pro-Israeli </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Lebanon's leading anti-Israeli
Muslim group Hezbollah, or Party of God, Tuesday vowed to
continue its attacks on the pro-Israeli militia South Lebanon
Army (SLA) in its controlled southern Christian town Jezzine.
</P>
<P>
In a ceremony marking the killed guerrillas, the
Iranian-backed Hezbollah's secretary-general, sheikh Hassan
Nasrallah, said that his party would continue to fight against
occupying forces on any piece of land in Lebanon, including
Jezzine, until all occupants are driven out of the country.
</P>
<P>
Jezzine, which lies just north of the Israeli occupied border
strip in south Lebanon with a population of 35,000, has been
policed by the SLA since the militia was created in 1985.
</P>
<P>
Nasrallah's comments came in reaction to the latest security
measures adopted by leader of the SLA Antoine Lahd.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Lahd announced that all residents of Jezzine will
have to apply for special travel permits 48 hours prior to
leaving or returning the area.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that the new measures were applied because of the
rising number of Hezbollah bombing attacks targetting his soldiers
inside the district.
</P>
<P>
The new restriction, which the SLA commander said would come
into effect on October 1, has raised fears of a mass exodus of
Jezzine's population.
</P>
<P>
"Instead of asking us to neutralize the area and stop
resistance, ask Lahd to withdraw from Jezzine and surrounding
areas and restore Lebanese government's authority on the area,"
the Hezbollah leader said.
</P>
<P>
"Only in this way, Jezzine and its residents will be
satisfied," he added.
</P>
<P>
Hezbollah is spearheading a guerrilla war in Lebanon trying
to oust 1,000 Israeli troops and 3,000 SLA militiamen from the
country.
</P>
<P>
Israel carved out a 1,200 square-kilometer self-declared
security zone in south Lebanon in 1985 to protect its north from
cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
