<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Chief Calls for More Humanitarian Aid to Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- "Fatigue over the
drawn-out peace process should not jeopardize the survival of the
millions of children and women in desperate need of continued
humanitarian assistance," Carol Bellamy, executive director of the
U.N. Children's Fund (UNICEF), said here on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Angolan children and women need out help now more than ever,"
said Bellamy, who visited Angola earlier this year and said that
she saw for herself the dire plight of the people.
</P>
<P>
"Over 20 years of civil war have devastated the country's
infrastructure, and deteriorating security over recent months has
forced thousands more families to flee their homes," she said,
adding "The need for basic necessities of life -- food, shelter,
clean water and health care -- are both urgent and immense."
</P>
<P>
More than 250,000 Angolans, 65 percent of whom are children
and women, have recently been displaced in the country and
represent a swelling of the more than 700,000 whose lives were
already displaced at the beginning of 1998.
</P>
<P>
Angola currently ranks among 174 nations on the United
Nations Development Programme's latest Human Developments Index
and has an infant mortality rate of 170 per 1,000 live births,
exceeded only Niger's 191 deaths per 1,000, according to a
UNICEF report.
</P>
<P>
"It is critical that the international community and
humanitarian agencies increase their efforts at this time to
help the people of Angola," she said.
</P>
<P>
So far the interagency humanitarian appeal for 91 million
U.S. dollars, launched by the UNICEF Executive Director on
behalf of all U.N. agencies, is only about 37 percent funded.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan Government and UNITA, the main rebel group,
signed a peace accord in 1994 which purported to end the
conflict in Angola, and a Government of National Unity and
Reconciliation was set up in 1997.
</P>
<P>
However, full implementation of the peace process remains to be
achieved, and the recent deteriorating security environment has
necessitated restriction on most of the programs of the U.N. and
the non-governmental organizations to provincial capitals and the
immediate surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
"Yet it is heartening to note that, despite all the
difficulties facing Angolans at this time, important work is still
being carried out by our partners," said Bellamy. "Particularly
notable are the National Immunization Days, which are going ahead
as planned."
</P>
<P>
Nearly three million Angolan children under five years old need
to be given the polio vaccine free of charge during this campaign.
Already, in the first phase of the campaign at the end of August,
550,000 children had received polio vaccine drops, the UNICEF said.
</P>
<P>
"Health workers make long, arduous and sometimes hazardous
trips to vaccine children throughout this vast country," Bellamy
said. "Banditry and landmines pose additional threats to health
workers in the territories and regions where much of the work has
to be done."
</P>
<P>
The campaign, supported by the World Health Organization
(WHO), UNICEF and non-governmental organizations, has benefited
from comprehensive media coverage and the efforts of nearly 4,000
Angolan health workers who are participating throughout the
country, the UNICEF report said.
</P>
<P>
"So much more still needs to be done," the UNICEF chief said,
adding that "Despite Angola's abundant natural wealth in natural
resources, years of war have left most of the country's estimated
12 million people in absolute poverty and their children fighting
for survival."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-15 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nile Water Level Reaches Record High in Egypt's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Nile water level in Lake
Nasser, the man-made lake behind the Aswan dam in Egypt, rose to a
record of 179.43 meters Tuesday, the Middle East News Agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
The volume of water stored in Lake Nasser stood at 146.23
billion cubic meters on Tuesday, an increase of 610 million cubic
meters compared to that on Monday.
</P>
<P>
A total of 240 million cubic meters of water were being
discharged from the Lake Tuesday to meet the needs of irrigation,
power generation, drinking water, industry, navigation and other
purposes.
</P>
<P>
The excess water is being diverted to the Toshka canal, which
irrigates a swath of desert to the northwest of the dam.
</P>
<P>
This is the second time since the dam's construction in 1971
that the Nile water has been diverted to the Toshka canal. The
first time was in 1996, when the water behind the dam reached the
then record level of 178 meters.
</P>
<P>
The current diversion began early this month when the water
exceeded the dam's safety level. The lake, which reaches 500
kilometers up the Nile, is considered full at a depth of 175
meters.
</P>
<P>
Egypt used to suffer periodic flooding from the Nile river
until the high dam's construction.
</P>
<P>
The average annual flow of the Nile is 84 billion cubic meters,
with 80 percent of the volume passing during the flood season of
August through October.
</P>
<P>
Unprecedented flood levels in Sudan have already destroyed
hundreds of homes while some southern parts of the Upper Egyptian
governorate of Aswan have been inundated.
</P>
<P>
The 1,670-kilometer Nile is Africa's longest river, running
south-north through several countries before pouring into the
Mediterranean. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
