<HEADLINE> WIPO to Cut Patent Registration Fees by 10 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The World Intellectual
Property Organization (WIPO) will cut patent registration fees by
10 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Geneva-based WIPO said that the reduction in fees to
register international patents, the second in a year, was approved
by 171 members at its annual meeting which ended on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Revenues in 1997 from 54,000 international patent applications
brought in 100 million Swiss francs (about 74 million U.S.
dollars). The number of applications rose 27 percent in the first
half of 1998, partly thanks to an earlier cut of 15 percent in
fees last January.
</P>
<P>
WIPO spokesman Laurent Manderieux said the latest cut would
bring the fee for an average international patent application down
to between 1,650 and 2,650 Swiss francs from 2,000-3,000.
</P>
<P>
WIPO also agreed to lower fees for registering industrial
designs by 20 percent, Manderieux added.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations agency has also decided to build a new
headquarters costing over 55 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
WIPO, the richest UN agency, has larger financial autonomy than
other U.N. agencies because more than 85 percent of its revenues
come from companies and not from governments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
