<HEADLINE> Arafat Arrives in Egypt for Arab Ministers' Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat arrived in the northern coastal city of
Alexandria Tuesday evening on a two-day visit to Egypt to attend
the Arab League (AL) Foreign Ministers' meeting.
</P>
<P>
He will update Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak in Alexandria
on the results of current peace-saving efforts and his three round
of talks in a week with U.S. Mideast Peace Coordinator Dennis Ross.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is also scheduled to deliver a speech at the opening
session of AL Foreign Ministerial Council's 110th meeting in Cairo
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In his address, the Palestinian leader will call on the Arab
countries to hold an emergency Arab summit to rescue the faltering
Mideast peace process and challenge Israel's intransigence.
</P>
<P>
His address will also tackle the outcome of Ross' mission to
the region, the reasons behind the current deadlock, the explosive
situation in occupied territories like Jerusalem and Hebron, and
difficult economic conditions in Palestinian areas due to the
siege imposed by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Ross arrived in the region last week on a new mission to narrow
the gap between the Palestinian and Israeli sides on an American
plan on Israeli redeployment.
</P>
<P>
But there is no breakthrough after his rounds of shuttling
between Arafat and Israeli prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. The
negotiations between both sides have been languishing for 18
months.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has accepted the U.S. proposal on a 13 percent Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank in return for harsher crackdown on
Palestinian militants. But he rejected Netanyahu's conditions that
PNA have only limited control over 3 percent of the land, which
will be turned into "nature reserves."
</P>
<P>
Egypt backs the U.S. initiative but warns Arafat against
striking a "bad" deal that would compromise Palestinians'
interests and can not be implemented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
