<HEADLINE> EU Satisfied at Bosnian Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The European Union expressed
on Tuesday satisfaction at the peaceful and orderly course of the
general elections held in Bosnia-Herzegovina last weekend.
</P>
<P>
The union described the elections being held in a positive
climate as an important step in the implementation of the Dayton
peace accord and on the way toward enhanced stability, normality
and reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
The satisfaction was declared by Austria that is holding the
rotating presidency of the 15-nation union.
</P>
<P>
The EU said in a written statement that the high voter turnout
proved the growing democratic maturity in the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
The union also expressed gratitude to the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE) for its professional
preparation and organization of the elections held on September 12
and 13 under difficult circumstances.
</P>
<P>
The EU hoped that the election results would soon become
available.
</P>
<P>
OSCE Ambassador Robert Barry, however, said on Tuesday that the
international body supervising the general elections in Bosnia
postponed release of results in that OSCE did not want to publish
incomplete figures.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador added that any partial result would hamper
political dialogue in the country and that of claims by various
Bosnian parties that they won the elections, nobody has yet basis
for claiming victory.  
</P>
</TEXT>
