<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Announces 61,270 Reported AIDS Cases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Ethiopian Health
Ministry announced Tuesday that there are 61,270 reported cases
of AIDS in the country until last June.
</P>
<P>
The Ethiopian News Agency quoted a statement issued by the
ministry as saying that however, the number of AIDS patients
across the country is estimated at over 400,000, making Ethiopia
one of the highly-affected countries in eastern and southern
Africa.
</P>
<P>
According to the statement, there are also an estimated 2.5
million HIV virus carriers in Ethiopia which has a population of
58 million.
</P>
<P>
An HIV/AIDS policy was approved by the Council of Ministers of
Ethiopia on August 14, 1998 in order to curb the spread of the
killing disease at an alarming rate in the country.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the policy aims at coordinating efforts of
various sections of the society including donors and at
generating funds necessary for the fight against the AIDS
pandemic.
</P>
<P>
It said that creating situations conducive to preventing and
controlling HIV/AIDS, giving appropriate care to children who
lost their families as a result of AIDS and providing care and
counseling services to AIDS sufferers are some of the major
objectives of the policy.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to a recent press report, since the AIDS
disease was first spotted in Ethiopia in 1984, about 150,000
children have contracted HIV by the end of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Adults between the ages of 20 and 49 years are responsible for
about 90 percent of the reported AIDS cases. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
