<HEADLINE> Lesotho Soldiers Aid Oppositions: Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho opposition
party supporters, who took to the street in capital Maseru and
seized government vehicles Tuesday morning, were being aided by
army soldiers, police said.
</P>
<P>
The South African Press Association (SAPA) quoted Lesotho
Police Commissioner Bolutu Makoaba as saying that his officers
were too scared to arrest protesters because the soldiers were
assisting them.
</P>
<P>
Makoaba said that he was unable to take up the matter with the
defense force because its chief was last week forced to step down
by mutinous officers.
</P>
<P>
He was referring to Lieutenant-General Makhula Mosakheng, who
was forced to resign at gun point on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
Mosakheng's successor, Lieutenant-General Anthony Thibedi,
also appeared not to be in control of the army, Makoaba said.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner also confirmed that government vehicles were
being seized by protesting youths.
</P>
<P>
There were no reports of injuries to civil servants or damage
to property, but a security guard outside a local business was
injured, he said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, there was a report saying that Lesotho
army dispersed groups of youths from opposition parties, who
attacked civil servants, and that the situation in the capital
was under military control.
</P>
<P>
Army trucks were patroling the streets of the capital and
groups of police officers were stationed at the strategic points
along the main streets, SAPA quoted witnesses as reporting.
</P>
