<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Resumes Credit Talks With World Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria has resumed talks with
the World Bank (WB) on renewing credit facilities frozen by the
bank, the official News Agency of Nigeria said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The talks started Monday in Nigerian capital Abuja between
Finance Minister Mallam Ismaila and visiting WB Vice President
for Africa, Jean-Louis Sarbid.
</P>
<P>
"We are ready to access whatever facilities that would assist
us, especially when our foreign currency earnings are falling as
a result of dwindling oil prices," said the Nigerian minister.
</P>
<P>
He added that the present Nigerian administration led by
General Abdulsalam Abubakar is trying to revitalize the economy
by attracting foreign investors.
</P>
<P>
In his response, Sarbid said he would use his brief stay in
the west African country to discuss ways in which the bank could
be of assistance to Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He said he would also use the opportunity to find out ways of
making Nigeria attractive to foreign investors, where fuel queues
would vanish and where school pupils studying on bare floor would
find desks and chairs to sit on.
</P>
<P>
Sarid said that the talks, which would continue at the bank's
headquarters in New York next week, would center on how to
achieve a realistic price for petroleum products, stressing that
in all development efforts sound economic management is
essential. 
</P>
</TEXT>
