<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Approves Toughening Methamphetamine Trafficking </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Penalties for trafficking
in methamphetamines would increase to equal those for crack
cocaine under a bill the U.S. House of Representatives passed by
voice vote on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The measure would increase penalties for manufacturing,
trafficking, importing or possessing methamphetamines by cutting
in half the amount of the drug required to trigger a mandatory
minimum sentence. The Senate has not yet voted on a similar bill.
</P>
<P>
It would require a mandatory minimum 10-year sentence for 50
grams of speed and a five-year minimum for five grams.
</P>
<P>
Under current law, 100 grams of methamphetamine drugs trigger
a 10-year minimum sentence, and 10 grams trigger a five-year
minimum.
</P>
<P>
Part of the current law that would not change let judges impose
a life sentence on an offender with a previous felony drug
conviction or when use of the drug leads to the death or serious
bodily injury of another.
</P>
<P>
Methamphetamine abuse is a "national problem," said
Representative Bill McCollum, a Republican," Methamphetamine
deaths around the country have skyrocketed."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
