<HEADLINE> Kinkel, Dini Call for New International Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 15 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus
Kinkel and his Italian counterpart Lamberto Dini Tuesday proposed
that a new international police peace mission be established in
Albania given the renewed unrest in the country.
</P>
<P>
In a joint letter to Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schuessel of
Austria, who now holds the rotating presidency of the European
Union, Kinkel and Dini also called on the EU to strengthen its
efforts to help stabilize the situation in the Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
Albania's efforts to achieve political and economic
stabilization had been increasingly threatened given the overall
unstable situation in the Balkan region and especially the Kosovo
crisis, the two ministers said in the letter publicized Tuesday in
Bonn.
</P>
<P>
"It had become increasingly important for the world community
and especially the EU to strengthen their efforts to contribute to
a democratic consolidation of the institutions in the country and
a stabilization of the overall situation," they said.
</P>
<P>
A development like the one in Spring last year, which sank
Albania in anarchy and chaos, should be allowed to be repeated,
the two ministers stressed.
</P>
<P>
According to Kinkel and Dini, a new international police
mission in Albania could help the local authorities in restoring
order and controlling arms smuggling to Kosovo as well as illegal
immigrations.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers also called on the EU to seek further
measures to help Tirana to promote economic development, to combat
corruption and to overcome difficulties concerning inflows of
Kosovo refugees.  
</P>
