<HEADLINE> Flood Claims One Life in Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A 45-year-old woman became
on Tuesday the first victim of the Belgian flood that affected
four of the country's nine provinces.
</P>
<P>
The woman was drowned to death after the car she was driving
swerved off road and submerged in a deep ditch at
Heist-op-den-Berg in northern Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Military servicemen and flood rescuers were called in to help
evacuate people from communities immediately menaced by the rising
waters that overflew river embankments in northeastern Belgium.
</P>
<P>
Though torrential rains stopped on Tuesday and the water
stopped to rise in the rivers in the eastern province of Liege,
the situation still remained critical in the northeastern
provinces of Brahant and Limbourg.
</P>
<P>
The water in rivers Ambleve, Vesdre, Hoegne and Demer as well
as the Meuse, fed by huge quantities of rain water, rose to
alarming levels by surpassing the 1993 and 1995 flood levels.
</P>
<P>
Third-degree warnings are given in case of catastrophe by
Belgium's provincial authorities that are thus entitled to demand
military and special assistance.
</P>
<P>
The flood-stricken communities were each given up to 20 million
Belgian francs (600,000 U.S. dollars) to cover emergency relief
cost such as food and drinking water while provincial authorities
are expected to grant special funds to repair damaged
infrastructures in the provinces.
</P>
<P>
Continuous rains, that started late last month and kept on and
off for most of the past fortnight, were attributed to the
unusually warmer waters in the nearby North Sea.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
