<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Okays Extension of MONUA Mandate </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council on Tuesday voted 15-0 to adopt a resolution in its
decision to extend the mandate of the United Nations Observer
Mission in Angola (MONUA) until October 15 this year.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council decided to assess the overall situation
and take action on the future role of the United Nations in Angola
on the basis of a report and recommendations to be submitted by
the U.N. Secretary-General no later than October 8.
</P>
<P>
The resolution endorsed the decision of the Secretary-General
to instruct MONUA to adjust its deployment on the ground to
ensure safety and security of the MONUA personnel.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the resolution demanded that UNITA comply
immediately and without conditions with its obligations, in
particular the complete demilitarization of its forces and full
cooperation in the immediate and unconditional extension of State
administration throughout the national territory.
</P>
<P>
The resolution also called upon UNITA to withdraw immediately
from territories which it has occupied through military action
while reiterating its full support for the implementation of the
Lusaka Protocol.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member Security Council held UNITA responsible for the
current stalemate in the peace process, saying that "the primary
cause of the crisis in Angola and of the current impasse in the
peace process is the failure by the leadership of UNITA under
Lusaka Protocol."
</P>
<P>
The resolution "strongly urges the Government of Angola,
UNITA and States in the region to reject military action, to
pursue dialogue to resolve the crisis and to refrain from any
steps which could exacerbate the current situation."
</P>
<P>
The international community has said UNITA is blocking peace
process in Angola and leaders from 14 southern African countries
branded the UNITA leader, Jonas Savimbi, a war criminal.
</P>
<P>
The Angolan Government, headed by President Jose Eduardo Dos
Santos, accused rebel UNITA of its failure to come in terms with
the Lusaka Protocol.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan, the Angolan
president said on Monday that his government would no longer deal
with the former rebel leader of UNITA, Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Savimbi has again launched a military campaign all over
the national territory and has hardened his positions against
the Angolan Government, the Troika of Observers and the United
Nations themselves," he wrote in the letter, referring to an
observation group of representatives of the United States,
Russia and Portugal, the former colonial power.
</P>
<P>
After more than 20 years of civil war that left every industry
destroyed and millions dead, Angola has been hovering someplace
between peace and war for more than three years.
</P>
<P>
Angola won its independence from Portugal in 1975 and
immediately plunged into a civil war. A truce was achieved in
1992, and elections were held, UNITA leader Savimbi returned to
war. In 1994, facing likely defeat, he agreed to the Lusaka
Protocol.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
