community of Tanzanians working there," Mkapa said, adding that
Tanzania also has a lot of people from Swaziland who are doing
business or studying at colleges.
</P>
<P>
The exchanges have been spontaneously conducted, Mkapa said,
noting that people of the two nations have walked ahead of their
governments in promoting bilateral cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said it is high time that the two governments expanded
and formalized cooperation in other key sectors such as tourism,
agriculture and industry.
</P>
<P>
On the situation of the Great Lakes Region, Mkapa said member
countries view with great concern the escalation of conflicts
especially in the Democratic Republic of Congo (DRC) and Burundi.
</P>
<P>
He said the continued civil war in Congo (K), where rebels
have been fighting against government troops loyal to President
Laurent Kabila since August 2, poses a great threat to the peace
and stability of all surrounding countries and hinders their
development.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa reaffirmed that Tanzania advoes peaceful
resolution of the crisis in Congo. "Peace is an indispensable
condition for the socio-economic development of any society," he
said. "Africa desperately needs peace, security and stability."
</P>
<P>
"Africa must rise from the morass of poverty, underdevelopment
and conflict," he said, pointing out conflicts will undermine the
conducive environment for investment, industrial production and
sustained economic development in the continent. 
</P>
