<HEADLINE> Clinton Defense Team Expanded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton has chosen Gregory Craig, a ranking State Department
official, to join the team of White House officials handling
independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report on the Monica Lewinsky
matter, the White House said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"Mr. Craig will quarterback the response to the (Starr)
referral," White House spokesman Mike McCurry told reporters,
adding that Craig would hold the title of assistant to the
president and special counsel at the White House.
</P>
<P>
Craig is a former law partner of Clinton's private lawyer David
Kendall and also served on the staff of Senator Edward Kennedy, a
top Democrat who is a strong supporter of the president. Craig
will come to the White House from the State Department, where he
served as director of policy and planning.
</P>
<P>
He will join White House deputy chief of staff John Podesta,
White House counsel Charles Ruff and Kendall in representing
Clinton before the House of Representatives Judiciary Committee,
which is weighing the 445-page report that Starr sent Congress
last week, McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
McCurry said Craig will report directly to the president.
</P>
<P>
The White House has been seeking to strengthen Clinton's legal
and political team following the release of the Starr report,
which alleges that Clinton may have committed 11 impeachable
offenses related to his affair with Lewinsky and efforts to cover
it up. Clinton's lawyers have denied that the president did
anything that warrants impeachment. 
</P>
