<HEADLINE> European Stock Markets Slip with Renewed Fears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Most European shares slipped
on Tuesday, as fears about Asia, Russia and the weak dollar
resurfaced, but a steady start on Wall Street helped European
shares recover in late afternoon trading.
</P>
<P>
The London market was under pressure for much of the day, but
shares recovered late in the session, tracking Wall Street's move
out of the red.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE 100 finished the day 13 higher at 5282. The index was
75 points in the red mid-afternoon but recovered to close just
short of the 5283 session high.
</P>
<P>
A steady showing on Far Eastern equity markets, offered hope,
although stocks drew little comfort from some soothing inflation
data, which undermined sterling as economists said UK interest
rates were likely to move lower sooner.
</P>
<P>
"Although there are some positive factors floating around,
there just seem to be too many negatives," one trader was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The market had gotten ahead of itself expecting G-7 interest
rate cuts soon, and rates should have been cut some time ago if
they were to have had any effect, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
In Frankfurt, the Xetra Dax closed down 41.95 at 4,851.56 in
quiet trading.
</P>
<P>
"Without a sustained breakthrough of a resistance level of
5,000 points, the DAX remains delicate," one German equities
analyst said.
</P>
<P>
In Paris, French shares also drifted lower, with the Cac 40
index closing down 16.8 points at 3698.
</P>
<P>
Dealers in Paris said investors are staying on the sidelines
ahead of Federal Reserve Alan Greenspan's speech on Wednesday.
</P>
