Testifying before the House International Relations Committee,
Martin Indyk, assistant secretary of state for Near Eastern
affairs, said the U.N. Security Council must first decide on how
to respond to Iraq's decision to freeze its cooperation on weapons
inspection.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi government's actions have put the U.S. administration
"back on the ladder of potentially escalating confrontation with
Iraq," said Indyk.
</P>
<P>
"So be it. We will not accept the indefinite blockage by Iraq"
of U.N. weapons inspections, he stressed. "Force remains an
option...It has not been taken off the table."
</P>
<P>
The U.S. had a "considerably stronger strike capability" in the
region than we did at the time of the last confrontation with
Baghdad," he noted, adding, "We can augment that force rapidly
should we need to do so."
</P>
<P>
Indyk said the United States will decide when and how to
respond to Iraq's actions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
