<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African, Botswanan Officials Meet Over Lesotho </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- South African Defense
Minister Joe Modise Tuesday briefed Botswana's Deputy President
Ian Khama in Gaborone about the political situation in Lesotho,
South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
The Gaborone briefing had taken place "within the context of
recent Southern African Development Community's efforts to
restore peace, democracy, stability and rule of the law in
Lesotho, South African Deputy President Thabo Mbeki's spokesman
Ronnie Mamoepa was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Modise had two rounds of talks with Lesotho cabinet ministers
and representatives of the army in the country since Sunday.
</P>
<P>
While the Tuesday meeting was held in Botswana's capital,
Lesotho opposition party supporters had been gathering in Maseru,
the capital of the land-locked kingdom in protest against delays
in releasing a tri-national report on alleged electoral fraud in
Lesotho.
</P>
<P>
A joint investigation team formed by officials from South
Africa, Botswana and Zimbabwe have been probing into the alleged
rigging of results of Lesoth's general elections in May.
</P>
<P>
A report by the team reportedly completed last week. However,
informed sources said, Mbeki decided to withhold it until it had
been seen by the presidents of South Africa, Botswana and
Zimbabwe, who form a troika protecting Lesotho's democracy.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the meeting between Modise and Khama, there was
still no official word on when the report would be released to
the Lesotho people.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe's defense minister, who earlier indicated he would
attend the meeting in Gaborone, failed to arrive and the briefing
went ahead without him.
</P>
<P>
Mamoepa refused to give details of the talks with Khama, who
is also Botswana's defense minister, saying that the meeting had
noted the troika presidents' commitment to "deliver the report as
soon as possible".
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the situation in Maseru, where opposition youths
forced civil servants out of government cars and seized the
vehicles Tuesday morning, Mamoepa said: "the meeting expressed
its gravest concern about the degeneration of the situation into
lawless and disorder."
</P>
<P>
"In this regard it resolved to call on all leaders in Lesotho
to stablize the situation," he said.
</P>
<P>
Sources reaching here said that Lesotho's protesters seized up
to 50 government vehicles and impounded them at the Palace of
King Letsie III in Maseru.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday's unrest follows a mutiny last week in which junior
army officers arrested more than 20 senior officers and forced
army chief lieutenan-General Makhule Mosakheng to resign.
</P>
</TEXT>
