<HEADLINE> Latin American Nations Delay Arms Purchases Amid Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Latin American nations
face growing pressure to delay arms purchases as Asia's economic
woes spread to the region, according to the latest edition of a
U.S. weekly magazine.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela, the hardest hit Latin American country by the
crisis, has delayed purchasing two F-16 fighter planes and may
scale back purchases of training aircraft, The Defense News
reported.
</P>
<P>
The outlook in Venezuela is very uncertain. "The country is
facing serious economic problems generated by a drop in the value
of its oil exports and pressure on a currency that many economists
argue is overvalued," the magazine said.
</P>
<P>
Chile's defense spending, which depends in part on the
performance of its copper industry, which in turn relies on sales
to Asian nations, has delayed the purchase of new fighter aircraft
until at least next year.
</P>
<P>
The country's military relies heavily on a state-owned fund
that receives 10 percent of its revenue from copper exports. The
fund has yielded about 250 million U.S. dollars for the military
annually in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Chile's prospective purchase of an initial lot of 16 fighters
has been delayed into at least next year.
</P>
<P>
As lower commodity prices slow Latin American economies and
government spending reductions are needed to defend the value of
national currencies, the likelihood of defense cutbacks increases,
the report quoted U.S. and European defense officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Latin America represents a small but growing market for
defense equipment," said the report.
</P>
<P>
From 1994 to 1997, Latin American nations spent 5 billion U.S.
dollars on weapons, representing 6.9 percent of total arms
purchase agreements with developing nations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
