<HEADLINE> Annan Meets Envoys From Pakistan, S.Arabia, UAE </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan had met with U.N. representatives from Pakistan, Saudi
Arabia and the United Arab Emirates on Afghanistan, U.N. spokesman
Fred Eckhard said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general met the three representatives Monday and
he expressed his concern over the heightening tension along the
Iran-Afghanistan border and reports of mass killing following the
August 8 capture of Mazar-i-Sharif by the Taleban," Eckhard said.
</P>
<P>
"The secretary-general asked the representatives to use their
influence to persuade the Taleban to respect the rights of all
civilians regardless of their religious beliefs. They agreed to do
so," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The crisis between the two neighboring Islamic states began
when the military faction Taleban captured the city of
Mazar-i-Sharif and was accused of killing nine Iranian diplomats
during the takeover. The Taleban denied the allegation by saying
that unidentified soliders acting on their own killed the Iranian
diplomats. The crisis between the two states deepened at the
weekend with the Taleban's takeover of the city of Bamiyan, west
of the Afghan capital Kabul.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab Emirates are the
only three countries which recognize the Taleban government.
</P>
