<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Build Adequate Railway System: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian Minister of Transport Rear
Admiral Fbi Porbeni said Wednesday that his government has planned to
build "an efficient, adequate, safe and befitting railway system that
will serve the country in the next millennium".
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a delivering ceremony of new locomotives from China,
the minister said the government would build a railway network in
the country's new industrial and commercial centers.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, construction projects will soon
begin, which include Port Harcourt-Onne Port, Abuja-Minna,
Abuja-Kaduna and East-West railway lines.
</P>
<P>
For example, the Port Harcourt-Onne Port line is designed to
serve the ever-growing oil and its related industries in the
area, he said.
</P>
<P>
The China Civil Engineering Construction Corporation (CCECC)
Wednesday delivered five new locomotives and 15 coaches to the Nigerian
Railway Corporation (NRC), bringing the total number of locomotives
and rolling stock delivered to Nigeria so far to 493 including 35
locomotives, 118 coaches, 320 wagons and 20 rail cars.
</P>
<P>
The delivery of locomotives and rolling stock is a part of a
contract signed in 1995 between Nigerian and Chinese companies.
</P>
<P>
Under the contract, the Chinese side was responsible for
feasibility study and design of 4,200-km railway lines, 3,500-km
track rehabilitation, and supply of locomotives, coaches, wagons
and rail cars.
</P>
<P>
Chen Xiaoxing, Acting General Manager of CCECC Nigerian
Railway Rehabilitation Project Management Office, said at the
ceremony that up to now, the feasibility study and and design
work had already been finished with 83 percent of the track
rehabilitation work fulfilled. The whole project would be soon
completed, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
