<HEADLINE> Late Chinese President Remembered by Hometown People </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- People of the hometown of
late President Yang Shangkun, who died early this week, have
expressed deep love for him.
</P>
<P>
At the Shuangjiang Township of Tongnan County, southwest
China's Sichuan Province, where the late president was born,
continuous streams of people have visited the mourning hall to
offer their condolences to Yang, who died of illness in Beijing on
September 14 at the age of 92.
</P>
<P>
Yang left his hometown at 1920 at the age of 14, and only
returned for the first time in 1987 when he was over 80 years. He
re-visited his hometown in 1993 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
Every time Yang returned home, he showed great concern about
the livelihood of the local people.
</P>
<P>
"He asked me whether I was paid in IOUs and whether my family
had a washing machine," farmer Liu Fakun recalled of a meeting
with Yang in April, 1993 during Yang's second return trip to his
hometown.
</P>
<P>
Jin Zhenbao, headmaster of Shuangjiang Primary School, said
that each time Yang met with the village folks, he would ask the
teachers to sit at the front-row seats and inquire about education
there.
</P>
<P>
Xu Zuwen, magistrate of Tongnan County, recalled: During each
of his return trip home, he said repeatedly that the folks should
be freed of any trouble by doing anything special for him.
</P>
<P>
"Instead, he often asked me whether people's life had
improved," Xu said.
</P>
<P>
Sixty-year-old Liu Huaiqing had this to say: "When he left us
last year, he said he would return home again next year. But now
his last wish will not be realized."
</P>
<P>
"His gentle voice and kind face will always linger in our
hearts," Liu said with tears welling his eyes.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burtenshaw Admits 'Bung' Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Steve Burtenshaw has
apologized to a Football Association disciplinary hearing after
admitting receiving an illegal payment while he was at Arsenal.
</P>
<P>
The former Gunners chief scout accepted a 35,000 pounds
payment from Scandinavian agent Rune Hauge two months after John
Jensen moved to Highbury from Brondby in September 1992.
</P>
<P>
Burtenshaw, now chief scout at Queens Park Rangers, was
charged after the Inland Revenue were alerted to the large sum of
money deposited in an offshore account.
</P>
<P>
He will have an anxious wait until Friday to hear the FA
ruling after judgment was deferred.
</P>
<P>
FA spokesman Steve Double said: "It was clearly a conflict of
interests with his role with Arsenal.
</P>
<P>
"The unauthorised payment is outside FA rules. It was accepted
by the FA commission that the payment was not solicited and
counsel representing him said that other than this incident he
had an unblemished 50-year career in football.
</P>
<P>
"He added he was guilty of a misjudgment for which he is
deeply sorry."
</P>
<P>
The inquiry follows a four-year investigation by the FA which
culminated in Burtenshaw being charged in January this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
