<HEADLINE> Clinton, Czech President Meet at White House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton and Czech President Vaclav Havel met at the White House
Wednesday to discuss European security issues.
</P>
<P>
Welcoming Havel at a South Lawn ceremony by the White House,
Clinton praised the Czech president for his role in his country's
democratic process.
</P>
<P>
"It owes a very great deal, in our time, to the inspiration
provided by a single man, Vaclav Havel, who for years spoke when
it mattered and often at enormous personal cost," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Havel said his country looked forward to becoming a member of
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO), which is to
formally admit Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic as new
members next spring.
</P>
<P>
"There is no doubt in my mind that it was your personal
leadership that made this historic development possible," Havel
said to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
Havel said NATO membership was "one of the most important
guarantees of our democratic development".
</P>
<P>
Havel, 61, is on a five-day U.S. visit and is expected to meet
Vice President Al Gore, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and
other U.S. officials this week. 
