<HEADLINE> Sweden's Inflation Falls to Zero </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Swedish inflation fell by
0.5 percent in August, bringing the annual inflation rate to about
zero, down from nearly two percent at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The August decline, which was mainly caused by a dramatic cut
in tobacco tax, was the largest in a single month since November
1992.
</P>
<P>
The government cut the tobacco tax after widespread cigarette
smuggling, which started to lessen Sweden's tobacco tax
revenues. As a result of the tax cut, the price of cigarettes fell
by 16 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
