<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Gulf War Syndrome Beyond Gulf </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The "Gulf War syndrome"
are not only common among Gulf War veterans, they are also
frequently reported by soldiers who never went to the region,
according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
The syndrome, such as fatigue, moodiness, memory problems and
muscle pain, that many Gulf War veterans complain of are
not likely to be explained by toxic exposures, exotic infections
or other risk factors peculiar to the war, said a report by a
team of epidemiologists in Wednesday's Journal of the American
Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
The scientists from the Federal Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention in Atlanta, after a survey of four Air Force units in
1995, found that 45 percent of Gulf War veterans had chronic
physical complaints, but about 15 percent of soldiers who had
never been deployed to the Gulf had the same problems.
</P>
<P>
Many had suspected that the illness was sourced from the Gulf
War in which chemical weapons might have been exploded.
</P>
<P>
Soon after the Gulf War in 1991, many soldiers reported that
they were suffering tiredness, difficulty concentrating, muscle
and joint pain, as well as diarrhea, skin rashes and breathing
problems. About 100,000 people have signed up for medical exams
offered by the federal government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
