<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Introduce Electronic Service Delivery in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A senior Hong Kong official
said here Wednesday that in the next century the government may
provide its services to the community electronically through an
information infrastructure accessible throughout the city.
</P>
<P>
Kwong Ki-chi, secretary for information technology and
broadcasting of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR),
said that the government was now "actively planning for the
introduction of Electronic Service Delivery in the year 2000 to
keep Hong Kong in the forefront of Information Technology ( IT)
development and to exploit the full potential of IT."
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the Hong Kong International
Computer Conference '98, Kwong said, Electronic Service Delivery,
as the scheme is called, aims to provide government services to
the community electronically through an information infrastructure
accessible throughout the SAR.
</P>
<P>
"In the not too distant future, we will be able to transact
business with government on-line and on a seamless basis through
the use of information kiosks installed at convenient public
locations, personal computers at home or in the office, telephone
through interactive voice response system or interactive
television," Kwong said.
</P>
<P>
Public services will be available 24 hours a day and seven days
a week, he added. In short, the scheme will transform the way
public services are delivered, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Kwong anticipated that the scheme would serve as a catalyst to
pump-prime the development of electronic commerce in the private
sector.
</P>
<P>
The open and common information infrastructure adopted for the
scheme could also be readily used by the private sector for the
conduct of electronic transactions at a later stage.
</P>
<P>
A total of 44 local and international companies have expressed
their interest in the scheme, Kwong said. Some of them had solid
experience in implementing similar Electronic Service Delivery
projects elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
Kwong said, "Our plan is to call for tenders for operating the
Electronic Service Delivery Scheme by the end of the year, award
the contract in mid 1999 and launch the first phase of the scheme
within 2000.
</P>
<P>
"To support the implementation of the Electronic Service
Delivery Scheme and to facilitate the development of electronic
commerce in Hong Kong, we consider it necessary to have locally
established certification authorities to provide security and
trust in the conduct of electronic transactions under a public
key infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Kwong said the government was also looking into the need for a
legal framework to enhance certainty in the conduct of electronic
transactions. The objective was to create an environment to help
electronic transactions to take hold in Hong Kong. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Anti-Piracy Operation Nets 100,000 Pirated Discs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong customs officers
seized more than 100,000 suspected pirated optical discs, worth
about 1.9 million HK dollars (244,000 U.S. dollars), after raiding
a shopping arcade Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
At about 6 p.m., the officers raided 40 shops at a shopping
arcade at Kwai Chung, making the seizure and arresting 11 men.
</P>
<P>
Of the pirated optical discs, there were 12,000 VCDs of
Japanese TV drama series, which were very popular in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
"We have been achieving a significant result in checking the
sale of pirated Japanese TV dramas," said a spokesman for the
Customs and Excise Department.
</P>
<P>
The customs officers have seized more than 240,000 pirated
Japanese TV dramas in separate anti-piracy operations during the
past week, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Customs officers at all control points are maintaining
vigilance against smuggling of pirated compact discs, including
VCDs of the Japanese TV dramas, into Hong Kong, he added.
</P>
<P>
The department was also concerned over piracy activities via
e-mail or Internet. "The situation is now under close supervision
by Customs. We shall strengthen the collection of intelligence to
locate the source of the goods before taking further action," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The Customs would spare no efforts in combating piracy
activities and preserving the good image of Hong Kong, the
spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Warned Airport Traffic Plan Violates EU Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The European Commission said
Wednesday that Italy's air traffic distribution plan between the
two airports near Milan violates European Union (EU) law.
</P>
<P>
European Transport Commissioner Neil Kinnock said that the
commission, the executive arm of the 15-nation EU, agreed that
the redistribution of air traffic between Linate and Malpensa
airports went against EU laws on fair competition.
</P>
<P>
The decision was originally postponed for a week so the Italian
government could reconsider its decree on moving almost all other
European countries' airlines out of the convenient Linate airport
to newly-built Malpensa.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, days of unremitting efforts came to no avail,"
said Kinnock who had been involved in long negotiations with the
Italian authorities.
</P>
<P>
He added that the commission had been trying to persuade Italy
to make rapid and effective efforts to bring its distribution plan
into line with the requirements of fair competition laws
stipulated in the Treaty of Amsterdam for the single market.
</P>
<P>
The Italian government decided last November to redistribute
airline traffic between Milan's existing airport, Linate, and the
new airport, Malpensa, due to start operating on October 25.
</P>
<P>
The Italian authorities passed the decree that all carriers
with more than two million passengers each year would continue to
fly in and out of the easily-accessible Linate while other flights
would have to fly in and out of Malpensa, which is 53 kilometers
away from Milan and still lacks ground transport facilities.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, nine European carriers including British
Airways, Iberia, TAP, Sabena, Lufthansa, Air France, Olympic,
Austria Airlines and SAS complained to the European Commission
that the plan was discriminatory and disproportionate.
</P>
<P>
The carriers argued that passengers would continue to choose to
fly Italy's national carrier Alitalia out of Linate close by the
Milan town center because of insufficient road and rail links
between Milan and Malpensa.
</P>
<P>
Kinnock said that the European Council of Transport Ministers
was expected to uphold the commission's decision should Italy
stick to its decree.
</P>
<P>
The council, however, can overrule the commission's decision
with a qualified majority . Otherwise, the EU legal procedure
will start to deal with Italy's plan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Rules Out New Taxes, Assures Bread Subsidy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Finance Minister
Mohieddin el-Gharib said on Wednesday the government does not
intend to increase taxes in the foreseeable future, or cut back
bread subsidies.
</P>
<P>
"On the contrary, there are trends to reduce taxations on
individuals and organizations whenever possible," he told a
conference on market economies in the Arab states, organized by
Euromoney, an international financial foundation.
</P>
<P>
Gharib said "bread subsidies will also continue and there is
no intention to cancel them either."
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian government has been for years subsidizing sugar,
oil, bread and other basic necessities to cater to the nation's
huge poor population, who are estimated at one third of the whole
population.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian minister said the government is committed to
reducing customs tariffs on imports over stages to cut down local
market prices without putting local industries at risk.
</P>
<P>
The government is also determined to increase the contribution
of the private sector in the economy and improve the climate for
investment.
</P>
<P>
But he denied reports of a plan to privatize the customs
sector, saying that the government will have an agreement with a
foreign company before the end of the year to help improve custom
services, pinpoint origin of imports and improve standards of
specifications. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Professional Training School Opens In Suzhou </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SUZHOU, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Suzhou Industrial Park
Professional Training School was inaugurated Tuesday in this city
in eastern China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the school is to train quality workers for
foreign-funded enterprises both in and outside the Suzhou
Industrial Park, the largest Sino-Singaporean cooperative project.
</P>
<P>
The school has fully absorbed Singapore's advanced experience
in professional training, and is managed as an enterprise, which
is something new in China.
</P>
<P>
In May last year, when Singaporean Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong
visited the park, he suggested speeding up professional education
in the park. This call received prompt attention from the related
departments of Suzhou, Jiangsu and the central government.
</P>
<P>
The opening of the school is an important step to draw on the
experience of Singapore and a new attempt to restructure China's
educational system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
