<HEADLINE> Egypt Rules Out New Taxes, Assures Bread Subsidy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Finance Minister
Mohieddin el-Gharib said on Wednesday the government does not
intend to increase taxes in the foreseeable future, or cut back
bread subsidies.
</P>
<P>
"On the contrary, there are trends to reduce taxations on
individuals and organizations whenever possible," he told a
conference on market economies in the Arab states, organized by
Euromoney, an international financial foundation.
</P>
<P>
Gharib said "bread subsidies will also continue and there is
no intention to cancel them either."
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian government has been for years subsidizing sugar,
oil, bread and other basic necessities to cater to the nation's
huge poor population, who are estimated at one third of the whole
population.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian minister said the government is committed to
reducing customs tariffs on imports over stages to cut down local
market prices without putting local industries at risk.
</P>
<P>
The government is also determined to increase the contribution
of the private sector in the economy and improve the climate for
investment.
</P>
<P>
But he denied reports of a plan to privatize the customs
sector, saying that the government will have an agreement with a
foreign company before the end of the year to help improve custom
services, pinpoint origin of imports and improve standards of
specifications. 
