<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Provides Emergency Aid to Bangladesh Flood Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Canada announced Wednesday
that it will provide additional emergency relief aid to flood
victims in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian International Development Agency (CIDA) will give
wheat valued at 2.5 million Canadian dollars (1.68 million
U.S. dollars). It will be delivered for immediate distribution
through the public distribution system of Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
"Two-thirds of Bangladesh was flooded in the heaviest rains in
over a decade, drastically reducing the current harvest of rice
and adversely affecting the next crop," said International
Cooperation Minister Diane Marleau.
</P>
<P>
"Canadians are moved by the situation of the 30 million people
affected by the disaster which will leave future food stocks
extremely inadequate," she added.
</P>
<P>
In addition to food aid, CIDA will also provide 425,000
Canadian dollars (284,750 dollars) for the purchase and
distribution of essential medicines, water purification tablets
and oral rehydration salts to over 250,000 families in areas most
affected by the floods.
</P>
<P>
CIDA has already committed over 250,000 Canadian dollars
(166,250 dollars) for repairing houses and the rehabilitation of
agriculture and fish production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
