<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Chief: Israeli Policy Fuels Arab Resistance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Arab League (AL) Secretary
General Esmat Abdel Meguid Wednesday warned that Israel risks
stirring up Arab outrage by applying its lop-sided peace policy.
</P>
<P>
"Israel's attempt to impose its concept of peace on the Arab
nation could not ensure its security and stability, but would
rather feed the spirit of Arab resistance," he said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before the inaugural session of the 110th Arab League
Foreign Ministerial Council meetings here Wednesday, Abdel Meguid
said the kind of peace Arab countries want is the one
"consecrated" by the international community.
</P>
<P>
"It is peace based on implementing U.N. Security Council
resolutions 242, 338, 425, 252 and the land-for-peace
principle ... which means Israel's withdrawal from all occupied
Arab territories," he explained.
</P>
<P>
The AL chief appealed to the United State to exercise its role
as a genuine sponsor of the Mideast peace process, "out of
protecting its interests in the region on the one hand, and
giving credence to international legitimacy principles and
resolutions, on the other."
</P>
<P>
The Arab-Israeli negotiations have been stalled on all tracks
for nearly two years. U.S. mediation attempts to break the
Palestinian-Israeli peace impasse have been hamstrung by Israel's
rejection of a U.S. plan for West Bank redeployment.
</P>
<P>
Abdel Meguid urged Arab Americans to work to counteract the
pressure of Zionist lobby on the U.S. administration in support of
Israel.
</P>
<P>
"It is high time Arabs seek the support of some 3 million
Americans of Arab origin who have a say in the U.S. political
system in order to counter balance Zionist pressure groups," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The two-day meetings are attended by Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat, Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk
al-Shara and Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa, as well as
other foreign ministers and senior diplomats from the 22 AL member
states. 
</P>
</TEXT>
