<HEADLINE> Gov't, People Face Difficulties Together: Tung </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong government will
seek to stimulate the economy and spend prudently when formulating
policies at a time when the economy is slowing down, Chief
Executive Tung Chee Hwa said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting with chairmen of the Provisional Urban and
Regional Councils and the Provisional District Boards, Tung said
that the government will join hands with members of the public to
tide over this difficult period.
</P>
<P>
Tung said, Hong Kong's economic base is narrow and its economy
has undergone drastic changes as a result of the Asian financial
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
"To stimulate the economy, we will look into ways to expand our
economic base and the types of value added economic activities. It
is obvious that labor intensive industries are no longer our
advantage," he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that a preliminary report by the Chief Executive's
Commission on Innovation and Technology will be ready this month,
Tung hoped that there would be some indications on the direction
for industrial development.
</P>
<P>
Tung and the chairmen also exchanged views on issues such as
the review on district organizations as well as medical services.
</P>
<P>
Tung had talked with a number of political parties in groups in
the previous two days to seek their views on future policy
directions as his second Policy Address is due to be delivered
early October. 
</P>
