<HEADLINE> Bee-keeping Business Starts in Somali's Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The business of
bee-keeping is becoming popular and attractive to a growing
number of Somalis for the first time in Mogadishu, the country's
capital.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 families have now launched a campaign for
installing their new bee cages in Mogadishu in the past ten days
alone, said Ibrahim Farah Hussein, a bee-keeping expert.
</P>
<P>
According to a group led by Ali Shinnileh, a bee expert and a
campaigner for the bee-keeping business, hundreds of local
families are now installing their boxes. "In the next two months,
more than 1,000 families will be having their own honey producing
creatures," he said.
</P>
<P>
Even though the pure honey is very much sought and expensive
in Mogadishu for its good taste and its use as medicine, the bee
has been very much detested by the Somalis for its mal-behavior
when it gets mad and itches the people. Most of the Somali
families especially those in Mogadishu do not believe up to the
moment that the bee can be tamed and kept around the houses and
farms for yielding honey industry.
</P>
<P>
According to Shinnileh, his team goes along the streets every
morning in search for the bee families under the trees and roofs.
And whenever a bee family or families are found, the experts try
to persuade the owners of the area to start the habit of
bee-keeping.
</P>
<P>
"We also bring new families of the bee from the countryside to
those who wish and this is how our business and clients increase
by the day," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
