<HEADLINE> Moderate Newspaper Tous Banned Again in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Iranian moderate evening
newspaper Tous once again was banned from publication as of
Wednesday after Iran's supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei
lashed out at some print media for abusing freedom.
</P>
<P>
The conservative evening paper Kayhan reported on Wednesday
that a judicial official announced the ban order on Tuesday to
Tous' license holder and editorial director Mohammad Sadeq Javadi
Hesar.
</P>
<P>
Hesar was ordered to stop publication of Tous, which was named
after a famous ancient Iranian city, until further notice, Kayhan
said.
</P>
<P>
The judicial official said that the paper was banned for
publication of articles against national interests and security.
</P>
<P>
The ban came after Khamenei on Tuesday called on cultural and
judicial bodies to deal with "the group of the press which are
abusing the freedoms."
</P>
<P>
"I keep waiting to see what the responsible bodies will do"
with the group of the press which started targeting the people's
faith, he told a group of commanders of the Islamic Revolutionary
Guards Corps (IRGC).
</P>
<P>
Khamenei said that the Ministry of Culture and Islamic
Guidance, judicial and security bodies should identify those who
have targeted the people's faith and have desecrated the Islamic
revolution.
</P>
<P>
"I am making it clear for the officials that they should take
measures and find out which paper is going beyond the boundaries
of freedom," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tous appeared on newsstands only on July 25 to replace the
banned moderate daily Jameah (Society) and was welcomed by the
public, particularly the Iranian youth for its support for the
policies of President Mohammad Khatami.
</P>
<P>
It was banned for the first time on August 1 following strong
protest from the hard-liners and conservatives against its
pro-democracy articles.
</P>
<P>
But the ban was lifted one day after it was announced as
the Ministry of Culture and Islamic Guidance called on the
conservative judiciary to revoke the ban order. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
