<HEADLINE> Philippines Says Gov't Need Not to Buy Stocks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Philippine President Joseph
Estrada brushed aside here Wednesday calls for the government to
buy stocks to boost public confidence in the Philippine economy.
</P>
<P>
Estrada said there is no need to buy stocks as proposed by the
Philippine Stock Exchange as the stock market has been recovering
for the last three days.
</P>
<P>
"No, No. The government should not intervene in the exercise of
private business," the president said when asked about whether the
government will follow the proposal of the Philippine Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, Philippine Stock Exchange head Jose Yulo urged
the government to buy stocks to revive confidence in the domestic
economy.
</P>
<P>
He said the government's investment into the stock market need
not involve a high amount, and will merely serve as a token show
of the government's faith in the performance of Philippine
companies.
</P>
<P>
The composite index of the Philippine Stock Exchange fell to a
seven-year low of 1,082.18 points last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Since the very beginning of the Asian financial crisis, the
index has fallen by more than 50 percent. 
</P>
