<HEADLINE> Sixth Pyongyang Film Festival Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The sixth film festival for
non-aligned nations and other developing countries opened
Wednesday at Pyongyang International Cinema in the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea (DPRK).
</P>
<P>
Present at the opening ceremony were Yang Hyong Sop,
Vice-Chairman of the Presidium of the Supreme People's Assembly of
Korea, DPRK Minister of Culture Choe Jae Hwon and film workers
from some non-aligned nations and other developing countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the ceremony, Yang wished the festival a complete
success and pledged to work for the expansion of the friendly
cooperation between film workers.
</P>
<P>
More than 70 feature and documentary films from over 30
countries, international organizations and bodies are attending
the festival.
</P>
<P>
Film contests and exhibitions will be held during the festival,
which is scheduled to close on September 25.
</P>
<P>
The foundations for the Pyongyang Film Festival were laid in
September 1983 at the first ministerial meeting for non-aligned
nations and other developing countries in the DPRK capital.
</P>
<P>
The first festival of its kind was held in September 1987.
</P>
