<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Appoints More Vice-Prime Ministers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 26 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris
Yeltsin Wednesday named Vladimir Ryzhkov, Alexander Shokhin and
Vladimir Bulgak as Deputy Prime Ministers.
</P>
<P>
Ryzhkov had been First Deputy Chairman of the State Duma (lower
house of parliament) and a prominent member of Our Home Is Russia
(NDR) parliamentary group before the new appointment. Shokhin had
been NDR's leader in the Duma, and Bulgak, Acting Science Minister.
</P>
<P>
The Interfax news agency, quoting an NDR source, said Shokhin
would be in charge of financial matters and relations with
international financial institutions in the new cabinet headed by
Yevgeny Primakov. Ryzhkov will be responsible for social affairs
and Bulgak for industry and communications.
</P>
<P>
Ryzhkov, born in 1966, graduated from Altai State University
and taught there after his graduation. He joined NDR in 1995. He
was elected State Duma first deputy chairman representing NDR in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Shokhin was born in 1951. He can speak fluent English as a 1974
graduate from School of Economics of Moscow State University. He
was first appointed Deputy Prime Minister in charge of social
policy, and Labor Minister, in November 1991.
</P>
<P>
Shokhin was appointed Deputy Prime Minister in March 1994 in
the cabinet under Viktor Chernomyrdin. He left the government
eight months later.
</P>
<P>
He was elected Duma Deputy Chairman in January 1996 and became
NDR parliamentary group leader in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Bulgak was born in Moscow in 1941. He graduated from Moscow
Electrical Engineering Communication Institute in 1963 and the
National Economy Management Institute in 1973.
</P>
<P>
Bulgak served as Russia's Communications Minister from
November 1991 to March 1997.
</P>
<P>
He was appointed Deputy Prime Minister on March 17, 1997, a
position he had held until April 1998, when he became Science
Minister in the Sergei Kiriyenko cabinet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
