<HEADLINE> Typhoon No. 5 Sweeps Japan, Killing Two </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Two people were killed and 23
injured as a large typhoon, packing winds of up to 90 kilometers per
hour, swept central and northeastern Japan on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The typhoon, the season's fifth, first hit Japan's largest main
island Honshu near Omaezaki in Shizuoka Prefecture in central Japan at
around 4:30 a.m. (local time), and grew in size as it moved north, the
Meteorological Agency said.
</P>
<P>
The National Police Agency said two people in Chiba and Yamanashi
prefectures died and one person is missing.
</P>
<P>
The typhoon brought heavy rain between the southern Tohoku and
northern Tokai regions between midnight Tuesday and Wednesday morning,
with rainfall measuring about 100 millimeters per hour in Kiryu, Gunma
Prefecture, northeast of Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
Bullet train services on the Tokaido, Tohoku, Nagano and Yamagata
Shinkansen lines were halted or delayed due to rain and strong winds,
affecting some 150,000 travelers, railway officials said.
</P>
<P>
Japan Airlines, All Nippon Airways, Japan Air System and Air Nippon
canceled a total of 184 flights, affecting some 24,000 passengers, the
airlines said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
