<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel, Palestinians Draw Different conclusions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 16 (Xinhua) -- As U.S. Middle East peace
envoy Dennis Ross is winding up his mission in the region with no
imminent breakthrough in sight, Israel and the Palestinians are
drawing different conclusions over his mediating efforts.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported Wednesday that Palestinian National
Authority President Yasser Arafat has described Ross' visit as a
failure, saying it had not yielded any result.
</P>
<P>
The radio quoted Arafat as telling an Egyptian newspaper that
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu had attempted to
destroy the peace process by procrastinating and dodging issues
concerning the overdue Israeli withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Ross is on a short trip to Amman Wednesday to brief Jordanian
Crown Prince Hassan on his week-long efforts to bridge the gaps
between Israel and the Palestinians over the Israeli
redeployment. He has traveled to Egypt for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
Jordan and Egypt are playing important mediating roles in the
Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
In an intensive effort which began last Wednesday, Ross has
held rounds of talks with Arafat and Netanyahu, as well as other
officials from both sides, but he has reportedly failed to help
them resolve their disputes on a series of issues, even those
secondary matters such as the safe passage between Gaza and the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin indicated Tuesday
that Ross will likely return to Washington empty-handed at the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted Palestinian newspapers as accusing Ross of
his "Zionist" and "racist" positions in the mediation, saying he
had acted against the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In Israel, the Prime Minister's Office expressed its regret
over Palestinians' "anti-Semitism" attitudes. Netanyahu's media
adviser David Bar-Illan praised Ross as a "fair mediator," saying
he had considered the positions of both sides.
</P>
<P>
As Ross is expected to hold his last rounds of talks with
Netanyahu and Arafat after returning from Amman later Wednesday,
Netanyahu convened his inner cabinet Wednesday to discuss the
current Israeli-Palestinian negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The details of the session were not disclosed, but Israel
Radio said Netanyahu is not scheduled to meet either
U.S. President Bill Clinton or Arafat next week when he is in New
York to attend the U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Many have expected that Netanyahu and Arafat will hold a
summit, probably together with Clinton, during that time and
finalize an agreement over the second Israeli withdrawal from the
West Bank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0109 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Romania's Credit Risk Rating Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Romania's chances of
obtaining foreign loans decreased after international rating
agency Moody's decided to increase its credit risk rating,
according to reports here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Moody's announced earlier this week that it is downgrading the
rating of Romania's debt in hard currency from Ba3 to B1, and the
rating of bank deposits in hard currency from B1 to B2.
Consequently the rating of Eurobonds issued by the Romanian
government and the National Bank was lowered from Ba3 to B1.
</P>
<P>
Because of the downgradings, Romania's credit risk rating
increased. As a result, interest rates in Romania increased, which
lowered Romania's chances of obtaining foreign loans.
</P>
<P>
According to a statement from Moody's, Romania proved to be
slower in carrying out market reforms than other countries in
transition, which has affected its potential in economic growth in
the medium term.
</P>
<P>
The private sector only manufactures 12 percent of its
industrial output and 50 percent of exports, while the large
inefficient state-owned enterprises monopolizes most of the
economic production. That situation has lead to a poor micro- and
macro-economic situation and undermined the country's capacity for
acquiring hard currency.
</P>
<P>
Moody's estimated that in 1998 the deficit of Romania's current
account will range from 2.5 billion to 2.9 billion U.S. dollars
(six to seven percent of its gross domestic product), given that
foreign direct and portfolio investments will be considerably
smaller than those in previous years.
</P>
<P>
Considering that direct foreign investment was less than 500
million dollars in the first half of this year, and the net
portfolio investment was insignificant, Moody's said the only
financial resources left for Romania in 1999 were the
privatization of important companies with the participation of
foreign investors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
