<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Peacekeeper Wounded in South Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A United Nations peacekeeper
working in south Lebanon was wounded by Israeli shelling
Wednesday morning, the Orient radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The soldier, from Norwegian battalion within the U.N. Interim
Forces in Lebanon (UNIFIL), was wounded when Israeli shells fired
in the direction of a Norwegian patrol near the village of Blat
on the edge of the Israeli occupied south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The UNIFIL spokesman Timor Goksel said that they have
protested to the Israeli army and received an apology.
</P>
<P>
In Jerusalem, an Israeli army statement has confirmed the
attack, saying they would launch an investigation into the
incident.
</P>
<P>
Since UNIFIL troops were first established in 1978 after
Israeli first invasion of Lebanon, a total of 222 peacekeepers
have been killed in separate incidents or military conflicts
between Israeli forces and Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
The 4,500-strong U.N. forces, which were designed to help
restore Lebanese government's authority over southern part of
the country, comprises troops from Finland, France, Nepal,
Norway, Fiji, Ghana, Ireland, Italy and Poland.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a 1,200-square-kilometer self-declared security
zone in south Lebanon in 1985 to protect its north from
cross-border attacks by Lebanese guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
Since then, conflicts between Israeli forces and Lebanese
guerrillas have never stopped and U.N. troops frequently were
mistakenly attacked. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Long-Term Plan Needed to Tackle Flood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Residents here feel relieved at
last as flooding waters are receding in the capital city
remarkably, with more ground appearing above water and traffic
partially returning normal.
</P>
<P>
As of Tuesday, 17 flood-hit districts in Bangladesh had become
flood-free, and the overall situation in the remaining of the 52
affected districts were improving gradually, according to
officials of the Disaster Management and Relief Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"The situation remained static in no district...while water
continued to recede rapidly from upstream down to the southern
downstream," a ministry official said.
</P>
<P>
Nearly two-thirds of Dhaka and three-fourths of the country
were under water at a certain moment during the
over-two-month-long flood which started hitting the country in
early July, directly and indirectly affecting about half of the
country's 127 million people, with nearly 30 million of them being
hit seriously.
</P>
<P>
The prolonged flood has claimed 755 lives, damaged more than
1.39 million acres (562,950 hectares) of crops, 867,632 houses,
15,896 kilometers of roads, 4,343 kilometers of embankments, 6,095
bridges and culverts, and 1,669 educational institutions. And
nearly 200 people have died of water-borne diseases such as
diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary estimates show that the loss caused by the flood,
which experts described as "the biggest in a century," may be as
high as 3.4 billion U.S. dollars, about 10 percent of the
country's gross domestic products (GDP).
</P>
<P>
The heavy loss of both lives and properties might have been
avoided or at least reduced if the government had taken necessary
precautionary measures and there had been more flood control
facilities in the country, the experts said.
</P>
<P>
An effective flood-forecasting system should be set up capable
of telling whether there is any possibility of a flood and its
possible duration, instead of merely warning people of a flood
when it comes, and so the government could take precautionary
measures accordingly, they said.
</P>
<P>
If the government had been prompt in realizing the possible
long duration and severity of this year's flood, in which the
flood forecasting system could play a significant role, the losses
could have been minimized, according to the experts.
</P>
<P>
As a common phenomenon in Bangladesh, flood occurs in the
country almost every year due to the country's particular
geographical location and its climatic features.
</P>
<P>
The location of the major parts of the country at the lowermost
reaches of the three mighty river systems - the Ganges, the
Brahmaputra-Jamuna and the Meghna, and heavy monsoon rainfall
coinciding with flood waters from the upstreams of rivers and
surges in the Bay of Bengal, make floods an annual phenomenon in
Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
To reduce flood-caused losses, they said, the government should
make long-term plans to deal with possible flooding in the future
instead of merely distributing relief materials during and after
the flood.
</P>
<P>
The country's major flood facilities are the about 500
embankments along major rivers, dikes and a 250-meter-long barrage
in northeastern Bangladesh, according to Water Resources Minister
Abdur Razzaq.
</P>
<P>
But for the Dhaka Protection Embankment and the
Dhaka-Narayanganj-Demra Embankment, the country's capital city
would have been totally inundated this year.
</P>
<P>
These projects, which were mainly built after the 1987-88 flood
and are badly in need of renovation, are insufficient for
protecting the country from flood, the experts said. They
suggested the construction of upstream storage dams, more
embankments and reservoirs in plains for shallow storage, and
channel improvement by dredging rivers.
</P>
<P>
They also proposed measures such as flood preparedness and
community-based flood preparedness activities like evacuation,
sheltering, flood fighting, stock-piling of food and medical
supplies.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua recently, the water resources
minister blamed heavy rains, rising sea levels in the Bay of
Bengal, the effect of the La Nina weather phenomenon, the
reduction of flood plain because of unplanned construction of
roads, bridges, culverts and homesteads, and the rise of riverbeds
due to siltation for the prolonged flood this year.
</P>
<P>
It's a good thing that the government knows what has caused the
flood, but what is more important is that the government knows how
to avoid flood-related losses and take concrete measures to tackle
the issue of flood, the experts pointed out.
</P>
<P>
To this end, they said, the ruling and the opposition parties
should join hands to address the flood issue for the interest of
the people, instead of trying to gain benefit for their respective
parties only. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
