<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Minister of Tourism Mamdouh al-Beltagui
inaugurated Tuesday the Ras Sidr Tourist Promotion Conference to
promote tourism and foreign investment, the Middle East News
Agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Beltagui said at the opening ceremony that foreign tourists
visiting Egypt rose to 4 million in 1997 from 1 million in 1980,
with tourism proceeds climbing to 3.8 billion U.S. dollars from
300 million.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian banks have capitalized on the financial
crises in Asia and Russia, earning 1-3 million dollars on Asian
stock markets and 2 million in Russia.
</P>
<P>
The National Bank of Egypt, one of Egypt's four largest
state-owned banks, also bought 1.4 billion dollars worth of
securities in the London stock exchange and earned some 100
million dollars while the Commercial International Bank bought
some 25 million dollars worth of shares and made profits of about
5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian-German talks started Tuesday on the
establishment of four industrial joint ventures to produce alloys
and engines, aluminium components, spare parts of washing machines
and air-conditioning systems, the Middle East News Agency reported
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The projects are part of a series of cooperation agreements
signed during the first forum between Egyptian and German
businessmen in 1997.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Foreign investments flowing into the Middle East will
increase over the coming years, said Mohsen Khalil, director of
the Middle East and North Africa Department in the International
Finance Corporation.
</P>
<P>
Khalil said at the first session of the ongoing Euromoney
Conference that many countries of the region, including Egypt,
Morocco, Tunisia and Lebanon, have adopted serious measures
towards economic liberalization and encouraging the private
sector to play a bigger role in the economic development.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- Jordanian and German officials Tuesday reviewed a
number of projects in Jordan that Germany is to finance by the end
of 1999, Jordan's official PETRA news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The projects covered such fields as water supply,
transportation, agriculture, infrastructure and the development of
national data systems.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Lebanese revenues from property in August rose
about 22 percent to 17.876 million dollars as against the same
period last year, the Daily Star reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a report issued by the Finance Ministry as
saying taxes levied from property deals were 6.5 percent on an
average.
</P>
<P>
BEIRUT -- Kuwait will hold a made-in-Kuwait exhibition Thursday
in Lebanon, the first of its kind, with an aim to boost trade with
Lebanon, the Star daily reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 40 Kuwaiti companies will take part in the fair.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, Lebanese exports to Kuwait totaled 100 million
dollars while Kuwaiti only exported 3 million dollars worth of
commodities to Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
Lebanese industrial products enter Kuwait free of customs and
Kuwait is seeking a similar deal.

16/09/98 13:42 GMT

