<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Finishes Stronger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 16 (Xinhua) --The Australian dollar closed
stronger Wednesday, despite coming off a high of 59.75 U.S. cents
during local trading Wednesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Senior foreign exchange dealer at Colonial State Bank, Nick
Volanakis, said an improvement in commodities overnight helped the
local currency gain strength.
</P>
<P>
"Commodities were up quite a lot overnight, gold is the only
disappointment," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Australian dollar ended here at 59.61 U.S. cents from 59.49
at Tuesday's close.
</P>
<P>
Volanakis said the currency market would continue to be
influenced by U.S. politics, particularly the situation of its
beleaguered president.
</P>
<P>
"Bill Clinton opened up a can of worms on Friday night over the
possibility of stimulating the world economy," he said.
</P>
<P>
"A lot of people understood that the U.S. will lower interest
rates, if not, a few other countries will."
</P>
<P>
The address by U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
Thursday morning will be watched closely to see if the chairman
agrees with the comments made by Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"Greenspan is greatly respected and I think anything he says
will have a major impact on the market in the next 24 hours," he
said.
</P>
<P>
For the first time in 14 days the Australian dollar hit the 80
Japanese yen level, trading at 80.05 from 79.24 Tuesday. It was
also buying 1.0091 German marks from 1.0090. 
</P>
</TEXT>
