<HEADLINE> Australian Stocks End Lower in a Subdued Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 16 (Xinhua) --The Australian sharemarket
lost its momentum Wednesday, closing slightly lower because of
some profit taking and nervousness about overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
After two days of rises, the benchmark all ordinaries index
closed 1.1 points softer at 2,553.2, with a late rally in some of
the major bank stocks helping it climb back from an intra-day low
of 2,539.4.
</P>
<P>
"We've had a couple of days of good rises so I think the market
took a breather today and there was also a little bit of profit
taking and nervousness about volatility overseas," said Morgan
Stockbroking dealer Neil Gynther.
</P>
<P>
Client adviser Brett O'Donovan said the slow day on the local
bourse could signal the start of uncertainty ahead of the upcoming
federal election.
</P>
<P>
"People could be sitting on their hands for the next two and a
half weeks," he said.
</P>
<P>
On the Australian market, the all industrials index shed 2.2 to
4,483.9 and the all resources index retreated 0.2 points to 996.1.
</P>
<P>
The banking index stacked on 27.5 points to 5,496.5, with
Westpac picking up 16.4 cents, ANZ gaining eight and the
Commonwealth falling 8.3.
</P>
<P>
The National Australia Bank, which announced it would raise 400
million U.S. dollars through a preference share issue in the
United States, closed steady at 20.70 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
Elsewhere in the industrial sector, News Corp. shed 8.2 cents
to 10.70 Australian dollars, while its preferred scrip eased three
cents.
</P>
<P>
Telstra installment receipts firmed two cents, topping the
turnover table with 9.17 million receipts changing hands.
</P>
<P>
In the resources sector, Rio Tinto was one of the stand out
performers, stacking on 36 cents.
</P>
<P>
Among other diversified resource stocks, WMC, which announced
Tuesday it will close three of its high cost nickel mines at
Kambalda, dropped 13 to 4.80 Australian dollars.
</P>
<P>
The gold index fell 6.9 points to 1,008.8, the spot price of
gold bullion in Sydney was 289.25 U.S. dollars an ounce, a slight
drop from Tuesday's close of 289.55 an ounce.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary national turnover was 224.02 million shares traded
for 689.65 million Australian dollars (413.79 million U.S.
dollars), with falling stocks outnumbering rising stocks by 517 to
416 and 394 stocks steady. 
</P>
</TEXT>
