<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S.Korea to Repay 24 Billion Dollars Before Next July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SEOUL, September 16 (Xinhua) -- South Korea must repay 24
billion U.S. dollars of external debt between October and next
July, the Ministry of Finance and Economy said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The long-term debts, which will expire before next July, amount
to 18.7 billion dollars while five billion dollars in short-term
loans with interest must be paid back.
</P>
<P>
The ministry said South Korea, whose foreign exchange reserves
stand at about 42 billion dollars, would have enough foreign
currency boosted by current account surpluses and capital inflows
to repay the debts.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts expressed concern over the issue, saying the
country might be mired in another debt crisis next year.
</P>
<P>
They said the International Monetary Fund (IMF), faced with
mounting liquidity problems amid the global spread of financial
crises, will urge South Korea to repay its long-term public debt.
</P>
<P>
South Korea and the IMF have yet to negotiate the renewal of
debt maturities. South Korea borrowed 58 billion dollars in an IMF
rescue package last December after it was gripped by a financial
crisis triggered by corporate bankruptcies and bad loans.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, financial institutions might run into trouble in
persuading foreign banks to roll over seven billion dollars of
short-term debt if fresh turmoil engulfs the nation.
</P>
<P>
Given the fact that South Korea was forced to the brink of
declaring a debt moratorium last November in the wake of foreign
lenders' refusal to roll over debts, such possibilities could not
be ruled out, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Adding fuel to the fire is the prediction that the global
economic downturn will cause South Korea to reap a much smaller
current account surplus next year while the outlook for massive
capital inflows is not that bright, taking into account the fact
that Western capital still shows no signs of returning to emerging
capital markets.
</P>
<P>
Last week, the Samsung Economic Research Institute said South
Korea had to increase its usable foreign currency reserves to 78
billion dollars by September in 1999 to fight another possible
financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
