<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Forum on Capital Market Opens in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Finance Minister
Simeon Nyachae called for rising harmony of regional capital and
financial markets at the opening ceremony of a top-level
conference on world capital market here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"As (regional and global) integration proceeds, the need for
harmonization of fiscal and monetary policy becomes important,"
he said at the 23rd annual conference of the International
Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO).
</P>
<P>
"Globalization of the capital and financial markets makes it
imperative for every country to pay attention to the developments
in other parts of the world," said the minister.
</P>
<P>
He said tjat among the most challenging tasks of capital and
financial market regulators is to create financial harmony in the
emerging economic and monetary unions, especially at the regional
level.
</P>
<P>
"The transition from national to regional monetary and capital
authorities require a high degree of cooperation and
collaboration to harmonize money and capital markets within the
region," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The minister said that the global financial system has changed
rapidly in 1990s, ushering in new opportunities as well as
challenges in market development and regulation.
</P>
<P>
This will offer a new climate of hope for the emerging
economies of the world, which have enormous investment
opportunities but lack the financial resources to exploit such
opportunities, he added.
</P>
<P>
"To access external capital, it is necessary that our
financial systems must be transparent, efficient and well
managed," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
More than 600 regulators of capital markets from over 60
countries attended the four-day conference.
</P>
<P>
The IOSCO meeting, the first ever held in Africa, is focused
on the deliberations of the Principles of Securities Regulations,
a landmark document that sets out the objectives of securities
regulation.
</P>
<P>
Other topics to be covered will include cross-border
investment flows and the stability and development of markets,
international cooperation in the investigation and enforcement of
securities laws.
</P>
<P>
Delegates from the World Bank, the International Monetary Fund
and the U.N. Industrial Development Organization will also attend
the meeting.
</P>
<P>
IOSCO, set up 23 years ago, is a Montreal-based world body
composed of 134 member regulatory agencies. It meets annually to
discuss issues over world securities and futures markets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
