<HEADLINE> HK Youth Should Know More of Motherland, Says Foundation Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The youngsters of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (SAR) should take more visits
to China's mainland to know more of the Chinese history and
culture and become a new generation to serve the community, the
head of a local nongovernmental organization said here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Tours and visits to the mainland would help Hong Kong youth to
understand the present conditions of their motherland as well as
to learn about the origin, history, fine heritage and culture of
the Chinese people," said Annie Wu, Chairman of the Executive
Committee of the Chinese History and Culture Educational
Foundation for Youth, at a press conference here on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The youngsters would then develop a sense of identity with the
motherland, to grow into a new generation that loves China and
Hong Kong and is committed to building a better place to live and
serving the community, she said.
</P>
<P>
The foundation organized two cultural exchange and study tours
to Beijing and Xinjiang in July and August this year, which
involved hundreds of young Hong Kong students. Members of the
Foundation delegation met with Chinese President Jiang Zemin
during the Beijing visit, which Wu described as historically
significant for the organization.
</P>
<P>
It was announced at the press conference that Chinese pianist
Xiang-Dong Kong, who now lives in the United States, had been
invited to be the Foundation's Overseas Culture Ambassador, who
will hold a charity concert later this month in Los Angeles to
raise fund for the Foundation as well as China's flood children
victims so that they could go back to schools.
</P>
<P>
And famous Hong Kong-based female painter Yvonne Tang will
organize an exhibition for her latest paintings, with the
proceeded to be donated to the Foundation.
</P>
<P>
And as part of the future activities, the Foundation is now
organizing another study tour to Shanghai later this month, during
which Hong Kong students would celebrate the National Day with
their Shanghai counterparts.
</P>
<P>
The non-profit making Foundation was founded in February this
year, with SAR Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa as Honorary Patron
and Jiang Enzhu, director of the Xinhua News Agency (Hong Kong
Branch) as Honorary Advisor. The organization accepts donations
from overseas compatriots as well as organizations and individuals
from Hong Kong, Macao and Taiwan. Funds of the Foundation are
solely used for organizing History and Cultural Educational Groups
for Youth, Wu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
