<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Well-Placed to Provide Chinese Support for Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong, as a bilingual
city, is well-placed to provide Chinese language support for the
development of applications and content on the Internet, a senior
Hong Kong government official said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
There is a growing demand for content in Chinese on the
Internet in Asia in particular as the use of the Internet spreads
around the globe, said K C Kwong, secretary for information
technology and broadcasting of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the 9th Asian Information
Technology Exhibition (IT Expo '98), Kwong said that with the
ever- increasing number of users all over the world, the Internet
has become an important channel for communication, information
sharing, on-line government services and electronic business.
</P>
<P>
But communication on the Internet is still based largely on the
English language, he said.
</P>
<P>
This is only to be expected given the history of development of
the Internet, Kwong said. However, the scene is changing rapidly
as the use of the Internet becomes popular around the world, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Kwong pointed out that the HKSAR government fully recognizes
this and has taken measures to promote the use of Chinese.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Within the government, we have adopted a common
Chinese character set to facilitate data exchange between
government departments and the public."
</P>
<P>
"And, nearly all of our Web sites now support both Chinese and
English languages. Our current plan to deliver public services
electronically, through the Internet and other communication
channels, will also be enabled for communication in Chinese," he
added.
</P>
<P>
"We are also working closely with other governments and
institutions under the aegis of the International Standards
Organization in the development of the ISO 10646 standard, which
is an international coding standard aimed at encompassing
characters of Asian languages into one single common character
set," he continued.
</P>
<P>
Kwong noted that harmonization of internal codes for Chinese
characters is not enough. There are equally important issues that
demand immediate attention.
</P>
<P>
The first is the provision of more sophisticated and
user-friendly conversion tools capable of supporting the use of
traditional and simplified Chinese characters, Kwong said.
</P>
<P>
The second is the development of an efficient and effective
mechanism for searching and retrieving information in either
traditional or simplified Chinese characters on the Internet and
the most important is the provision of content in Chinese.
</P>
<P>
All this requires close collaboration between government, the
information technology and services industry and academia, Kwong
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Official on Taiwan Residents' Entry to HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A Hong Kong security
official said here Wednesday that the policy of requiring Taiwan
residents to apply for an entry permit before entering Hong Kong
has not changed after Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
The application procedures for Taiwan Visit Permit (TVP) have
remain the same, Regina Ip, secretary for Security, said in a
written reply to a Legislative Council member's question on
whether there are changes in the policies and procedures for
issuing entry visas to residents of Taiwan after Hong Kong's
return to China.
</P>
<P>
She said TVP applicants have to submit their applications to
the Immigration Department through the authorized offices of
altogether 21 airlines in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
Applications for renewal of TVPs may however be submitted to
the Immigration Department in person, through their authorized
persons in Hong Kong, or through the authorized airline offices in
Taiwan, she said.
</P>
<P>
On Taiwan's application for joining the World Trade
Organization (WTO), Ip said the government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) has long supported Chinese
Taipei's application for WTO membership.
</P>
<P>
She noted that the General Council of the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade (GATT) reached an understanding in 1992 that
China's accession to GATT should precede that of Chinese Taipei.
</P>
<P>
The SAR government has all along abided by this understanding,
she added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
