<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Charity Springs up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- China's reforms towards the
socialist market economy have triggered a fast growth of charity,
an official with the China Charity Federation (CCF) said here
today.
</P>
<P>
A recent report of the Ministry of Civil Affairs show that
there are 117 million senior citizens in China above the age of
60, nearly nine million of them living with no proper care.
</P>
<P>
There are also 200,000 orphans, and more than 50 million
disabled, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
"It's impossible for the Chinese government to take care of all
of them," the official said, adding that charity organizations
have much to do.
</P>
<P>
Founded in 1994, the CCF is the first of the kind in the
non-governmental sector to help people in need. It has so far had
79 member associations. China has now a total of 42,385 charity
organizations and welfare houses.
</P>
<P>
To date, the CCF has helped 2,000 children get rid of harelips
free of charge and drilled 15,000 wells for poor people living in
northwestern China's Gansu Province. It has also offered many
essential equipment to over 30 elderly welfare homes.
</P>
<P>
The CCF donated over 12 million yuan (about 1.4 million U.S.
dollars) to Zhangbei county in north China's Hebei Province, which
was hit by a disastrous earthquake early this year.
</P>
<P>
The CCF also donated nearly 500 million yuan (about 60 million
U.S. dollars) to the flood-stricken areas throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
The recent charity performance jointly held by the CCF and
China Central Television Station (CCTV) has collected over 600
million yuan (about 72 million U.S. dollars) for the flood victims.
</P>
<P>
This year's ravaging summer flooding killed 3,004 people,
displaced some 223 million people across the nation, and caused an
economic loss of 166.6 billion yuan (about 20.8 billion
U.S. dollars), according to a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
The CCF has also launched an auction website on the Internet
together with the Beijing Municipal Telegraph Bureau and Wisdom
Science and Technology Enterprise, raising money for a disaster
fighters fund. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0130 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> URGENT: Myanmar Government Calls for Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 16 (Xinhua)-- The Myanmar government
Wednesday urged all the political parties in the country including
the National League for Democracy (NLD) to cooperate in
establishing social and economic foundation for a stable
democracy, according to an official information sheet issued
here.
</P>
<P>
"The government views with grave concern the expressed
intention of the NLD to convene a People's Parliament before the
country has had time to complete a National Constitution which
will ensure political stability," it said, adding that without a
constitution, the Parliament would be unable to govern
effectively, but will lead to institutional confusion, social
chaos and genuine political crisis.
</P>
<P>
The government warned that "if political crisis leads to that
in national security, then Myanmar's very existence is in danger
of splitting into a number of Mini-states."
</P>
<P>
Concerning the detention of some NLD members recently, the
government has no wish to "house" them for any longer than
necessary, and will free them soon if the NLD leaders cooperate,
the information sheet said.
</P>
<P>
According to the NLD, the numbers of its members detained since
May 27 has gone up to 802, including 195 parliament
representatives elected in the 1990 election, and 607 other party
organizers.
</P>
<P>
Of them, 60 parliament representatives-elect and 302 party
organizers have so far been detained after the NLD declared its
intention to convene a parliament itself in September when the
party received no response from the government on the expiry of a
dead line set on August 21 for holding a parliament elected in the
election.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990 general election, participated by 93 political
parties, the NLD won 396 out of 485 parliamentary seats.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the NLD warned in a latest statement issued on
Wednesday that the present political, economic and social crisis
could not be settled if the government goes on preventing the
representatives-elect from convening a parliament by detaining
them.
</P>
<P>
The NLD also announced in the statement that it has formed a
10-member Representing Committee of the parliament
representatives-elect in the 1990 General Election with NLD
Chairman U Aung Shwe as Chairman. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
