<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0131 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Not to Sign CTBT in Present Form: Vajpayee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Prime Minister Atal Behari
Vajpayee said Wednesday that India is not prepared to sign the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) in its present form.
</P>
<P>
Briefing newsmen in Chennai, capital of Tamil Nadu in southern
India, he said that he understands that the treaty itself could
not be amended, yet the government is seeking a different
arrangement, especially with regard to transfer of high technology
and other aspects.
</P>
<P>
He said that India was negotiating with key nations on the CTBT
issue to create conditions for signing it.
</P>
<P>
Since June 11 this year, the United States and India have held
four rounds of talks on the CTBT and other concerned issues.
Further talks between the two sides are expected to be held later
this month in New York when Vajpayee goes there next week to
address the United Nations General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The successive nuclear tests by India and Pakistan in May this
year have caused great concern across the world as they have
aggravated the tense situation in South Asia, especially between
India and Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
The international community has time and again called upon the
two nations to stop their nuclear development programs and start a
peaceful dialogue to solve their disputes. The United States and
other western countries have imposed economic sanctions against
both the countries and urged them to sign the CTBT.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee said that there is no necessity for further nuclear
tests, as the required data have already been collected and
nothing more is needed. That is why India's attitude has changed
and India has declared a self moratorium, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
