<HEADLINE> Tanzania Seeks More Kuwaiti Investments </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Vice President
Omari Ali Juma Wednesday called on Kuwait to increase investment in
Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
Juma, who is on a three-day official visit here, made the call
at a press conference held at the Kuwaiti Bayan Palace.
</P>
<P>
He said Tanzania is abundant in natural resources, but
"unfortunately we have no capital and know-how to develop those
resources."
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, Juma said, Tanzania is indeed an ideal
investment area in view of its peaceful and stable political
situation, and geographic advantages.
</P>
<P>
Tanzania's long borderlines have made convenient land
transportation with its neighboring countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait, which has financed 10 projects in Tanzania so far with
an investment of 155 million U.S. dollars, have increased its
investments in Tanzania in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Juma reiterated his country's support for Kuwait's
sovereignty and territorial integrity, calling on Iraq, which had
a short-lived occupation of Kuwait in 1990, to abide by all
relevant U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Juma also stressed the need to extend and
consolidate a comprehensive bilateral relationship, saying "we
have proposed that we should give our friendship a new approach."
</P>
<P>
Ties between Tanzania and Kuwait have warmed up since 1992 with
the increase of visit exchanges by senior officials between the
two countries. 
