<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The Egyptian Ministry of Planning predicted that the
unemployment rate in 1998 will fall to 7.9 percent from 8.3
percent last year.
</P>
<P>
The Arabic daily Al Hayat reported Tuesday that the estimate
includes a rise of labour force to some 18.3 million this year.
</P>
<P>
Sources from the ministry attributed the lower unemployment
rate to government's employment policy, which was designed to
promote vocational and administrative training and continued
studies of the labour market abroad to seek new job opportunities.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- World financial and banking experts will meet in
Cairo October 4 to discuss ways to improve the efficiency of
banking sector in the Middle East, the Arabic Al Hayat reported
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The seminar on formulation of financial systems for development
in the Middle East and North Africa, organized by the World Bank
(WB), coincides with the joint annual meeting of the WB and the
International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
The seminar is planned in the backdrop of the crippling
financial crisis in Asia.
</P>
<P>
RAMALLAH -- The average monthly expenditures per Palestinian
family are 742 U.S. dollars, with 792 dollars in the West Bank and
628 dollars in the Gaza Strip, report from the Palestinian Central
Administration of Statistics has showed.
</P>
<P>
The agency, surveyed 3,600 Palestinian families, said the
relatively lower spending in Gaza resulted from Israel's closure
on the area and subsequent lower income.
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- The accuracy of the arrivals and departures of the
Royal Jordanian's (RJ) commercial flights increased by 4.3 percent
in the first eight months of this year as against the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
A RJ report released Tuesday said 80 percent of the airline's
flights arrived and departed on schedule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
