<HEADLINE> Lesotho Government Paralyzed as Turmoil Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Lesotho government
departments became paralyzed Wednesday as civil servants abandoned
their offices and went home for fear of increasing turmoils in the
capital of Maseru, sources reaching here said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, opposition supporters in the country took to the
streets for the second successive day to protest the delay in
releasing an investigation report into alleged electoral fraud in
the southern African kingdom.
</P>
<P>
A joint investigation team formed by officials from South Africa,
Botswana and Zimbabwe reportedly completed last week a report on the
Lesotho elections in May. However, the South African government, which
chairs the team, declined to make the report public immediately.
</P>
<P>
Lesotho opposition coalition spokesman Mamelo Morrison was quoted
as saying that employees in government departments and parastatals had
either closed shop or were in the process of doing so.
</P>
<P>
Junior officers of the Lesotho army, who forced army chief Makhula
Mosakheng to resign last week, have offered support to protesters,
informed sources said.
</P>
<P>
Earlier on Wednesday angry protesters also blocked entrances to
parliament. Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili, cabinet ministers and
senior government officials were unable to gain entry to their offices
because of the blockade.
</P>
<P>
Protesters locked the parliamentary gates and left a message that
anybody who tampered with the lock would do so at their own risk,
witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the protesters said their intention was to make
the Mosisili government ungovernable as "it was in power illegally".
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Lesotho opposition party supporters seized government
vehicles and blocked entrances to other government officers in town
and parastatals like the Lesotho Telecommunications Corporations.
</P>
</TEXT>
