<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Vows to Keep Borrowings Within Budgeted Limit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Indian Finance Minister
Yashwant Sinha said Wednesday that his ministry and the Reserve
Bank of India (RBI) are working out a common strategy to keep the
fiscal deficit within the targeted 5.6 percent of GDP in fiscal
1998-99.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an economic editors conference here, he said, "We
will make sure that government does not borrow more than the
budgeted levels. The RBI's busy season credit policy to be
announced next month will contain measures to take care of this."
</P>
<P>
The Indian government's borrowing program is put at more than
790 billion rupees (18.72 billion U.S. dollars) in the 1998-99
budget against 560 billion rupees (14.55 billion dollars) in the
previous fiscal year, he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to higher inflation, Sinha said inflation would be
reined in over the next few months. He attributed the price rise
to increases in prices of agricultural commodities.
</P>
<P>
According to reports, in the past couple of months, prices of
daily necessities have risen sharply and the inflation rate has
been recorded at 8.78 percent, the highest in the past three
years.
</P>
<P>
Turning to the country's economic policy, Sinha said India
would not retreat into protectionism. India's integration with the
global economic process would continue as no country could afford
to remain in an island of isolation in the fast changing world
economy.
</P>
<P>
He said India would make a forceful plea for reforming the
international financial system at the annual meeting of the
International Monetary Fund (IMF)-World Bank in Washington next
month to ensure that unscrupulous global operators did not trample
upon national interests of developing countries as those in East
Asia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
