<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China's War on Illegal Foreign-Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
They also said that smuggling, money laundering, tax fraud
and profiteering are often behind illegal foreign-exchange
activities.
</P>
<P>
"Illegal dealings in foreign exchange can seriously disturb
the economic and financial order and endanger national economic
security, and therefore must be harshly dealt with," a SAFE
official said.
</P>
<P>
The measures already taken to stamp out illegal
foreign-exchange trading activities include a general examination
of foreign-exchange settlements of enterprises, and revising
existing rules and regulations and increasing punishment for
violators, according to the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the customs, banks and foreign-exchange
administration departments computers will soon be linked up to
ensure synchronical transmitting and checking of the inflow and
outflow of goods and foreign exchange, thereby eliminating
loopholes.
</P>
<P>
The majority of economists here agree that despite the impact
of the Asian financial crisis, and the devastating floods, the
Chinese economy is in good shape and is improving month by
month. They also said that China will be able to realize its goal
of an eight percent increase in gross domestic product for all of
1998.
</P>
<P>
All this indicates that the people are fully justified to remain
confident in the economy and the yuan, they noted.
</P>
<P>
Official statistics show that China reported a trade surplus of
31.38 billion U.S. dollars in the first eight months of this year,
attracted 23.9 billion U.S. dollars in direct foreign investment
in the first seven months, and has current foreign-exchange
reserves valued at 140 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, China has a sound balance of international
payments and a reasonably sized and structured foreign debt.
</P>
