<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Geologist Puts Forward New Flood Explanation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- An extreme increase in the
amount of vapor and heat escaping from the earth's crust is one
geological factor contributing to the floods that ravaged the
Yangtze River Valley this year, according to Beijing geochemist Du
Letian.
</P>
<P>
He set forth this new idea in an interview with Xinhua, saying
that the rain cloud mass from the Indian Ocean was not capable, by
itself, of causing this year's unusually heavy rainfall.
</P>
<P>
"The Yangtze River is a large gap where gases, with vapor and
heat, intermittently escape from the earth's crust with pressure
dozens or even hundreds of times stronger than the atmospheric
pressure. The escaped gases were extremely strong this year." Du
said.
</P>
<P>
He also pointed out that vapor and heat emitted from
underground is the major reason the four hottest cities in China
are located along the Yangtze.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said, these gases prevented the rain cloud mass
from moving northward and significantly enlarged the cloud mass.
</P>
<P>
"So this year's rainfall greatly exceeded that in the past," he
added.
</P>
<P>
The geochemist noted that although he is not yet certain of the
geological effects on precipitation, underground meteorological
research is essential for natural disaster prevention and relief.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
