<HEADLINE> Pakistan Not to Sign CTBT Until Sanctions Lifted: FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz said Wednesday that his country would not sign the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) until sanctions against it
are lifted and its legitimate concerns addressed to its
satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister made the remarks while winding up
discussions on the issue of the CTBT in a joint session of the
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The major opposition parties continued to boycott the house
proceedings on the second day. They complained that the government
had not taken them into its confidence while opening the debate on
the issue.
</P>
<P>
The joint sitting of the parliament was convened for exclusive
debate on the CTBT to evolve consensus on the issue. The joint
sitting, however, could not table a resolution.
</P>
<P>
Aziz assured members of the parliament that their suggestions
would guide the government in its future negotiations on the CTBT
and national interest would come uppermost.
</P>
<P>
There would be no bargain on national interest, Aziz said,
adding that Pakistan is a nuclear power and this capability would
be protected at all costs.
</P>
<P>
"The signing of CTBT would not affect our nuclear capability
and no world power can deny this," the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to a demand for linking the solution to the Kashmir
issue with the signing of the CTBT, Aziz said that after
Pakistan's nuclear tests there is a greater realization in the
world community that a solution to the Kashmir issue is vital for
lasting peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said the government would intensify its efforts for the
solution of the Kashmir issue. He also said there was no
justification for economic and other sanctions against Pakistan
and demanded their lifting immediately. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
