<HEADLINE> Business Travel: Target for Cost Control in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Business travel is where
many Asian companies are considering to chop spending amid the
current economic woes and efficient management can help them
achieve the goal without cutting such trips, a travel service said
here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Travel and entertainment are the third largest expense for most
companies, after salaries and costs in information technology,
said Tim Johnson, who heads American Express Travel Services Group
in the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
Asian companies spend about 100 billion U.S. dollars on travel
and entertainment a year, about one-quarter of the total by firms
worldwide, according to American Express, a global travel services
company.
</P>
<P>
Johnson told an economic forum here Wednesday, "After almost 30
years of fabulous growth, there is a compelling need for Asian
companies to cut operating costs."
</P>
<P>
Asian companies have started to tighten budgets by firing
workers or using updated technology in face of the current
economic trouble, but many of them ignore the fact that efficient
management of travel and related expenses can help cut operating
costs significantly, he said.
</P>
<P>
American Express estimates that corporations can save around 30
percent of their spending on travel and entertainment by
efficiently monitoring their expenses and creating a
cost-effective travel program.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
