<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China's War on Illegal Foreign-Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Surpluses on both capital and current accounts have
ensured an ample foreign-exchange supply in China and all major
indicators show that, theoretically and practically, China has a
sound economic foundation to keep the exchange rate of its yuan
stable," said Li Guobin, a senior economist at the State
Information Center.
</P>
<P>
Along with most Chinese economists, many international
institutions and foreign government officials also are upbeat
about China's economy and ability to keep the yuan stable and the
economy growing at at a relatively high rate.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund (IMF), for example,
praised China highly in its 1998 global economic report.
</P>
<P>
Although there has been a financial crisis in parts of Asia,
the Chinese financial market has been unaffected and has remained
stable, which indicates that the macroeconomic policies China has
adopted since 1993 have yielded actual effects, the IMF said.
</P>
<P>
It also warned that there is limited room for financial
speculation in China, as the country has huge foreign-exchange
reserves and capital inflow is mostly in the form of direct
investment.
</P>
<P>
An observer here who declined to be named said, "The IMF report
has sounded the alarm for those who intend to rake in fat profits
in China through illegal foreign-exchange dealings and
speculation."
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, the Chinese yuan has remained strong
despite massive devaluations of the currencies of many countries
in the region beginning in July 1997. The yuan has been traded at
around 8.3 to the U.S. dollar for more than one year.
</P>
<P>
"The whole world has benefited greatly from China's effort to
keep the yuan's exchange rate stable," Robert Rubin,
U.S. treasury secretary said in the latest issue of Fortune, a
widely read financial magazine.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-British Joint Liaison Group Ends Meeting in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Sino-British Joint
Liaison Group (JLG) ended its two-day meeting here Wednesday with
a joint communique issued.
</P>
<P>
The next meeting of the JLG will take place in Beijing this
year, at a time to be decided by the two sides, the communique
said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese Senior Representative Wang Guisheng and his British
counterpart, Ambassador Alan Paul, jointly held a press conference
here after the JLG's 43rd meeting.
</P>
<P>
Wang noted that the JLG meeting was held under the
circumstances of the effective and successful practice of "one
country, two systems" and "Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong"
with a high degree of autonomy by the government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) and the people of Hong Kong
with the strong backing of the Central People's Government and the
Chinese people as a whole over the past one year or more.
</P>
<P>
In a positive, friendly and practical manner, he said, the two
sides exchanged views on the situation in Hong Kong and some
remaining issues such as the issue of Vietnamese refugees and boat
 people and the issue concerning the continued application of the
Paris Convention on third party liability in the field of nuclear
energy.
</P>
<P>
Wang reaffirmed the central government's support for the SAR
government's efforts to maintain the linked exchange rate between
the Hong Kong dollar and the greenback and to stabilize the
financial market.
</P>
<P>
When asked to comment on roles of the JLG, Wang said that
before Hong Kong's return to China, the JLG had done a great deal
of effective work and played an important role in implementing the
 Sino-British Joint Declaration on the Question of Hong Kong and
promoting the smooth return of Hong Kong to China.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the JLG is not an organ of power, but an organ
for liaison. It will not participate or interfere in the daily
management of the SAR affairs.
</P>
<P>
Wang listed several reasons for the continued existence of the
JLG after Hong Kong's return to China.
</P>
<P>
First, the Joint Declaration stipulates that the JLG will
continue its work until January 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Second, the JLG has only basically completed its historical
missions and the two sides still need to hold consultations and
exchange views on some remaining issues or new issues arising from
new circumstances.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the Vietnamese refugees and boat people, Wang
said the SAR government, along with the Central People's
Government, has made concerted efforts to bring this long-standing
problem to an end.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese side noted and appreciated the efforts made by the
British side and hoped that the British side will undertake its
inescapable responsibility for the final solution of this matter,
he said.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that there are a total of more than 1,100 Vietnamese
refugees and boat people stranded in Hong Kong and the U.N. High
Commissioner for Refugees' debt to the Hong Kong SAR amounts to
1.16 billion HK dollars (148.7 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that more efforts will be made by the
British side in this regard.
</P>
<P>
Paul described his discussions with the Chinese side as free
and wide-ranging. "At the meeting we took the opportunity to
review developments in the six months that have elapsed since our
last plenary meeting in March," he said.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated the British government's strong support for the
SAR government's commitment to the defense of the Hong Kong dollar
peg to the U.S. dollar and for the contribution it is making to
global currency stability.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of Vietnamese boat people, Paul said the British
side remains ready to do what it can in support of the efforts of
the SAR and China's central government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
