<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Bond Market Hit by Foreign Exodus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The foreign exodus from
the South African bond market which started in May has so far led
to a net disinvestment of almost six billion Rand (963 million
U.S. Dollars) for the year, the latest bond exchange figures
show.
</P>
<P>
According to the Business Day report Wednesday, net foreign
sales of bonds have reached more than 22 billion Rand (3.53
billion U.S. Dollars) since May, more than wiping out all the net
foreign investment in the market this year.
</P>
<P>
On Monday alone, the report said, foreigners sold a sizable
one billion Rand (160 million Dollars) in bonds.
</P>
<P>
Last year, South Africa saw a net investment of 14.8 billion
Rand (2.4 billion Dollars) in the bond market.
</P>
<P>
With the capital exodus continuing unabated, hopes of an ease
in interest rates in the near future were dashed. The flight
from local bond market is one of the main reasons behind the
sharp rises in the central bank's lending rate in recent months.
</P>
<P>
Governor of the South African Reserve Bank, Chris Stals, said
the outflow of capital was causing a liquidity shortage in the
country's financial markets, which was why the bank had to hike
its lending rate to commercial banks to just under 22 percent
last month, the highest level in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
The reserve bank's rate hike and the subsequent increases in
commercial banks' interest rates have raised fears that South
Africa would fall into recession at the beginning of next year.
</P>
<P>
Economists said that the havoc wreaked by the foreign stampede
from the South African capital market highlighted the country's
dependence on "hot" capital inflows from abroad to finance
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
But some economists said local and foreign sentiment could
improve, after the U.S. presidential crisis is resolved, and
after the G-7 industrialized nations take concrete action to
stave off a global financial crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
