<HEADLINE> East China Province Upgrades Power Facilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- East China's Jiangsu Province
will spend at least 48.8 billion yuan over the next three years to
increase power output to meet the growing demand for electricity.
</P>
<P>
The program aims to bring installed capacity to 19.5 million
kilowatts by the year 2000 from the present 14.38 million
kilowatts, according to provincial power department sources.
</P>
<P>
Over the past five years, Jiangsu has achieved an annual
economic growth of 15.5 percent, with a gross domestic product
reaching 669.5 billion yuan last year, ranking second in China,
next to south China Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The rapid expansion of the economy in Jiangsu, one major
economic powerhouse in the country, has put great pressure on the
power supply which has long been restricted by backward facilities
and the lack of variety in energy sources.
</P>
<P>
Under the new program, the province will use much of these
funds to build some large and medium-sized power plants equipped
with generating units of no less than 300,000 kilowatts each.
</P>
<P>
These will include a nuclear power station with two
one-million-kilowatt generating units in Lianyungang, and two
pumping regenerative stations, in Yixing and Liyang.
</P>
<P>
The province will transform many existing small power stations
into environment-friendly and modern facilities. It also plans to
establish or upgrade more than 400 transformer substations to
ensure a better power supply for both urban and rural residents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
