<HEADLINE> Arab Foreign Ministers Start Meetings in Cairo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Foreign ministers from the 22
Arab League (AL) member states met Wednesday at its headquarters
in Cairo to coordinate stances on vital issues challenging the
Arab world.
</P>
<P>
At the 110th session of the AL Foreign Ministerial Council
meeting, the ministers will discuss draft resolutions, which
reaffirm the land-for-peace principle and the Palestinians' rights
to self-determination, and call on the world community to impose
"appropriate sanctions" against Israel.
</P>
<P>
The resolutions, among other issues, also tackle the Lockerbie
bombing incident which involved two Libyan suspects, deadlock in
peace talks between Syria, Lebanon and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Arab-Israeli peace talks on all tracks have hit an impasse
due to Israel's intransigence.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority President Yasser Arafat will
address the opening session on the latest developments in the
Palestinian-Israeli peace negotiations and on the outcome of
U.S. peace coordinator Dennis Ross' current mission aimed at
reviving the stalled peace drive.
</P>
<P>
Ross has held several rounds of talks with Palestinian and
Israeli officials on their security cooperation and the scope of
Israeli troops withdrawal from the West Bank. No substantial
progress has so far been achieved.
</P>
<P>
Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa chairs the two-day
meeting because Syria holds the current rotating presidency of the
organization. 
</P>
</TEXT>
