<HEADLINE> Indonesian Attorney General Heads Team to Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Attorney General
Andi M. Ghalib will head the team tasked to investigate the
alleged hidden wealth of former president Soeharto, a minister
said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The team will be composed of the chief of the Indonesian Police
and the head of the State Auditor's Office, Coordinating Minister
for Development Supervision and State Administrative Reform
Hartarto told reporters before a cabinet meeting at the
Presidential Office.
</P>
<P>
"It will soon contact the former president to inform him of the
investigation," he said.
</P>
<P>
President B.J. Habibie Tuesday ordered a special team to
directly examine Soeharto over his recent statement that he did
not have "a single cent" of savings overseas as widely alleged.
</P>
<P>
American magazine Forbes estimated in July that Soeharto, who
stepped down amid mounting public pressure on May 21, had a
fortune worth 4 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
But Soeharto swore that he did not have any deposits abroad in
a statement broadcast by his own daughter's television station
early this month.
</P>
<P>
Ghalib told reporters Wednesday that the probe is being
conducted in response to the people's demand and because Soeharto
and his children have opened the doors.
</P>
<P>
The probe will focus on allegations that the former president
has a great deal of money stashed here and abroad, the source of
his children's wealth, and the presidential instructions that
Soeharto issued special privileges to family members, relatives
and close friends.
</P>
<P>
"The team will investigate matters that are supported by data,"
Ghalib said, adding that it will work on the presumption of
innocence until proven guilty.
</P>
<P>
Questioning will start before the end of this week, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Justice Minister Muladi said the probe on Soeharto
is the start of a legal action, meaning everything related to the
issue of hidden wealth will be identified and investigated.
</P>
<P>
He said the government will trace if the Soeharto family's
wealth came from corruption and collusion.
</P>
<P>
"The most important things is that (the probe) is open to the
people. It should be transparent," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
