<HEADLINE> Pakistan PM Offers to Mediate Between Iran, Taliban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif has offered to act as mediator in a bid to ease the
tension between Iran and the afghan Taliban militia, the
Associated Press of Pakistan said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a message to Iranian President Seyed Mohammad Khatami,
Sharif urged both Iran and Afghanistan to take steps to defuse the
current tension and show restraint and mutual understanding and
seek reconciliation and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"This is fundamental to the region's peace and stability as
well as Islamic solidarity in the long run," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Pakistan is ready to expedite this process in any way our
Iranian and Afghan brothers wish," he said.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Iran and the Taliban worsened last week after
the Taliban admitted that its forces killed nine Iranian nationals
in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
The Iranians were seized in a raid by the Taliban militia on
Iran's consulate in Mazar-i-Sharif, the stronghold of the
anti-Taliban Northern Alliance, on August 8.
</P>
<P>
Sharif slammed the killing of the Iranians as a "catastrophe"
and said Islamabad has asked the Taliban militia to "arrest and
punish the culprits." 
</P>
</TEXT>
