<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ansett Suspends Shanghai Services, Plans Fiji Flight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Australian-New Zealand
airline Ansett announced Wednesday its decision to suspend its
Sydney-Shanghai services from October 22 this year and a plan to
add Fiji to its international network later this year.
</P>
<P>
Ansett attributed the suspension of the Sydney-Shanghai
services to the current excessive capacity of four carriers on the
route, including Australian flag carrier Qantas and Air China and
Shanghai-based Eastern Airline.
</P>
<P>
The present situation has meant that the airline can no longer
afford to operate the service without sustaining significant
losses over a period of time, the company said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Ansett, which began flying the Sydney-Shanghai route on June 8,
1997, said it would continue to be represented in China through
its Shanghai office.
</P>
<P>
Craig Wallace, general manager of Ansett International, said
Ansett Australia, a division of Ansett Australia Limited, would
add Fiji to its international network from November 24 this year.
</P>
<P>
Wallace said it intends to operate services from Sydney to Nadi
of Fiji, a popular leisure destination, with a Boeing 757-200 on
Saturdays and an Airbus A320 on Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
"Fiji has a distinct combination of leisure, business...
traffic on the route," Wallace said in the statement. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
