<HEADLINE> Qomolangma Reserve Provides Safe Sanctuary for Rare Species </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Qomolangma Reserve in
southwest China's Tibet Autonomous region, or the so-called "Roof
of the World", provides a safe sanctuary for a number of
endangered species.
</P>
<P>
Snow leopards, an endangered species which lives on the
highlands at altitudes ranging between 3,000-6,000 meters above
sea level, are frequently spotted in the state-class nature
reserve.
</P>
<P>
Other rare species include long-tailed leaf monkeys, wild
donkeys and Tar sheep, all of which were on the verge of
extinction prior to establishment of the reserve in 1988.
</P>
<P>
The regional government strictly prohibits hunting and logging
in the 330,000-sq.km. reserve.
</P>
<P>
"The reserve is a paradise for wild animals," said Cering
Truldan, deputy director of the Qomolangma Reserve Administration
Bureau, adding that staffers have effectively quelled excessive
hunting.
</P>
<P>
He said the increasing number of wild animals has also created
certain problems, including crop damage and attacks on
domesticated animals.
</P>
<P>
The local government has prioritized efforts to find solutions
to issues related to dealing with the relationship between
protecting wild animals and ensuring the well-being of residents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
