<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0172 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Economic Review: China's War on Illegal Foreign Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese officials and experts
have enthusiastically welcomed the government's declared war on
illegal foreign exchange dealings, describing it as conducive to
maintaining currency and financial market stability.
</P>
<P>
"The decision is very necessary and important for stabilizing
public sentiment and investor confidence as well as for
safeguarding the stability of the Renminbi yuan and the financial
order," Mao Yushi, director of the Beijing-based Unirule Institute
of Economics, said in an interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
This is especially so considering that the international
financial market remains turbulent, that some speculators with
ulterior motives both in and outside of China have fabricated and
spread rumors of yuan devaluation, and that the public has been
misled and become less confident about the yuan, he said.
</P>
<P>
The official decision, announced by a spokesman of the State
Administration of Foreign Exchange (SAFE) on Tuesday, has come in
response to a resurgence of black-market trading in foreign
exchange in some parts of China, and to increased efforts by some
people to evade foreign exchange payments and conduct unlawful
foreign-exchange arbitrages. All these practices have affected
China's balance of international payments.
</P>
<P>
"We must draw lessons from the financial turmoil in Southeast
Asia and Russia and resolutely crack down on illegal activities in
foreign exchange, or there might be grave consequences," Mao said.
</P>
<P>
Financial experts say that the harm done by illegal dealings in
foreign exchange should be viewed from the vantage point of
national economic security.
</P>
<P>
The financial crises in Southeast Asia and Russia have stemmed
partly from uncontrolled foreign-exchange dealings, which
increased the opportunities for international speculator to
profiteer, and caused the devaluation of local currencies as well
as economic recession and social instability, according to the
experts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
