<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Continue Military Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will carry on
with its military development program but with modifications in
the face of the country's economic slowdown, defense forces chief
General Ismail Omar said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The program for the period to year 2000, aimed at building up
the Malaysian military capability, is still relevant, Ismail said
while addressing a parade marking the defense forces' 65th
anniversary here.
</P>
<P>
He however said cutbacks in allocation because of the economic
downturn have prompted the defense forces to readjust the
priorities for its development program.
</P>
<P>
He said, "Human resource development still gets high priority
given that the soldiering profession in the future requires
personnel of high expertise and knowledge."
</P>
<P>
The defense forces chief ordered Malaysian soldiers to be
sensitive to development in information technology (IT) and
familiarize themselves with the various IT applications to benefit
the national defense agenda.
</P>
<P>
He also directed them to constantly uphold the system of
regimental orders based on loyalty, camaraderie, discipline and
uniformity.
</P>
<P>
He said it is these values that would determine the genuine
strength of the Malaysian defense forces as without them the
forces' personnel would not make effective use of even the most
sophisticated equipment they have. 
</P>
</TEXT>
