<HEADLINE> China to Hold International Chemical Industry Fair </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- China's State Bureau of
Petroleum and Chemical Industry will release the latest policies
concerning industry restructuring and efforts to attract foreign
funds on September 22.
</P>
<P>
The new government agency will also announce new petroleum and
chemical projects which are seeking overseas partners or are
export-oriented.
</P>
<P>
This will be part of the International Chemical Industry
Fair '98 scheduled from September 22 to 26, said Sun Dongliang,
executive vice-chairman of the Chemical Industry Sub-Council of
the China Council for the Promotion of Foreign Trade.
</P>
<P>
The fair, co-organized by the bureau and the council, will
also offer opportunities for technological exchanges, product
introduction, and discussions on partnering possibilities.
</P>
<P>
According to the exhibition schedule, China's major chemical
research organizations will release 400 research results on
September 23.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, delegates from the United Kingdom, the United
States, Italy, South Africa and Taiwan will brief the audience on
the petroleum and chemical industry in their respective countries
and regions.
</P>
<P>
The fair is "the first large exhibition organized by the new
State Bureau of Petroleum and Chemical Industry, which has
undertaken major adjustments of functions and operational
mechanisms," said Sun.
</P>
<P>
Participants will include 1,000 domestic businesses and 80
overseas companies from 18 countries and regions. A national
delegation from South Africa's Ministry of Trade and Industry will
also attend.
</P>
<P>
This exhibition is the fourth in a series which began in
1992.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the trade volume for each of the previous
fairs was 15 billion yuan, about half of which was in foreign
trade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
