<HEADLINE> German Trade Surplus Surges in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Germany posted a trade surplus
of 14.2 billion marks (about 8.4 billion U.S. dollars) in July,
the highest monthly surplus registered in the past 10 years, the
German Federal Statistics Office said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Preliminary figures issued by the statistics office put
Germany's exports in July at 85 billion marks (about 50 billion
dollars), up 7.7 percent over the same month last year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Germany's imports grew only by 4.6 percent to a
total of 70.8 billion marks (about 41.6 billion dollars) in July.
</P>
<P>
For the first seven months as a whole, Germany saw its exports
surge by 10.9 percent to 559.1 billion marks (about 328.9 billion
dollars) while imports rose by 8.4 percent to 478.5 billion marks
(about 281.5 billion dollars), with a trade surplus of 80.6
billion marks (about 47.4 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the continuing exports boom, Germany's current
account deficit, which also measures trade in services and
financial transfers, shrank to 1.6 billion marks (about 941
million dollars) for the first seven months compared with 8.1
billion marks (about 4.8 billion dollars) for the corresponding
period of last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
