<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Blacks Feel More Unsafe Than Whites: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 16 (Xinhua) --The South African black
people are more frightened of their safety than whites, a victim
survey, which polled nearly 14,000 people, has found.
</P>
<P>
While 58 percent of white Johannesburg residents felt unsafe
in their neighborhoods at night, 67 of the blacks and 83 of
coloreds feared for their safety at night.
</P>
<P>
In Cape Town, the legislative capital of South Africa, only 20
percent whites felt threatened in their neighborhoods after dark,
while for black Capetonians, the figure was 50 percent, showed
the survey, conducted by the Institute for Security Studies.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that a majority of those who lived in four
largest metropolitan areas, namely Johannesburg, Pretoria, Durban
and Cape Town, had been victims of crime since 1993.
</P>
<P>
Johannesburg is believed to be the most dangerous city in
South Africa with 63 percent of the 1,200 surveyed saying that
they had been crime victims since 1993.
</P>
<P>
Other cities in the country were not that far behind. In
Durban the figure was 60 percent, in Pretoria 55 percent and in
Cape Town 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
The survey found that blacks were more likely to become crime
victims than whites in all major cities, with the notable
exception of Johannesburg where 70 percent of whites people
surveyed had been crime victims in the past four years, compared
with 58 percent of blacks.
</P>
<P>
Whites on the whole had more confidence in the police than
blacks, 45 percent of whites in Johannesburg believed that police
in their neighborhoods were doing a good job of controlling crime
while only 27 of blacks thought the same.
</P>
<P>
Asked what government should do to make cities safe, only a
small minority of those polled believed that penalties for crime
should be made harsher. Most believed that solution lay in more
effective policing.
</P>
<P>
Asked what government should do aside from policing, the
majority of respondents said that the government's most urgent
task was to create jobs.
</P>
<P>
The most prevalent crimes committed in South Africa's
metropolises were burglary and robbery, followed by assault and
car theft.
</P>
<P>
People in Pretoria, where hijacking incidents are
comparatively low, are twice as likely to be murdered as they are
to be hijacked, the survey showed.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Golden Monkey Population on the Decline </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The total golden monkey
population has dropped 764, some 300 less than the number of giant
pandas, according to a recent habitat survey.
</P>
<P>
China's three species of golden monkeys are found in southwest
China's Guizhou, Sichuan and Yunnan provinces. Golden monkeys
living in Guizhou Province face the greatest danger of extinction.
</P>
<P>
The natural of the monkeys, which weigh between 10-25 kg and
consume leaves, buds, flowers and fruits of more than 100
varieties of plants and fungi as well as insects, little birds and
their eggs, and fish, crabs and small animals, is limited to
primeval forests in the Fanjingshan Nature Reserve.
</P>
<P>
The scarcity of the animal can be attributed to the slow
reproduction cycle and evolution process, according to Prof. Ma
Hanzhang, an academician with the Chinese Academy of Engineering.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
