<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taliban Chief Seeks U.N. Condemnation of Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Afghan Taliban leader Mulla
Omar Wednesday asked the United Nations to condemn Iran if it
refuses to resolve its conflict with the Taliban on the basis of
international law.
</P>
<P>
If Iran is not ready to resolve the problem with the Taliban
militia on the basis of international law, "the United Nations
should condemn it," Radio Kabul quoted Omar as saying in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
"If the United Nations shuts its eyes and does not condemn
Iran, then the forum which regards itself as a neutral body would
be meaningless for the world people," Omar said.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban chief said his administration has made three to
four official requests but they have been ignored.
</P>
<P>
"If the United Nations does not consider our demand and Iran
does not get ready to resolve the dispute with Islamic Emirates of
Afghanistan on the basis of international laws, then the United
Nations should not interfere in the affairs of Afghanistan in
future," he said.
</P>
<P>
Iran, he said, can settle its problems with the Taliban
administration in accordance with international law.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, according to a report reaching here Wednesday
afternoon from Kabul, Omar Wednesday invited Iran to hold peace
negotiations to defuse tensions as Tehran ordered its forces to be
ready for swift action against the Taliban militia.
</P>
<P>
According to media reports, Iran has placed its army on a state
of high alert along the Iran-Afghan border. Senior Iranian leaders
have said Iran will take revenge on the Taliban for the killing of
its diplomats. 
</P>
</TEXT>
