<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Peace Effort Lauded </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's peace effort to
help defuse the Cambodian crisis has won applause from the
international community, Thai Foreign Ministry officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Europe and Japan endorsed Thailand's bid to
help broker talks between Cambodian conflicting parties and
expressed the hope that it would succeed in defusing tension in
the country, Foreign Ministry deputy spokesman Kitti Wasinondha
said.
</P>
<P>
Thai Deputy Foreign Minister Sukhumbhand Paribatra has just
ended a peace mission to Cambodia where he had separate meetings
with King Norodom Sihanouk and leaders of the three main political
parties -- Chea Sim of the Cambodian People's Party, Prince
Norodom Ranariddh of Funcinpec and Sam Rainsy of his self-named
party, according to Thai Foreign Ministry officials.
</P>
<P>
Sukhumbhand also tried to ensure safe travel guarantees for the
two opposition leaders to join a summit with Cambodian Second
Prime Minister Hun Sen under the chairmanship of King Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
Under Thailand's brokerage, the three conflicting parties have
agreed to hold talks.
</P>
<P>
In a message conveyed to Thailand, U.S. State Department
spokesman James Rubin hailed the trip as both timely and important
to the cause of peace and democracy.
</P>
<P>
Japan saw special significance in the deputy minister's
audience with King Sihanouk, noting that the monarch is endowed
with the "august role of arbitrator" under the Cambodian
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
Austrian Foreign Minister Wolfgang Schussel, speaking for the
EU presidency, praised the Thai initiative as conforming with that
of a good neighbor and with the European Union's stand for a
non-violent resolution of the Cambodian conflict. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
