<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Screenplay Depicts Roman Army in Ancient China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, September 16 (Xinhua) -- "The Last Roman Military
Group," a screenplay depicting a battle between Roman soldiers and
Chinese on the Silk Road 2,000 years ago, was published recently
in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
The film was written by Jiang Qingqing, a young journalist in
Hangzhou, capital of east China's Zhejiang Province. Jiang
gathered his material during a visit to the city of Yongchang in
northwest China's Gansu Province three years ago.
</P>
<P>
According to historical records, more than 45,000 Roman
soldiers took part in a battle in Central Asia in 53 B.C. and were
defeated by Asians.
</P>
<P>
About 6,000 soldiers were thought to have survived the fierce
battle, but were never heard from again.
</P>
<P>
The Han Dynastic records speak of a Roman military group that
encountered a Chinese army many years later, who, after
surrendering to the Han Dynasty, settled in northwest China. Some
believe the descendants of this group still live in Gansu Province.
</P>
<P>
Based on such historical facts, the screenplay focuses on human
nature and harmony rather than the conflict and resettlement of
the Roman soldiers.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
