<HEADLINE> Five AIDS/HIV Cases Found in Medan, Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Two persons suffering from
full-blown AIDS and three others who are HIV-positive have been
discovered in Medan, capital of Indonesia's North Sumatra
province.
</P>
<P>
"All 19 Thai fishermen found stranded at the Belawan port (in
Medan) have also tested HIV-positive," Medan Mayor H. Bahtiar
Djafar was quoted by Antara News Agency Wednesday as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said more AIDS and HIV cases have yet to be detected.
</P>
<P>
On the spread of the lethal disease, he said, the prevalence
and incidence of sexually-transmitted diseases in Medan is quite
high due to the high mobility of merchants, workers, tourists and
other people who enter and leave the city through the Belawan port
and the Polinia airport.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that over 700 people in Indonesia are known to
be infected with the HIV virus that causes AIDS. Among them, 195
were positively suffering from AIDS, while the others were
HIV-infected. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fossil Fragments May Belong To Largest Asian Dinosaur </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Archeologists in Chongqing
in southeast China have unearthed dinosaur fossil fragments
which they believe belong to the largest dinosaur ever discovered
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
The fossil fragments were found at a construction site two
meters underground in Tongnan County, and are thought to date back
some 140 million years. Among the more than 30 fossil bones are a
scapula 2.2 meters long and a vertebra 0.9 meters high.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists said this dinosaur might have been some 28 meters
in length when full grown. This is six or seven meters longer than
 the largest known fossil dinosaur ever found in Asia, discovered
in Mamenxi near the city of Chongqing forty years ago.
</P>
<P>
But many parts of this latest discovery are missing and some
fossils are very fragile because they were positioned very close
to the earth's surface, said one archeologist, adding that the
discovery provides valuable material for dinosaur research and
other inquiries into the conditions of the region in remote
antiquity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila-Rebels Peace Talks Still Ongoing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Peace talks between the
Philippine government and the separatist Moro Islamic Liberation
Front (MILF) are still ongoing, Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora
said here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zamora said that while speculations on recent kidnappings may
have hampered negotiations somewhat, the low-level peace talks
have not stopped.
</P>
<P>
In a radio interview, Zamora also said both sides have set up
informal channels to continue talks if negotiations at the low
level fail.
</P>
<P>
"We have to focus on this particular problem but the peace
talks at the panel level will not be stopped... as a matter of
fact, MILF negotiators are talking to me," he said.
</P>
<P>
Zamora added that the government has even accepted the MILF's
offer to proceed with the talks after the kidnapping of Italian
priest Luciano Benedetti, whose abduction was initially linked to
the MILF.
</P>
<P>
Zamora also dismissed as a case of media misinterpretation
President Joseph Estrada's reported backtracking on peace talks
with the secessionist rebels.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a breakaway faction of the mainstream Moro National
Liberation Front (MNLF) which already signed a peace treaty with
the government in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The MILF and the government began their low-level peace talks
in January 1997. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0202 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African Leaders Urged to Watch on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Mozambican President Joaquim
Chissano has called upon African especially southern African
leaders to keep close eyes on the situation in Angola.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the dinner for visiting Namibian President Sam
Nujoma here Tuesday, President Chissano said that Angola's
opposition movement the United Union for Total Independence of
Angola (UNITA)is pushing the war-torn country to the verge of
fighting by ignoring the 1994 Lusaka Peace Protocol.
</P>
<P>
"We hope the new leaders of the breakaway UNITA faction can
turn the situation toward peace, national unity, state
reconstruction and regional peace and stability," Wednesday's
Noticias newspaper quoted Chissano as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Mozambican president reiterated support for the Angolan
people and government, calling upon the international community
to continue providing all necessary assistances to Angola in
order to ensure a final peace in the country and the
reintegration of all citizens into the society.
</P>
<P>
Chissano expressed his confidence that as the United Nations
new special representative of Secretary-General Kofi Annan to
Angola, Issa Diallo, arrived in the country, a new scenario will
appear and the conflict will be resolved.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the developments in the Democratic Republic of
Congo (DRC), the Mozambican president said that in order to keep
the Congo crisis in rein, it is important for the resolutions
adopted at the summit of the Southern African Development
Community (SADC) in Mauritius early this week and the agreements
reached at the meetings in South Africa's Pretoria and Zimbabwe's
Victoria Falls earlier to be observed.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the best way to quickly restore peace in
Congo (K) is to resume dialog," said Chissano.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the conflicts in Lesotho since over a month ago
are also worrisome and they could bring negative affects on the
stability in the sub-region.
</P>
<P>
"We call on the Basotho and their leaders to bring the social,
economic and political life of the country back to normal through
peaceful approaches." he said.
</P>
<P>
Chissano also called upon the world community to reschedule or
write off the debts burdening the African states, saying that
heavy debts are impeding the development and growth of these
countries and unbalancing their trade.
</P>
<P>
Echoing the words of the Mozambican leader, President Nujoma
said that Africa should not merely be the receiver of the foreign
manufactured goods and the industrialized nations should
implement more generous trade policies toward Africa so that the
African products could have quick access to their markets.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma arrived in Maputo Tuesday evening on his first state
visit to Mozambique since he became the Namibian president.
</P>
<P>
Besides holding talks with Chissano on the cooperation between
the two southern African nations, Nujoma will pay a visit to
central Mozambican city of Beira.
</P>
<P>
Nujoma is scheduled to end his visit Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
