<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0203 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tianjin Striving to Vitalize Local Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The north China city Tianjin
is trying to vitalize its local economy by investing in several
new sectors to propel economic growth.
</P>
<P>
This move is designed to counter the diminishing force of major
economic city powerhouses such as the coastal development zone and
the petrochemical and automobile industries which have been
feeling the adverse impact of many unfavorable factors since the
beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the newly chosen sectors for
development include real estate, high-tech industries, and
research and development of new industrial products.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the city spent 3.1 billion yuan in housing
construction in the first half of this year, a rise of 12 percent
over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to supporting measures for boosting real estate
development, the city sold 1.23 million square meters of
open-market apartments between January and June, a rise of 71
percent.
</P>
<P>
The development of the real estate sector over the past six
months contributed 1.21 percentage points to Tianjin's economic
growth this year, a growth targeted for nine percent.
</P>
<P>
The city will put even more investment into the real estate
sector in the later half of the year. It is estimated that 10
billion yuan will be spent in housing construction this year, with
completed apartment buildings totaling 4.5 million square meters
and sales of 3 million square meters of apartments.
</P>
<P>
The real estate sector, including the renovating of
dilapidated housing and the construction of new and modern
apartments, is expected to contribute two percentage points to the
city's economic growth in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The city also reported encouraging results from investments
in high-tech industries, technical upgrading and technological
innovations, and the development of new industrial products.
</P>
<P>
For example, in the first six months, Tianjin had a rise
of 14.6 percent over the same period last year in the output value
of new industrial products.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> World Cup Can't be Rescheduled, FIFA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The next World Cup cannot be
rescheduled for bad weather in joint-host countries South Korea
and Japan, according to a news release from FIFA on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
South Korean officials suggested earlier this year that the c
ompetition should start in May 2002 to avoid the traditional
rainy season.
</P>
<P>
But FIFA's planning group said at a meeting Tuesday that the
dates for the event cannot be changed because June and July are
traditionally reserved for the World Cup.
</P>
<P>
The quadrennial, monthlong competition usually starts around
June 10. The professional soccer season in Europe and South
America ends in April.
</P>
<P>
"Any change of timing would severely disrupt soccer operations
around the world," FIFA said.
</P>
<P>
However, officials have asked both nations to investigate past
weather in the region between May and September to allow FIFA's
executive committee to make a final decision at a two-day meeting
starting September 24.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: China Invests Heavily in Highway Construction (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- China expects heavy
investments in highway construction to promote economic growth
during 1998.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government recently added 20 billion yuan to its
highway construction budget, bringing the total budgeted figure
for the year to 180 billion yuan. The initial figure of 120
billion yuan was increased to 160 billion yuan in June.
</P>
<P>
The massive investment is expected to increase this year's GDP
by 0.795 percentage points, according to recent estimates by the
Ministry of Communications.
</P>
<P>
Increasing investment has promoted China's economic growth,
according to well-known economist Hu Angang. Hu pointed out
ongoing adjustments of the economic structure, especially in terms
of redundant processing industries and undeveloped basic
facilities.
</P>
<P>
"Accelerating the construction of basic facilities will be a
major factor in ensuring fulfillment of the eight percent economic
growth goal for 1998 and alleviating existing bottlenecks," said
Hu.
</P>
<P>
He added that the highway system, a key infrastructure sector
which has long restricted economic development, is undoubtedly a
key target for investment.
</P>
<P>
China commenced its highway construction program less than a
century ago. The nation's first highway, which was constructed in
southwest China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region in 1906,
was only several dozen kilometers long. The nation's total highway
mileage in 1949 stood at 80,000 km, with the figure rising sharply
to 1.23 million km by the end of last year. Highways are currently
found in all counties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: China Invests Heavily in Highway Construction (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, China's current level of 11 kilometers of highways for
every 100 sq.km is far less than the 60 km average in developed
countries, and less than a third of the average level in
developing countries such as India and Thailand in the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
China's highways are for the most part low grade arteries with
limited capacity. The nation's 4,700-km expressway system
represents a mere five percent of the total length of the
U.S. system. The mileage for high-grade highways accounts for a
mere 10.7 percent of the total. Statistics show that vehicles
plying China's highways travel at only an average speed of 30
km/hr.
</P>
<P>
The 180 billion yuan earmarked for highway construction will
create 1.2 million jobs during 1998 and will greatly benefit
efforts to reemploy laid-off workers, according to Zhu Yongguang,
director of the Department for System Restructuring and Regulation
under the Ministry of Communications.
</P>
<P>
June statistics show that 4.38 million Chinese workers were
engaged in highway construction, including 3.36 million farmers.
</P>
<P>
Highway construction will also promote growth in related
industries, said Zhu. Over 1.03 million tons of steel, 14 million
tons of cement, 250,000 tons of asphalt, and 1.73 million tons of
oil consumed funds totalling 46.45 billion yuan during the first
half of this year.
</P>
<P>
Zhu noted that various other industries will witness
accelerated development in conjunction with the expanded scale of
highway construction during the latter half of the year.
</P>
<P>
China will set a new record by constructing highways stretching
over 33,000 km during 1998, including the record construction of
expressways covering some 1,560 kilometers.
</P>
<P>
China's long-term policy centers on accelerating infrastructure
construction. The State Council plan calls for 500 billion yuan in
funding for highway construction over three years. The total
highway mileage will hit 1.4 million km by the year 2002, with the
expressway network covering 10,000 kilometers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
