<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Academic on U.S. Policies Toward South Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 16 (Xinhua) -- An American academic said
here Wednesday that the first interest of the United States right
now in South Asia is the containment of nuclear activities
followed by increased trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua, Stephen F. Dachi, chair for South
Asia Area Studies at the Foreign Service Institute of U.S.
Department of State, said that the United States would like to
ensure that there is no more testing but agreement to sign the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.
</P>
<P>
Besides, the United States has important objectives of
developing economic relations and promoting investment and trade
with the South Asia region, he said.
</P>
<P>
Unfortunately, the sanctions slapped on India and Pakistan by
the United States following their nuclear tests in May make it
more difficult to improve the economic ties, he said.
</P>
<P>
Dachi is on a lecture tour in Nepal at the invitation of the
U.S. Information Service Office here. During his 29 years of
foreign service career which ended in March 1996, Dachi traveled
frequently in Asia, Europe and the Americas to lecture on global
economy and U.S. foreign policies.
</P>
<P>
He said that his country is also very concerned about the
tensions between India and Pakistan, terrorism and narcotics flow
in the region and human rights violations in Afghanistan, which is
considered by the U.S. as part of South Asia.
</P>
<P>
The South Asia region did not figure prominently in U.S.
foreign policies after the end of the cold war. But last November
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright visited Pakistan and
India in preparation for a scheduled visit to the two countries by
President Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
"When Secretary of State Albright came here, the U.S.
government was very hopeful that we could have a major improvement
in cooperation relations," Dachi said. "The testing has changed
the situation unfortunately."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the United States was not changing its foreign
policies toward South Asia, but devoting more attention to
strengthening relations with the region.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the United States always has three to five
foreign policy crises going on in the world at any one time, so it
is very difficult some time to devote all the necessary attention
to every issue in the world.
</P>
<P>
"South Asia is sometimes not very high on the administration's
priority list. That's what the secretary of state and the
president want to remedy, but the situation is more difficult," he
said.
</P>
<P>
He added that President Clinton's visit to India and Pakistan
is still under review.
</P>
<P>
But he said that it is possible that the United States will
lift the sanctions on India and Pakistan in the near future
"because all these sanctions were imposed by congressional action
and there has been very definite recognition in the U.S. Congress
that we have to review our sanctions policies because sometimes
they do not work very well."
</P>
<P>
He said that there is a two-party special commission appointed
by the Congress to evaluate U.S. sanctions policies.
</P>
<P>
In the case of selling wheat to Pakistan, the Congress voted to
suspend embargo for the deal about three weeks ago, he said.
</P>
<P>
On regional cooperation, Dachi said that "regional cooperation
in SAARC (South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation) is
always being impeded, slowed down by the tensions between India
and Pakistan."
</P>
<P>
He said that when the two powers are concentrating on
difficulties in relations between themselves, it is very difficult
to get the smaller member countries to move toward very firm
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, formed in December 1985, groups Bangladesh, Bhutan,
India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka.
</P>
<P>
On the development prospects of the region in the 21st century,
Dachi noted that Bangladesh has made most progress in the last
five years with thousands of new jobs created, energy resources
developed and many people becoming better-off.
</P>
<P>
India made some progress for a few years with the economic
reform, he said, but now it is slowing down.
</P>
<P>
He said Sri Lanka would be doing very well except for the civil
war, while for Nepal, the big breakthrough lies in development of
hydro-power, but investment and market are the problems to be
addressed.
</P>
<P>
He observed that as obstacles to peaceful development are great
in South Asia, one of the poorest regions in the world, and the
prospects for resolving the political obstacles are not very
encouraging, economic prospects are not bright here in the next
century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
