<HEADLINE> Arafat Updates Mubarak on Peace Contacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat Wednesday morning held talks with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak on his recent contacts made to break the
peace impasse with Israel, the Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Arafat arrived in the northern coastal city of Alexandria
Tuesday evening on a two-day visit to Egypt to attend the Arab
League (AL) Foreign Ministers' meeting.
</P>
<P>
His talks with Mubarak in Alexandria focused on the results of
current peace-saving efforts and his three round of talks in a
week with U.S. Mideast peace coordinator Dennis Ross.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's Presidential Political Adviser Osama el-Baz,
Palestinian Minister of Planning and International Cooperation
Nabil Shaath attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is scheduled to deliver a speech at the opening session
of AL Foreign Ministerial Council's 110th meeting in Cairo later
in the day.
</P>
<P>
In his address, the Palestinian leader will call on the Arab
countries to hold an emergency Arab summit to rescue the faltering
Mideast peace process and challenge Israel's intransigence.
</P>
<P>
Ross arrived in the region last week on a new mission to narrow
the gaps between the Palestinian and Israeli sides on an American
plan on Israeli redeployment. But there is no breakthrough after
his rounds of shuttling between Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
Arafat has accepted the U.S. proposal on a 13 percent Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank in return for harsher crackdown on
Palestinian militants. But he rejected Netanyahu's idea of turning
3 percent into a "nature reserve" over which the PNA has only
limited control.
</P>
<P>
Egypt backs the U.S. initiative but warns Arafat against
striking a "bad" deal that would compromise Palestinians'
interests and can not be implemented. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Artificial Breeding Techniques Developed for Golden Monkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUIYANG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists may be
able to save the golden monkey in southwest China's Guizhou
Province from extinction, thanks to the development of artificial
breeding techniques for this very endangered species.
</P>
<P>
Covered with golden hair, the four young golden monkeys bred by
artificial means are all in good health. The Fanjingshan natural
reserve zone of the province has spent 1.5 million yuan (about
190,000 U.S. dollars) to establish a farm for the Guizhou golden
monkeys, which are also known as grey golden monkeys.
</P>
<P>
This species only lives in areas around the Fanjingshan
Mountain region, and it has been placed under first-category state
protection.
</P>
<P>
Only one of the 11 golden monkeys living on the reserve-zone
farm has died of natural causes, and all of the young monkeys bred
under artificial conditions are healthy, compared with only a 42
percent survival rate in the wild.
</P>
<P>
China first caught and bred a golden monkey in 1991, and now
researchers understand the animal's breeding behavior. "When the
number of golden monkeys increase to a certain level, we will send
them back to nature in groups," said Yang Yeqing, director of the
administration department of the Fanjingshan nature reserve.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
