<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Monopoly on Thai Whisky Industry to Be Ended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A 55-year-old state monopoly
on whisky production in Thailand is to be lifted as the government
approved a plan to liberalize the industry, a government press
release available Wednesday said.
</P>
<P>
Currently, whisky production is monopolized by a business
group, which operates all the 11 state-owned liquor plants through
two concessions from the Finance and Industry Ministries.
</P>
<P>
The government will allow private investors to bid for all the
11 distilleries within 15 years and for the machinery, the press
release said.
</P>
<P>
Interested investors can apply for liquor production within the
next two or three months, but sale of products can only begin
after current concessions expire on December 31, 1999.
</P>
<P>
To make locally-produced liquor more competitive, the
government has decided not to tax whisky production licensing.
</P>
<P>
The Finance Ministry said that even though the government's
income from liquor tax will be reduced, it will earn more from
excise paid by new whisky producers estimated to seize about 50
percent of the total market.
</P>
<P>
The ministry also reported that in 1997, tax collected from
white whisky and blend whisky was 17.8 billion baht (445 million
U.S. dollars), of which 17.2 billion (430 million dollars) was
from state distilleries.
</P>
<P>
Tax collected from beer and wine in 1997 amounted to 21.6
billion baht (540 million dollars) and 42.12 million baht (1.06
million dollars) respectively. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
