<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Bank Tellers Fall Victim to ATMs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- More than 500 bank branches,
or about 8 percent of the total in Australia, have closed in the
past financial year ending June 30, as telephone banking and the
Internet replace the traditional bank tellers.
</P>
<P>
According to latest official statistics available here
Wednesday, the total number of branches across Australia fell by
506 to 5,615 from 6,121, down 8.2 percent, over the past financial
year.
</P>
<P>
The Reserve Bank of Australia, the nation's central bank, said
in a bulletin released this week that the drop added up the number
of branches closed over the past five years to 1,131.
</P>
<P>
Over the same period, the number of automatic teller machines
(ATMs) has jumped by 2,966 to 5,616.
</P>
<P>
People went into a bank branch from time to time, but
day-to-day banking was done electronically at the supermarket,
through electronic machines such as ATMs, or over the telephone
and the Internet, said Eric Kinsella, general manager of the
Commonwealth Bank of Australia's Victoria state branch.
</P>
<P>
As 95 percent of the households in Australia have access to
phones and one million households have access to the Internet, it
is convenient and cost-effective for Australian residents to pay
their bills over the phone or the Internet.
</P>
<P>
The massive closure has led to dismissal of thousands of
tellers by banks.
</P>
<P>
The Australian and New Zealand Banking Corporation, one of the
leading banks in Australia, announced earlier this year a plan to
fire about 2,000 redundant employees in the next few years.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Labor Party, the nation's opposition, has seized
the bank branch closures and banking services as an election
issue.
</P>
<P>
Opposition Leader Kim Beazley said Wednesday Australian banks
would be forced to contribute 20 million Australian dollars (12
million U.S. dollars) to a fund to ensure at least one bank stays
open in every country town if Labor is elected.
</P>
<P>
The closure of hundreds of banks in regional areas in recent
years has devastated many country towns and caused widespread
anger in the rural areas about the loss of services. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
