<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Predict Fulfillment of Economic Growth Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese economists predict
that the nation's economy will grow by a dramatic 9.1 percent in
the fourth quarter of this year.
</P>
<P>
Such a growth rate for the period will ensure that China can
achieve its 1998 economic goal of eight percent growth.
</P>
<P>
A report issued today by the Chinese Academy of Social
Sciences notes that increased investments in fixed assets, more
bank loans and rising income levels for urban residents will be
conducive to an anticipated rebound.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese economy dropped steadily between April and June by
6.9 percent over the same period of last year, representing the
lowest point since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Economists predict that investments in fixed assets will grow
by 16 percent during the fourth quarter, with related growth
expected to stimulate the economy and boost imports. The trade
surplus for the year is expected to hit 45.5 billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Reform of the grain circulation system will lead to slight
rises in prices for grain and food. Price hikes for industrial
products and overall prices increases will be minimal.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey in 34 cities revealed that the trend for
savings will remain strong and consumption power in turn will
remain weak.
</P>
<P>
Economists point to various good signs, but nonetheless note
the economy will face a number of obstacles resulting from
devastating summer floods and the sliding Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
They suggest that measures must be introduced to increase
exports and ensure the stability of the Renminbi.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
