<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Largest Inkstone Unveiled in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Craftsmen in north
China's Hebei Province have completed work on a huge inkstone and
presented it as a gift to greet Macao's return to Chinese
sovereignty next year.
</P>
<P>
The giant inkstone is eight meters long, three meters wide and
one meter tall and weighs more than 30 tons. It is believed to be
the largest of its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
Carved on the body of this "king of inkstones" are 99 flying
dragons and 9 phoenix, representing that the event will take place
in 1999. Nine carved tortoises suggest Macao's return since the
words "tortoise" and "return" sound alike in standard Chinese.
</P>
<P>
The enormous inkstone has two wells designed to contain ink;
one is in the shape of China and the other is carved in the shapes
of the sun, moon, stars and Earth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
