<HEADLINE> Israeli Strikers Threaten to Intensify Stoppage </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 16 (Xinhua) -- As their strike entered
the second day Wednesday, Israeli local authority workers
threatened to intensify it if demands for wage increase were not
met.
</P>
<P>
Trade Union of Israeli Local Authorities said that it had hold
negotiations with the Finance Ministry Tuesday night in an effort
to reach an agreement and end the strike.
</P>
<P>
However, it said, the officials from the ministry still refused
to give a 30 percent wage rise as the trade union suggested after
five hours of talks.
</P>
<P>
A representative of the trade union told Israel Radio that the
negotiations would continue on Wednesday. But he warned that if
the Finance Ministry did not make compromise, the trade union
would "unleash chaos all over the country."
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the Finance Ministry insisted that it would
agree to a wage increase not more than 27.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The trade union launched the strike on Tuesday, which kept
some 100,000 employees from the local authorities across the
country from their work.
</P>
<P>
The strike shut down most of the municipal departments,
hospitals and kindergartens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
