<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nuclear Industry Eyes Civilian Applications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- China's nuclear industry is
accelerating efforts to shift from military production to civilian
applications, and is rapidly becoming a major powerhouse in the
national economy.
</P>
<P>
The industry is operating under a new system featuring a
combination of military and civilian production combined with the
development of nuclear power and a diversified economy, according
to a senior industry official.
</P>
<P>
The sector has established a large number of enterprise groups
in developed coastal areas such as the east China municipality of
Shanghai and the southern province of Guangdong. Enterprises in
the sector have developed over 1,500 products for civilian use.
</P>
<P>
The industry has expanded its economic base by maintaining a
high growth rate for a number of years in succession and has in
turn contributed to dramatic improvements in the nation's
comprehensive economic strength.
</P>
<P>
Products designed for civilian use account for over 80 percent
of the total industrial output volume for China's nuclear sector.
</P>
<P>
The development of nuclear energy represents a major factor
enabling the industry to introduce strategic adjustments,
according to the official.
</P>
<P>
The Qinshan Nuclear Power Station in east China's Zhejiang
Province and the Daya Bay Nuclear Power Plant in Guangdong
province have exemplary safety records and their combined annual
power output is three times the total power China generated in
1952.
</P>
<P>
The two facilities have not only alleviated power shortages in
east China and Guangdong, but have also supplied substantial
quantities of power to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Construction of second and third phase projects at Qinshan, and
the Ling'ao and Lianyungang nuclear power stations is progressing
smoothly.
</P>
<P>
China's nuclear power generating capacity should approach 9.2
million kilowatts by early next century, with earnings from
nuclear power expected to reach 30 billion yuan annually. The
industry plans to further improve its industrial structure,
economic base and technology.
</P>
<P>
Nuclear power currently accounts for one percent of China's
total power output, a level substantially lower than the world
average of 70 percent. Nuclear power is a clean and highly
efficient energy source which enjoys wide-ranging market
advantages in terms of the energy structure, environment and
transportation.
</P>
<P>
Shandong, Fujian and Jiangxi provinces in east China, the
island province of Hainan in the south and Hunan province in
central China are actively preparaing to construct their own
nuclear power plants.
</P>
<P>
China is expected to achieve significant development in the
realm of nuclear power in the 21st century. For example, the
nation's nuclear power generating capacity will reach 20 million
kw by the year 2010, with the figure expected to rise to 40
million kw and account for five percent of the nation's total
power output by 2020. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
