<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Coffee Export Forecast Revised Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Kenya has revised up its
targeted 1997/98 coffee exports to 70,000 tons from originally
40,000 tons, said a spokesman of the state-run Coffee
Board of Kenya (CBK).
</P>
<P>
"Our export estimates for the season (October 1997/September
1998) are 70,000 tons. We can go beyond this figure or below it
but it is our forecast," said CBK's spokesman Paul Kivila.
</P>
<P>
Earlier forecasts had indicated that coffee output would stand
at 40,000 tons because the freak weather had cut the output, the
East African Standard newspaper reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The annual coffee yield averaged 80,000 tons in the east African
country.
</P>
<P>
Kivila was quoted as saying that in spite of the fall in
volume, Kenya would earn about 16-18 billion Shillings (267
million to 300 million U.S. Dollars) from coffee exports
because of the good prices from last October to this month.
</P>
<P>
"Although we got a smaller crop this season, the value is
relatively good because we experienced good prices, which covered
the shortfall," he said.
</P>
<P>
He estimated that the coffee production during the coming year
from October 1998 to September 1999 will rise to between 80,000
and 90,000 tons "if the country is not hit by freak weather
again."
</P>
<P>
Coffee exports, accounting for 25 percent of Kenya's annual
export revenue,is the third biggest export earner in Kenya,led
only by tourism and tea.
</P>
<P>
However, Kivila said that the horticultural industry is
threatening to replace the coffee sector as a major foreign
exchange earner. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
