<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Range Becomes World's Largest Settlement (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YINCHUAN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- More than 750,000 poor
farmers living in mountainous areas in northwest China's Ningxia
Hui Autonomous Region today began to move to new homes on a former
artillery range in central part of the region.
</P>
<P>
The range, the largest of its kind in China, covers 55,300 ha
in the central part of Hongshipu, a vast wasteland which will
become the world's largest settlement over two years.
</P>
<P>
Water from the Yellow River entered irrigation channels this
morning at 10:00 and made its way to the range located some 160 km
from the regional capital of Yinchuan. The roar of water pumps has
now replaced booming artillery rounds characteristic of the past
40 years.
</P>
<P>
Trucks and tractors carrying new residents filled the highway
leading to the range which was formerly restricted to military
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
A septuagenarian Muslim farmer named Yang Yili travelled the
100 km from his former home by donkey cart. His family was in the
first group of new arrivals.
</P>
<P>
Yang formerly lived in one of China's poorest and most arid
mountainous areas in southern Ningxia. The evaporation rate is 10
times the annual rainfall of 300 mm. Farmers lacked access to
adequate cultivatable land and harsh conditions made life
difficult.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, the central government earmarked three billion yuan
(360 million U.S. dollars) to transform Hongshipu into the world's
largest settlement.
</P>
<P>
China used a Kuwaiti government loan of 140 million U.S.
dollars to construct a massive irrigation project to divert water
from the Yellow River to Hongshipu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Range Becomes World's Largest Settlement (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The project will provide ample irrigation for 140,000 ha
surrounding Hongshipu and will facilitate the resettlement and
improve living conditions for some one million poverty-stricken
farmers from the region's mountainous areas.
</P>
<P>
"Geological and topological conditions are suitable for both
military training and farming," according to Liu Xinghua, director
of the artillery range administration.
</P>
<P>
Liu said the Constitution of the People's Republic of China
provides for the military to support national economic
construction by either vacating or opening military installations
for civilian use.
</P>
<P>
A recent White Paper on China's National Defense noted that the
country has opened more than 101 military airports and has either
opened or deactivated 29 military ports and military areas
covering some three million square meters for civilian use over
the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
Water and power systems are in place and an extensive highway
system links Hongshipu with other parts of the region. New
arrivals are currently constructing houses in areas throughout the
former range.
</P>
<P>
Yang's family of 12 has been allocated 1.6 ha of irrigated
land. "I'll level the land as soon as possible in order to plant
spring wheat. My family will no longer have to worry about food
and clothing," said Yang.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Weizheng, director of the massive relocation program,
said that "the resettlement effort will be completed by the year
2000, with Hongshipu becoming a new city about half the size of
Hong Kong." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
