<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts Call For Reintroducing Vegetation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Reintroducing vegetation in
the Yangtze River Valley represents the important measure needed
to prevent flooding in the region, according to experts attending
a symposium on environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Yang Fucheng, a forestry expert from the Southwest China
Forestry Institute, noted that silting has severely hampered the
operational capacities of over 50,000 reservoirs in the Yangtze
River Valley.
</P>
<P>
He said silting in tributaries in middle and lower reaches of
the Yangtze have impeded the normal flow of flood waters and
resulted in rising water levels.
</P>
<P>
An average 200 million cu.m. of silt is deposited in lakes in
the middle and lower reaches of Yangtze each year.
</P>
<P>
The surface area of Dongting Lake has dropped dramatically from
over 4,300 sq.km. in the 1950s to only 2,600 sq.km., with the
lake's flood water control capacity dropping from 29.3 billion
cu.m. to 17.4 billion cubic meters.
</P>
<P>
Experts attending the symposium urged related departments to
take immediate measures to reintroduce vegetation in the
Yangtze River Valley, protect natural forests, develop shelterbelt
systems and close hillsides to facilitate afforestation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0250 </DOCNO>
