<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Olympic Champion Sun Shuwei to Miss Asian Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Sun Shuwei, men's 10-meter
platform gold medalist at the 1992 Barcelona Olympics, will miss
the Bangkok Asian Games in December to focus on preparing for
the 2000 Olympics, his coach Hu Enyong said on Wedbesday.
</P>
<P>
The 22-year-old Sun, also winner of the world championships in
1991 and 1994, finished a modest 10th place in the springboard
event on Tuesday at the current national championships, which
serves as the trial for the Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
Due to an out-of-form, Sun has announced to pull out of his
favorite platform event to be held on Thursday, which means he
gives up the Asian Games, in which he swept the two consecutive
platform golds in the 1990 Beijing and 1994 Hiroshima editions.
</P>
<P>
"Sun had overworked himself in preparing for the 8th National
Games last year," Hu said. "He has been too exhausted. He needs
to relax."
</P>
<P>
The coach said it's also part of the efforts to let Sun
compete in the highboard event this time. "This could move his
attention otherwhere from the platform. But he is sure to
prepare for a participation in the platform event in Sydney."
</P>
<P>
Hu added that winning a second Olympic gold medal is the only
dream to be fulfilled before Sun's retirement. "That's the only
reason he is still diving."
</P>
<P>
Sun failed to take part in the Atlanta Olympic Games after
finishing a disappointing third in the pre-Olympic national
trials with his eyes injury. Then he conceded the Olympic berths
to new hands Tian Liang and Xiao Hailiang, who placed third and
fourth respectively in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
The diminutive star, nicknamed as "big boy" by western
reporters in the Barcelona Olympics, has made a strong comeback
since 1997, winning his speciality event in the National Games in
Shanghai last October and taking the double platform golds at the
Perth World Championships in January and the Goodwill Games in
July in New York.
</P>
<P>
But Russian Dimitry Sautin has emerged as the most powerful
opponent on the platform when Sun was resting his eyes injury in
1996, by winning the golds in the Atlanta Olympics, World
Championships and almost all the major international tournaments.
</P>
<P>
"Sautin has become a hurdle in front of us," Coach Hu said.
"But we're confident to beat him in Sydney."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
