<HEADLINE> China's Tibetan Children Perform in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A group of China's Tibetan
children performed songs and dances from the region's traditional
life and culture in the United States on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The China Tibet Children's Art Troupe performed on the
first-day of the international exchange during the 28th annual
International Children's Festival in Fairfax, Virginia. The event
is scheduled to last till September 20.
</P>
<P>
Also attending the festival at Wolf Trap Farm Park in Fairfax
County are troupes from Argentina, Armenia, Mexico and Russia, as
well as American host children.
</P>
<P>
Before an audience of some 3,000, the Tibetan children, aged 10
to 13, vividly portrayed to the American people and children from
other nations, life, work and the traditional culture in the
Himalayan region.
</P>
<P>
Their dance "A'shie" showed the way Tibetan people sing and
dance while performing their daily work. The Yak Dance, which is
simple and lively, reflected the children's life in the northern
Tibet Grasslands and how they cope with difficulties.
</P>
<P>
For many Americans, it was the first time to see such a
cultural dance performed by a group of girls and boys in
traditional Tibetan dress. Many described the performance as
"wonderful."
</P>
<P>
The 17-member Chinese children's troupe will present a dozen
different songs and dances during the festival. They plan to visit
other parts of the United States after the international art and
cultural exchange. 
</P>
</TEXT>
