<HEADLINE> Clinton: Ties with China Important to U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton on Tuesday told a visiting senior Chinese military leader
that the ties and friendship with China are very important for
America.
</P>
<P>
Clinton met with Zhang Wannian, vice chairman of China's
Central Military Commission, Tuesday evening in the White House.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the meeting said Clinton told the Chinese
general that both sides need to continue their efforts to maintain
the momentum of development, created by top-level exchange of
visits, in the bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
General Zhang said that he had come to the United States to
make concrete arrangements for furthering military ties between
the two countries in line with the agreements reached by the two
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Zhang arrived in Washington Monday afternoon at the invitation
of U.S. Secretary of Defense William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
He said upon arrival that he was seeking implementation of the
agreement reached by the Chinese and U.S. presidents on
military-to-military exchange and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Presidents Jiang Zemin and Clinton exchanged visits in eight
months since last October. They have agreed to establish a
constructive strategic relationship between the two countries,
with closer military-to-military ties as its important part.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday morning, General Zhang and U.S. Secretary Cohen held
talks on military cooperation. They signed a joint statement
afterward on military environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
The statement said that U.S. Defense Department and China's
Defense Ministry have agreed to exchange technical representative
groups to study military environmental protection and discuss
signing a technical document on exchange of relevant information.
</P>
<P>
Among other things, both sides have also agreed to send
observers to watch the other side's military exercises and
dispatch students to study in the other side's military
institutions in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Zhang said that China and the United States have extensive
common interest in and great potential for developing bilateral
relations. It is also conducive to peace and stability in the Asia
Pacific region and the world as a whole.
</P>
<P>
Before Clinton, Zhang met with Sandy Berger, national security
adviser to the president.
</P>
<P>
After the meetings, Secretary Cohen hosted a dinner reception
in honor of General Zhang and his entourage, who are expected to
leave Washington for other destinations in the U.S. Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
