<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mongolia: Slight Industrial Growth, But Sluggish Finance, Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Mongolia saw a moderate
growth in its industrial production in the first eight months this
year but faced serious problems in its public finance and foreign
trade, official reports said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
According to latest figures released by the State Statistics
Bureau, the country's industrial production in the eight months to
August grew by 4.4 percent from the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Among the top growing sectors, woollen textile was up 22.2
percent and mining was up 20.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the country was hopeful of a bumper harvest in
livestock farming, noting that the number of newborn lambs across
the country this year would be close to a record 10 million heads.
</P>
<P>
Between January and August, Mongolia's foreign trade totaled
493.9 million U.S. dollars, down 7.1 percent from the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
Affected by significant falls in copper and cashmere prices on
the international market, the country's export earnings dropped
sharply by 27 percent to 194.5 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Import volume stood at 299.4 million dollars, up by 12.8
percent from the same period last year, leading to a trade deficit
of 104.9 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
In Mongolia's foreign trade, Russia accounted for 23 percent,
followed by China with 16.7 percent and Sweden with 10.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Consumer prices in August rose by 4.8 percent compared with
that in December last year but fell by 2.9 percent compared with
July.
</P>
<P>
Mongolia is suffering serious problems in its public finance,
with a deficit of 36 billion togrog (42 million dollars) in the
first eight months, out of a revenue of 133.5 billion togrog (157
million dollars) and expenditure of 169.5 billion togrog (199
million dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
