<HEADLINE> OSCE Calls for Political Solution to Albanian Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WARSAW, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Polish Foreign Minister
Bronislaw Geremek, in his capacity as the chairman of the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), has
been stepping up consultations for a political solution to the
Albanian crisis.
</P>
<P>
Over the past two days, said a spokesman for the Polish Foreign
Ministry on Tuesday, Geremek has talked over the phone with
Albanian President Rexhep Mejdani, Prime Minister Fatos Nano and
opposition leaders about the situation in the tiny Balkan nation.
</P>
<P>
During their phone conversations, Geremek pointed to the
necessity of political dialogues in the wake of violent unrest in
Tirana, the capital of Albania, touched off by the weekend
assassination of the popular opposition leader Azem Hajdari.
</P>
<P>
In addition, he called for the Albanian government and
opposition leaders' attention to the Polish experience of tackling
similar situations years ago with political roundtables.
</P>
<P>
Geremek was quoted as saying that the crisis in Albania not
only hurts the process toward social and economic stability of the
country itself, but also the stability of the world at large.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, he said, Poland supports the Monday statement of the
European Union (EU) condemning the killing of Hajdari, a leading
opposition deputy in the Albanian parliament and a close friend of
former President Sali Berisha.
</P>
<P>
He added that Poland hopes that Tirana could make thorough
investigation into the assassination.
</P>
<P>
Two days of violent clashes beginning on Monday in Tirana
resulted in the death of at least three people and the injury of
14 others. 
</P>
</TEXT>
