<HEADLINE> Panama to Recover Noriega's Corrupt Money in France </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Panama has sent legal
representatives to recover state funds diverted by former military
strongman General Manuel Antonio Noriega into French banks.
</P>
<P>
Newspapers published here Tuesday quoted the Panamanian
government's General Accountant Gabriel Castro as saying that
Noriega has over 12.6 million U.S. dollars in French banks.
</P>
<P>
Originated from state funds, the money was a result of
corruption and mismanagement during Noriega's rule of the country.
</P>
<P>
Until now, Castro said, Panama has managed to recover, via
legal actions and with cooperation of the French authorities, 7.6
million dollars from frozen bank accounts of the former strongman.
</P>
<P>
The Panamanian legal representatives would try to recover the
rest five million dollars this time, he said.
</P>
<P>
Ousted from power by a U.S. military strike in 1989, Noriega
now is serving a 20-year prison term in the United States for
drug-trafficking. 
