<HEADLINE> Panama Demands Indemnity for Losses by U.S. Invasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Panama is demanding the
United States pay more than 250 million U.S. dollars for
losses caused by the U.S. invasion on December 20, 1989.
</P>
<P>
The National Human Rights Commission of Panama said Tuesday the
amount has increased since more Panamanians have come forward who
claim to have been injured. Originally, only 70 individuals
claimed to have been injured or lost family members during the
invasion.
</P>
<P>
In December 1989, former U.S. President George Bush ordered
U.S. Army troops to enter Panama to overthrow the country's former
strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega.
</P>
<P>
Panamanian legal advisors have met some victims at the city of
Colon, 80 kilometers west of the capital city, and in the
metropolitan neighborhood of El Chorrillo, which was destroyed
during the invasion.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Panamanian legal representative Gilma Camargo has
challenged the accuracy of the U.S. official war report on
Panamanian casualties. The report claims that only 202 civilians
were killed and 314 casualties were reported among military
personnel.
</P>
<P>
Vielka Barria, member of the commission, said the U.S. invasion
left over 18,000 Panamanians homeless and many persons maimed.
</P>
<P>
She said that until now reported cases of clandestine burials
by U.S. troops have not been thoroughly investigated.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, Washington questioned the accuracy of the demands,
which were also rejected by the Interamerican Commission of the
OAE. The OAE also defended its authority to investigate the
case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
