<HEADLINE> Flood Water Receding Fast in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The flood situation throughout
Bangladesh has improved further as water levels of major rivers
such as the Mrahmaputra and Ganges were continuing to fall
remarkably.
</P>
<P>
The situation in and around the capital city of Dhaka has also
improved with the fall of water levels in the Buriganga,
Shitalakhya, Turag and Kaliganga rivers.
</P>
<P>
If the situation continues, the flood situation across the
country is likely to improve markedly by the end of this month,
press reports Wednesday quoting sources of the Flood Forecasting
and Warning Center as saying.
</P>
<P>
However, major rivers are still flowing above the danger mark.
The sources from the center added that whether the water levels of
these rivers would continue to fall rapidly would depend on the
quantum of rainfall in the catchment areas of the major rivers
outside the country and unhindered discharge of waters through the
Meghna estuary.
</P>
<P>
The floods, which have lasted for more than two months, have
killed over 800 people, affected about 30 million people in 52 out
of the country's 64 districts and wrought havoc on agriculture,
industry, properties and infrastructure, according to the latest
figures released by the Ministry of Disaster Management and
Relief. 
</P>
</TEXT>
