<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Czech Economic Situation Worsens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Czech economy is declining
this year and the overall situation continues to deteriorate, the
State Statistical Bureau said Monday.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time in five years the Czech economy has
experienced a downturn.
</P>
<P>
Statistics released by the Bureau show the gross domestic
product (GDP) in the first half of 1998 was 592.8 billion Czech
Korun (19.1 billion U.S. dollars), 1.7 percent less than the same
period last year
</P>
<P>
The first and second quarters respectively saw a drop of 0.9
percent and 2.4 percent, statistics show.
</P>
<P>
The Czech GDP, after continued decline from 1991 to 1993, began
to pick up in 1994 with a growth of 2.7 percent. The economy
entered its best period in 1995, when the GDP increased by 6.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
However, as a result of playing up the function of the market
and ignoring macro-economic control, the country's economic growth
slowed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the Czech economy grew only by 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
Experters predict another drop of 1.5 percent for the Czech
economy this year.
</P>
<P>
Other macro-economic figures are not encouraging. The
unemployment rate in August reached a seven-year high at 6.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
Because of a lack of capital, the country is expected to have a
budget deficit of 26.8 billion Korun (864 million U.S. dollars)
next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar, UN Agency Cooperate on Birth Spacing Survey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 16 (Xinhua)-- Myanmar has been cooperating
with a U.N. organization to make surveys on birth spacing as part
of the country's efforts to strengthen the program.
</P>
<P>
The Myanmar Maternal and Child Welfare Association (MMCWA) and
the United Nations Fund for Population Activities (UNFPA) are
jointly sponsoring a birth spacing course here, attended by MMCWA
members from 10 townships in the country's urban and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
As part of the country's birth spacing program implemented by
the Myanmar Health Department and funded by the UNFPA, the
Myanmar Population Department undertook the fertility and
reproductive health survey (FRHS) in 1997, the second country-wide
demographic survey, to produce reliable estimates of major survey
variables for the whole country, including both urban and rural
areas.
</P>
<P>
The first survey, population changes and fertility survey
(PCFS) which was conducted in 1991, showed Myanmar's fertility
rate standing at 3.5. But in the 1997 survey, it dropped to 2.8.
</P>
<P>
The contraceptive prevalence rate in the PCFS was 16.8 percent
and it has risen to 32.7 percent in the FRHS.
</P>
<P>
The MMCWA, a non-governmental organization formed in 1991, has
made significant progress in getting its more than 540,000 members
involved in activities such as providing health service to mothers
and children in urban and rural areas, reducing the death rate of
mothers and babies and conducting education on breast-feeding.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the infant and maternal mortality rates in Myanmar
were 48.6 and 1.7 per 1,000 births respectively.
</P>
<P>
Myanmar's population is estimated to have reached 46.4 million
in the 1997-98 fiscal year which ended in March, maintaining an
annual growth rate of 1.84 percent, according to official
statistics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
