<HEADLINE> China's Pentathletes to Keep Dominance for years, German </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Former world champion
Hartmut Nienaber of German highly praised China's great
performances in the 46th Military Pentathlon World Championships
on Wednesday, saying China could stay atop in the sport for next
five to ten years.
</P>
<P>
"They had a high performance in the competition and broke
records. They did very well at home," said Nienaber, now the
German's team captain.
</P>
<P>
Nienaber, a ten-time winner of the military pentathlon worlds,
still holds two world records in the sport, which he set early in
1980s.
</P>
<P>
"China has lots of good competitors and could maintain the
dominance for next five to ten years, I think," Nienaber said.
</P>
<P>
China's Li Zhong and Yang Chunyi, winner and silver medalist
in the men's division respectively, were most impressed, Nienaber
added.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese has won four titles with one discipline left on
Wednesday and broke three world records in the championships
which of them have been televised by CCTV.
</P>
<P>
"Military pentathlon is a popular sport in the Chinese army,
but it's not the case in German," Nienaber said. "People there
know nothing about it and have no interest in the competition.
</P>
<P>
"It's impossible for European countries to catch up with China
or even beat them at least in recent years. But the sport will
have a big future," Nienaber continued. 
</P>
</TEXT>
