<HEADLINE> Desert Oil Field Emerges As Oasis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Vegetables are growing and
greenery is expanding in the Taklimakan Desert, known as the "Sea
to Death."
</P>
<P>
The second largest shifting desert in the world, the Taklimakan
in the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region was instilled with life
following the exploration effort of the Tarim Oil Field started in
1989.
</P>
<P>
While oil and gas resources were being tapped, the experimental
growing of vegetables, fruits, and plants was also proving to be
successful, to the delight of tens of thousands of oil workers
from across the country who had settled there.
</P>
<P>
In the Tazhong Oil Field, in the heart of the desert, man-made
greenery has been expanded to 14 hectares. Also, three
greenhouses have been built producing high-yield tomatoes and
cucumbers by taking advantage of the underground water resources.
</P>
<P>
And along the roadside, a 1.2-kilometer long "green belt" has
emerged.
</P>
<P>
The improved environment is drawing the presence of birds and
animals such as the state-protected wild camel.
</P>
<P>
The local oil field authorities have spent a total of 420
million yuan (51 million U.S. dollars) over the past nine years to
protect this fragile environment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
