<HEADLINE> Largest LPG Base Built in East China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NINGBO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Construction of the largest
liquefied petroleum gas base in east China began recently in Daxie
Island, in Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
The base is a key infrastructure project co-funded by the Ningbo
East China Liquefied Petroleum Co., Ltd. and BP Oil Ltd. of
Britain at a cost of 96.5 million U.S. dollars. It is the largest
joint venture in Daxie Island, the country's first development zone
with free-trade-zone status.
</P>
<P>
The project, scheduled to go into operation by the year 2000,
consists of two wharfs, two underground oil-storage containers
each coving 100,000 cubic meters, and other facilities with a
total construction area of 236,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
Daxie Island, near the major port of Ningbo in Zhejiang, became
a national development zone in 1992, with China International
Trust and Investment Corporation as the sole developer.
</P>
<P>
At present, more than 1,000 domestic and foreign-funded firms
have settled in the island and many key infrastructure facilities
are under construction, including a sea bridge that will
soon be opened to traffic.  
</P>
</TEXT>
