<HEADLINE> Shanghai Puts 22 Auto Projects on Bids </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
industrial center, recently listed 22 automobile projects in a bid
to seek foreign investment and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The projects involve estimated investments of 300 million
U.S. dollars each and are mainly designed to produce automobile
parts and components for the city's two joint venture cars --
Santana and Buick. The terms of cooperation range from 20 to 30
years.
</P>
<P>
The offering is part of a three-year program designed to
transform Shanghai into China's largest automobile manufacturing
center.
</P>
<P>
The Shanghai Automobile Industry Corp., the city's leading
manufacturer in the city, plans to readjust its product mix and
attach equal importance to the production of both vehicles and
parts.
</P>
<P>
The corporation's 50 subsidiaries involved in the production of
automobiles, motorcycles, buses, heavy-duty trucks and tractors,
had a combined 1997 sales volume of 73.3 billion yuan and total
export value of 67 million US dollars.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-three of the firms have established joint ventures with
10 multinational companies, including Volkswagen of Germany and
Ford and General Motors of the United States. Joint ventures
contributed 47 percent of the corporation's total sales
volume. 
</P>
