<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmarese Government Denies Detention of NLD Members </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Myanmarese government
Tuesday further denied its detention of more members of the
National League for Democracy (NLD), an major opposition party
with Aung San Suu Kyi as its General Secretary.
</P>
<P>
An official Information Sheet quoted the Myanmarese embassy in
Washington as saying that "no NLD members have been arbitrarily
detained or charged with a crime in recent days."
</P>
<P>
"Some NLD members were recently invited to government guest
houses to discuss matters relating to the unlawful attempt of that
party to unilaterally convene a parliament," the embassy told the
Washington Post.
</P>
<P>
The NLD said in a statement issued the same day that the number
of its members detained since May 27 has gone up to 783, including
196 parliament representatives elected in the 1990 election, and
587 other party organizers.
</P>
<P>
In the 1990 general election, participated by 93 political
parties, the NLD won 396 out of 485 parliamentary seats.
</P>
<P>
The NLD, after winning the election, has repeatedly demanded
the convening of a parliament elected in accordance with the then
Election Law, and on June 23 set a deadline for the ruling State
Peace and Development Council (SPDC) to hold the parliament within
60 days.
</P>
<P>
Receiving no response from the government on the expiry of the
deadline on August 21, the NLD declared its intention to convene
the parliament by itself in September.
</P>
<P>
According to the NLD, 61 parliament representatives-elect and
282 party organizers have so far been arrested after the party
made the declaration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bicycles Become New Kind of Garbage in Beijing, Students Find </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- China has been called the
"Kingdom of Bicycles" because it has more bikes than any other
place in the world. However, the capital city of Beijing is now
rapidly becoming a garbage heap of bicycles.
</P>
<P>
Three local middle school students who are environmental
protection volunteers have found that there are now nearly 3
million abandoned bicycles scattered around the city's residential
areas, along the street sides, and at the corners of out-door
markets.
</P>
<P>
This means that one in four Beijingers has discarded an old
bike, turning it into iron garbage.
</P>
<P>
These bicycles become rotted and covered with dust, forgotten
by their owners, and even ignored by thieves since they are
useless.
</P>
<P>
"So many abandoned bicycles not only occupy a lot of space,
they are also unpleasant to the eyes and destructive to the
environment," said Wang Meng, Li Ying and Ai Yuning, three
students from the No. 2 Middle School Attached to the Beijing
Municipal Railway Administration.
</P>
<P>
They conducted their investigation of discarded bicycles during
this year's summer holidays at schools, research institutes,
residential areas and bicycle-storage locations in the western
district of downtown Beijing.
</P>
<P>
They found that if the 3 million abandoned bicycles were
connected in one long chain, it would be 4,500 kilometers long,
nearly equal to the length of the Mekong River, the third longest
in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Right now, there are no authoritative and accurate statistics
to prove whether they are right or wrong, but their discovery
might bring the issue to official attention.
</P>
<P>
Beijing is among the Chinese cities with the largest number of
bicycles, with around 7 million.
</P>
<P>
The three students also found that most people cannot find
places that collect old bikes, so they simply cast them aside.
</P>
<P>
The students suggested that some old bike parts could be used
for other purposes, and collection depots should be set up in
residential areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0292 </DOCNO>
