<HEADLINE> U.S. House Passes Bill to Try Violent 14-Year-Olds as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House of
Representatives passed a bill Tuesday night that would allow more
juveniles to be tried as adults for violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
The bill, passed by a 280-126 vote, also would renew federal
support for the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children.
</P>
<P>
The juvenile crime provisions were attached to the legislation
to make it more likely that Congress to take final action on them
before adjourning for the year.
</P>
<P>
Democrats argued vigorously against the move, calling its
approach both irresponsible and hardhearted.
</P>
<P>
Representative William Clay, a Democrat, said the bill "would
result in... mandatory adult prosecution of 14-year-olds charged
with serious violent crimes."
</P>
<P>
But Republican supporters said it is time to teach youthful
offenders that their actions have serious consequences.
</P>
<P>
Representative Bill McCollum, a Republican, said juvenile
authorities are overwhelmed by caseloads while many young
offenders escape any kind of punishment. "It is extremely
important for us to recognize that we have a crisis in juvenile
crime today," he said.
</P>
<P>
McCollum said the bill is similar to a juvenile crime bill that
passed the House last year but stalled in the Senate to treat more
youth offenders as adults and urge states to do the same. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
