<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China's Guangxi Airlines Doing Well </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- An airline in Guilin in south
China's Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region has safely transported
2.7 million passengers and nearly 30,000 tons of cargo since it
began flying in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Guangxi Airlines was jointly funded by the Guangxi regional
government and China Southern Airlines based in Guangzhou, capital
of neighboring Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
The airline has now safely flown 28,112 flights with a total
flying time of 40,500 hours, and has been honored by China
Southern Airlines as an advanced unit for its excellent safety
record.
</P>
<P>
The airlines has spent more than 10 million yuan on training 26
pilots in the United States, in addition to its annual 3.5-
million-yuan domestic training program in Zhuhai, Guangdong
Province.
</P>
<P>
Facing a sluggish aviation market in China this year, the
airlines nevertheless is enjoying a seat occupancy rate of 65
percent.
</P>
<P>
During the first half of this year, Guangxi Airlines did 254
million yuan worth of business, with profits exceeding 15.9
million yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
