<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Transport Ministers Meet in Austria </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VIENNA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Austrian Transport Minister
Caspar Einem said Tuesday that most EU transport ministers agree
in principle on the liberalization of the European Union railways.
</P>
<P>
He spoke at a press conference with the EU commissioner for
transport Neil Kinnock after the EU transport ministers met
Tuesday in the Austrian city of Feldkirch for a two-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
Free transportation of EU railways and environmental problems
caused by vehicles were the major topics.
</P>
<P>
Sources close to the meeting said that France opposed the
liberalization idea, and Belgium also had doubts about it.
</P>
<P>
But Austria believed that railway liberalization would help
restore some of the volume of rail freight lost in the past 20
years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics shows that from 1970 to 1996, the volume of rail
freight dropped from 30 percent to 15 percent of the total freight
volume. 
</P>
</TEXT>
