<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Industrial Production Grows 8.5 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Industrial production in the
Yugoslav Republic increased by 8.5 percent in the past eight
months over the same period last year, the Federal Statistical
Bureau announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Although the sanctions against Yugoslavia have not been lifted
and the situation in Kosovo is still turbulent, Serbia, one of two
republics in the federation, had an industrial growth of 9.7
percent in the past eight months compared to the same period last
year, while the republic of Montenegro fell 4.5 percent, the
assistant to the general director of the bureau, Mirjana
Ranokovich, told a press conference.
</P>
<P>
The industrial production of the two autonomous provinces,
Vojvodina and Kosovo, increased by 8 percent and 4.5 percent
separately, while the native land of Serbia had a growth of 10.5
percent, according to Ranokovich.
</P>
<P>
Most of the industrial sectors in the republic, including the
electric power industry, metallurgical industry, food processing
industry and chemical industry, grew in a range of 0.6 to 15.9
percent more than the same period in 1997, she said.
</P>
<P>
Exports also increased by 4.3 percent to 1.536 billion
U.S. dollars, while imports were 3.085 billion U.S.dollars, a 1.7
percent increase over the same period last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
