<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest China Province Encouraging Overseas Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Qinghai
Province is making new efforts to encourage overseas investors to
participate in its resource-based development.
</P>
<P>
The latest effort came when the provincial government recently
worked out a regulation granting additional preferential policies
to attract overseas investors.
</P>
<P>
A government official said that Qinghai is abundant in natural
resources such as oil, gas, water and salt lakes for potash
fertilizer, all of which are ready for exploration.
</P>
<P>
According to the new regulation, preferential policies will be
given to export-oriented overseas-funded firms, high-tech
enterprises, enterprises involving agriculture and animal
husbandry, and such infrastructure projects as transportation,
energy, and communications.
</P>
<P>
Overseas-funded enterprises engaging in infrastructure
facilities and financial projects will be exempted from paying
fees for land use.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also makes it possible for overseas businesses
to invest in Qinghai in various ways such as joint-ventures,
purchasing, shareholding, and underwriting state-owned enterprises.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government has asked governments at all levels
to improve the investment environment by completing approval
procedures for overseas-invested enterprises within ten business
days.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the regulation, during the January-July period
overseas investment soared to 10.3 times that of the same period
last year.
</P>
<P>
In the first seven months this year, the province approved 15
overseas-invested enterprises, involving 196 million
U.S. dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
