<HEADLINE> France Calls for Contact Group Meeting on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
proposed on Tuesday that the "Contact Group" on former Yugoslavia
meet next week to impact a United Nations resolution on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
During 30-minute phone talks with his Russian counterpart Boris
Yeltsin, Chirac expressed concerns over continued fighting in the
Serbian province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
Worried about deteriorating conditions for people living in
Kosovo, he called for the Contact Group, of Britain, France,
Germany, Italy, Russia and the United States, to meet in New York.
</P>
<P>
As a spokesman said, Chirac was hopeful, after talks with
Yeltsin, of a U.N. resolution "to show the determination of the
international community to bring about an end to the fighting."
</P>
<P>
"France is renewing its efforts at the United Nations to get a
resolution (on Kosovo) adopted" in the near future, said the
spokesman with the president's office.
</P>
<P>
Chirac also briefed Yeltsin on his recent phone talks with
U.S. President Bill Clinton and German Chancellor Helmut Kohl,
saying that both leaders stressed the halt of fighting as a
precondition for reopening negotiations.
</P>
<P>
The strife in Kosovo, where 90 percent of the population are
ethnic Albanians, has killed at least 700 people and turned some
265,000 others to refugees since ethnic Albanian fighters started
a war of independence earlier this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
