<HEADLINE> Italy Calls for Restoration of Law, Order in Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister
Lamberto Dini Tuesday urged the political forces in Albania to
respect law and refrain from violence and threats of violence.
</P>
<P>
Dini, briefing an emergency session of the foreign affairs
committee of the Senate and the Chamber of Deputies, called on the
Albanian government to bring to justice the killers of a popular
opposition leader whose death sparked the unrest in the Balkan
country.
</P>
<P>
He said although Tirana returned to a semblance of normality
after two days of unrest, "the risk of a civil war in Albania is
ever present."
</P>
<P>
Dini said "no one" could replace an elected government and
parliament in maintaining law and order, adding that Albanian
President Rhxhep Mejdani could play a key role in reconciling the
conflicting factions.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Italian Prime Minister Rano Prodi
called Albania's Prime Minister Fatso Nano and opposition
leader Sali Berisha, saying Italy would not recognize "the result
of the exercise of violence as an instrument of political struggle
in Albania," according to Prodi's office.
</P>
<P>
Violent clashes in Tirana were touched off by the weekend
slaying of a leading opposition deputy in parliament Azem Hajdari,
a close associate of former President Sali Berisha. At least three
people have been killed and 14 wounded in the past two days of
political protest and street violence. 
</P>
