<HEADLINE> Shanghai Promotes Tourism on Internet </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
economic center, recently opened a website on the Internet to
promote tourism.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai International Tourism, the third such site launched
on the Internet in China, after Hong Kong and Beijing, was
jointly initiated by the municipal organizing committee of the
Shanghai Tourism Festival, Shanghai Jiaotong University and the AST
computer center in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The site includes guides to scenic spots, tourist agents,
hotels, restaurants, shopping centers and recreational facilities
in the city.
</P>
<P>
The new web page highlights the Shanghai Tourism Festival which
will be held from October 17 to November 8.
</P>
<P>
Recent statistics show that the number of overseas tourists
coming to Shanghai in the first half of the year was 729,200, down
seven percent from the same period last year due apparently to the
impact of the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
Since last October, the city has taken steps to attract outside
tourists by sending out 100 tourism promotion teams to other
countries, issuing 900,000 tourist guide brochures and video tapes
to overseas agents.
</P>
<P>
Local tourist agents have also created many new types of
tours enabling tourists to "be a Shanghainese for a day,"
"honeymoon in Shanghai" and "cross the millennium."  
</P>
</TEXT>
