-- All countries and various political forces, their leaders in
particular, should strengthen dialogue and cooperation and explore
ways to bring a peaceful and prosperous world into the 21st
century, said Chinese President Jiang Zemin yesterday during his
meeting with Pierre Mauroy, president of the Socialist
International.
</P>
<P>
-- China will continue to maintain the value of its currency
despite the widening Asian financial crisis. At the same time, the
Chinese government is stepping up its crackdown on foreign
exchange infractions such as the evasion of foreign exchange
payment and illegal dealings in foreign exchange amid a resurgence
in black market activities.
</P>
<P>
Responding to questions by reporters at a press conference, a
spokesman for the State Administration of Foreign Exchange said
that the growth of such infractions is a result of the influence
of the external economic environment and has already exerted a
negative impact on China's foreign exchange balance, and thus
should be firmly combated.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- High-level Sino-Japanese talks on the economy will help
maintain steady development in the economic relationship between
the two countries, a Chinese official said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
-- The Beijing-based Association for Relations Across the
Taiwan Straits (Arats) yesterday outlined its proposal on chief
Taiwan negotiator Koo Chen-fu's visit to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
-- The Ministry of Labor and Social Security moved yesterday to
give assurances to China's employees on the current pension system
and refuted rumors circulating on the Internet. 
</P>
