<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Urges Iran, Afghanistan Refrain From Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. administration
Tuesday urged Iran and Afghanistan to avoid military conflict as
the tensions between the two countries are rising and may erupt
into a cross-border war at any time.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a regular briefing, State Department spokesman
James Rubin said, "We urge all the parties in the region to
respect international borders and to refrain from taking actions
which would inflame or enlarge the conflict."
</P>
<P>
When asked if the outbreak of war would raise the possibility
of U.S. involvement, he said, "I've never heard anybody suggest
that."
</P>
<P>
"The capabilities are clearly in place for this kind of
military action that we have been urging not to take place," Rubin
said.
</P>
<P>
"We don't want to see actions that inflame or make the
situation worse nor actions by neighbors to interfere," Rubin
added.
</P>
<P>
However, speaking at the regular Defense Department briefing,
Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said, "I do not have any
indication of imminent military action along that border."
</P>
<P>
Both Iran and Afghanistan have massed troops on their common
border since the fundamentalist Taliban, in control of
Afghanistan, admitted Thursday to killing eight Iranian diplomats
and a journalist last month.
</P>
<P>
Iran on Tuesday called for nationwide demonstrations and put
its military and top civilian officials on full alert, reports
said.
</P>
<P>
Rubin also said that the United States understands the Iranian
government's anger over the killing of its diplomats.
</P>
<P>
"The inviolability of diplomats and diplomatic residences and
embassies is one of the oldest rules of a civilized society," he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
