<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Current Account Deficit Drops Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' current
account deficit in the first half of this year dropped to 100
million U.S. dollars from 224 million dollars recorded in the
first five months of the year, according to the country's central
bank.
</P>
<P>
In a report published Wednesday, the Central Bank of the
Philippines attributed the sharp drop to the country's sustained
export growth.
</P>
<P>
"For the month of June alone, there was a current account
surplus, bringing the January-June current account in near
balance," Central Bank Governor Gabriel Singson was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Central bank officials also clarified that the recent current
account deficit was only based on preliminary figures and that it
was possible the gap could be "lower than 100 million dollars."
</P>
<P>
Stronger inflow of dollar-denominated funds coming from foreign
borrowings during the period also contributed to the shrinking of
the country's current account, according to the report. 
</P>
</TEXT>
