<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB to Start Investigating Corruption in Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank has set up two
teams of experts consisting of its own staff and independent
consultants in a bid to clean up corruption in Indonesia,
especially that involving the bank's funds, national newspapers
reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The teams were scheduled to come here this week and next week
to help the Indonesian government shape new strategies to reduce
corruption, the World Bank country director for Indonesia, Dennis
de Tray, said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"There's no question that the World Bank has made mistakes in
the past in its efforts to ensure that the projects were well
managed, but we want to set the past behind us and make sure that
few mistakes are made in the future," he said.
</P>
<P>
The first team from Washington, headed by the bank's regional
manager of its social development sector unit Katherine Marshall,
is already here to start inquiring into the issue of corruption in
the country.
</P>
<P>
Marshall expected the team to be able to define the corruption
problems in the country by the end of the week, and be ready to
propose subsequent steps to reduce graft over the next six to
12-month period.
</P>
<P>
The sweeping move to tackle corruption comes a month after the
Asian Wall Street Journal published details of a World Bank
internal memorandum which disclosed that more than 20 percent of
the bank's loans were believed to have been siphoned off by
Indonesian officials.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Coordinating Minister for Development Supervision
and State Administrative Reform Hartarto Sastrosoenarto encouraged
all elements in society to help the government root out graft by
providing any evidence they had of its existence.
</P>
<P>
"The government will protect those who come forward to report
corruption cases against retribution," he said, adding that it
would also protect the rights of those accused. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0319 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Denies Support for Intervention in Congo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. administration
said on Tuesday that the conflict in Congo is among the most
dangerous in the world, and the United States is not helping any
of the country's neighbors to intervene.
</P>
<P>
Testifying at a hearing of the House International Relations
subcommittee, Assistant Secretary of State Susan Rice for African
affairs called allegations of American involvement "a specious and
ridiculous accusation that I want to lay to rest once and for all."
</P>
<P>
"We share regional and international frustration with the
Kinshasa government's failures with respect to both
democratization and human rights," said Rice.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless, we have firmly expressed the United States'
conviction that foreign intervention to topple the government
of... Congo is not acceptable," she added.
</P>
<P>
She said the fighting "threatens regional stability, hampers
economic progress, endangers the lives of millions of people,
perpetuates human rights abuses and impedes the democratic
transformation of Africa's third largest country."
</P>
<P>
At the same hearing, Congo's ambassador to the United States,
Faida Mitifu, repeated her government's suspicion that the U.S.
tacitly approves the invasion of Congo by troops from Rwanda and
Uganda.
</P>
<P>
"We hope this perception is not true," said the U.S.-educated
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, Mitifu said, U.S. officials have a "lopsided view
of the hostilities," and she noted frequent pronouncements from
Washington of the right of Congo's neighbors to secure their
borders.
</P>
<P>
In outlining the U.S. position, Rice said all foreign troops
must leave Rwanda for a lasting resolution of the conflict and
repeated calls for an immediate cease-fire and negotiations by all
parties.
</P>
<P>
Congolese President Laurent Kabila says rebels trying to
overthrow him are backed by Rwanda and Uganda, which in May 1997
helped him oust dictator Mobuto Sese Seko. Rwanda and Uganda deny
the allegations.
</P>
<P>
Also testifying at the hearing, Rwanda's ambassador, Theogene
Rudsingwa, insisted that his country is not involved in the Congo.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador agreed all foreign troops should withdraw but
added that would not solve the problem of conflicts within the
Congo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0320 </DOCNO>
