<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0324 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexico's Public Debt Jumps High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's public debt was
up 28.83 percent in the first half of the year to a total of 912
billion pesos (about 91 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The hike, over that of last year, led to a rise in the debt
service, as world financial instability turned into high interest
rates, said the journal El Financiero on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
In a supplementary analysis, the journal said if the current
trend continues for the rest of the year, an extra debt service
cost of 1.167 billion dollars would occur to the country.
</P>
<P>
As a result, experts were quoted as saying, total foreign
indebtedness as a proportion of Mexico's gross domestic product
(GDP) would be likely to go to 30.1 percent by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
The proportion stood at 29.4 percent at the end of June.
</P>
</TEXT>
