<BODY>
<HEADLINE>   Jordan Accused of Breaking Contract Promise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Michael Jordan was
accused of breaking promise regarding a movie contract but the
Chicago Bulls star denied Tuesday in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
"When you make a promise and you commit to do something, you
must honor that promise," Dean Dickie, the plaintiff's lawyer,
told jurors during opening statements in Cook County Circuit
Court.
</P>
<P>
Jordan sat at the defense table Tuesday, using a back entrance
to the courtroom to avoid reporters and onlookers. He is to
testify next week in a case expected to last about a month.
</P>
<P>
The 1993 lawsuit filed by Heaven Corp. accuses Jordan of
backing out of the film "Heaven is a Playground" after signing a
1988 contract guaranteeing him 350,000 U.S. dollars plus 5
percent of the film's profits.
</P>
<P>
Jordan's lawyer, Frederick Sperling, said his client never
refused to appear and the contract was a preliminary agreement
that was not legally binding. He added that the producers told
Jordan a lie about financing and missed a deadline in that
regard. Jordan has countersued, seeking 4  million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sperling said producers Brian Fried and Keith Bank threatened
Jordan with "high-profile, destructive legal action" and were now
making good on that threat.
</P>
<P>
Spearling charged Heaven Corp and tried to get more money by
waiting to sue until after the Bulls had won two championships
and Jordan was established as a superstar, rather than bring it
when Jordan was less well-known.
</P>
<P>
"They made a hedge," Sperling said."They made the movie
without Michael Jordan and waited to see how it did."
</P>
<P>
The movie, with former Loyola Marymount basketball standout Bo
Kimble assuming Jordan's role, made 168,000 U.S. dollars at the
box office. Dickie said that with Jordan as the star, "We would
have today a movie that is a classic."
</P>
<P>
Heaven Corp. is seeking 16 million to 20 million U.S. dollars
in damages, which it says represents the profit it would have
made had Jordan appeared. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0328 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Folkl Joins Minnesota WNBA Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Kristin Folkl is the
first player assigned to Minnesota's expansion WNBA team,
according to a report here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Folkl, a forward of the 1997-98 All-Pac-10 first team, led
Stanford in scoring (18.9) and rebounding (9.2) last season.
</P>
<P>
"I like challenges," Folkl said. "I feel like all my life I've
been faced with one challenge or another. And I just see this as
a great opportunity to do some good and to be able to conquer
something that a lot of people never thought would come to
fruition."
</P>
<P>
Folkl signed a 3-year contract with the WNBA on April 28, but
she wasn't available to play in the 1998 season because of injury.
</P>
<P>
She also helped Stanford's volleyball team to win two
consecutive NCAA championships. She tore the anterior cruciate
ligament in her left knee in March, had surgery and decided to
pass up her remaining year at Stanford. 
</P>
</TEXT>
