<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 01:00 GMT, September 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The World Bank Tuesday approved an interest-free
credit of 18.6 million U.S. dollars to support Niger's efforts to
improve the efficiency of the public sector and selected utilities.
</P>
<P>
Through privatization and regulatory reform, the western
African country will improve access to and the quality of services
in telecommunications, water and electricity. (WB-Credit-Niger)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States and China have agreed to
cooperate in military environmental protection, realizing the
importance of environmental quality.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Defense Department and China's Defense Ministry issued
here Tuesday a joint statement, saying both sides are concerned
with the quality of the ecological environment, an issue of great
significance to national stability and security.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William S. Cohen and visiting Zhang Wannian,
vice chairman of China's Central Military Commission, put their
signatures on the paper in the Pentagon Tuesday
morning. (US-China-Statement)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The Security Council of the United Nations
Tuesday strongly condemned the murder of Iranian diplomats in
Afghanistan by Taleban combatants.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Security Council was briefed by a U.N.
official on the situation in Afghanistan. The Taleban, a military
faction in Afghanistan, is accused of killing nine of Iranian
diplomats when it captured the town of Mazar-i-Sharif on August 8,
1998. (UN-Security Council-Taleban)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The Security Council of the United Nations on
Tuesday expressed concern over the activities by the Democratic
People's Republic of Korea involving the test launch on August 31,
1998.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the informal consultation of the
Security Council, the current President of the Council Hans
Dahlgren of Sweden said the members of the Council were seriously
concerned over the test launch by DPRK which was carried out
without prior notification to the countries in the
region. (Security Council-DPRK)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The cooperation between the United States and
Russia will continue despite Russia's economic crisis and
government shakeup, a senior U.S. official said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a hearing of a subcommittee of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, Steven Sestanovich, special advisor of the
State Department on former Soviet regions, said how Russia's
economic crisis is resolved "has profound political implications."
(US-Russia-Relations)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BUCHAREST -- Romanian Foreign Ministry is seriously worried
about the situation in Albania and appeals to all political forces
there to decline violence by giving consistency to the existing
democratic framework.
</P>
<P>
Romania commiserates over the losses of human lives that have
taken place in Tirana lately, and will examine in consultation
with NATO and EU member countries the way in which it can back up
Albania's democratic development, informed the department of the
spokesman for the Romanian Foreign Ministry on
Tuesday. (Romania-Albania)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
AMMAN -- A majority of the workers at the United Nations Relief
and Works Agency's (UNRWA) branch in Jordan Tuesday staged a
one-day strike to protest low wages and poor working conditions.
</P>
<P>
The strike was prompted by the cash-strapped agency's recent
decision to raise the salaries of 10 to 15 senior managers in its
five areas of operation by 30 to 40 percent, the official Jordan
Television quoted an anonymous worker at the agency as
saying. (Jordan-UNRWA-Strike)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Latin American nations face growing pressure to
delay arms purchases as Asia's economic woes spread to the region,
according to the latest edition of a U.S. weekly magazine.
</P>
<P>
Venezuela, the hardest hit Latin American country by the
crisis, has delayed purchasing two F-16 fighter planes and may
scale back purchases of training aircraft, The Defense News
reported. (US-Latin America-Weapons)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations has launched a 54.3
million U.S. dollars appeal for humanitarian assistance to help
some 280,000 displaced persons and refugees residing in the
Yugoslav province of Kosovo and in parts of Albania.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) said on Tuesday
that most of the funds will be used for food and emergency aid,
and will help people prepare for the coming Winter.
</P>
<P>
As a component of the appeal, UNDP is asking for 1.4 million
U.S. dollars to improve living conditions for the local population
in Tropoje, a poor district in Albania where a large concentration
of refugees from Kosovo now reside. (UN-Appeal-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- British Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown said
Tuesday he would present proposals by the the Group of Seven (G7)
industrial nations on how to deal with the serious global
financial situation.
</P>
<P>
Brown, due to pay a brief visit to Japan Wednesday, told
reporters that Japan, the world's second-largest economy, was a
key engine for growth in Asia and the rest of the world. (UK-G7
Proposals)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
HANOI -- Vietnam and the United States began their sixth round
of talks on a bilateral trade agreement in Hanoi on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The two countries will deal with issues involving the rights of
American firms to engage in import and export activities in
Vietnam and the degree of openness in the service market, sources
said.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam Trade Ministry officials said Vietnam must revise a
number of trade policies that were inconsistent with World Trade
Organization (WTO) principles if it wanted to solve the problems
in those issues. (Vietnam-US-Trade)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- Egyptian Prime Minister Kamal el-Ganzouri Tuesday
called upon the Israeli government and people to work for
materializing comprehensive peace in the Middle East.
(Egypt-PM-Israel) 
</P>
