<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia Tie Brazil 2-2 in U.S. Cup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Olga Letyushova scored in
the 82nd minute as Russia played to a 2-2 draw with Brazil in the
women's U.S. Cup soccer series in Oneonta, New York, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Russians, still fighting for a berth in next year's
Women's World Cup, nearly upset the South American champions in
the final minutes despite being overmatched for much of the
second half.
</P>
<P>
Letyushova scored the apparent game-winner on a long pass in
the 87th minute but it was disallowed when she was ruled offside.
</P>
<P>
Brazil is one of 10 teams already qualified for the 1999
Women's World Cup, which will be played in the United States from
June 19 through July 10.
</P>
<P>
Brazil took a 2-0 lead in the first half on goals by Pretinha.
</P>
<P>
Pretinha drove a left-footed shot high into the right corner
in the 25th minute on an assist from Roseli. She made it 2-0 at
the end of the first half after sending a long shot past Russian
keeper Svetlana Petko.
</P>
<P>
The Russians finally scored four minutes into the second half
when Natalia Barbashina rolled a soft shot past her on a feed
from Inna Grigorieva.
</P>
<P>
The series resumes on Friday in Rochester when Brazil plays
Mexico and the United States plays Russia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0336 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feyenoord, Villa and Brann Score Respective Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Feyenoord had a flying start
in the UEFA Cup when they defeated VFB Stuttgart 3-1 in the first
round, first leg match on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Feyenoord, clear at the top of the Dutch league after winning
their first four games, outgunned last season's Cup Winners' Cup
runners-up with Jon Dahl Tomasson and Jean-Paul van Gastel
scoring all their goals in the first half.
</P>
<P>
English league leaders Aston Villa did it the other way round
as they produced a remarkable late assault to beat visiting
Norwegian part-timers Stromsgodset 3-2.
</P>
<P>
Villa trailed 2-0 with seven minutes left but emerged
victorious as 18 year-old substitute Darius Vassell scored twice
in injury time.
</P>
<P>
Another Norwegian side Brann Bergen also went 2-0 up against
the odds but their defence stood firm to shock Werder Bremen.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Italian side Parma produced a shock defeat when
they lost to Fenerbahce 1-0 in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
There were no such slips for fellow Italians AS Roma or
Liverpool, Monaco, Club Bruges and Real Sociedad, who all notched
up good away wins and look well-placed to advance.
</P>
<P>
In what always looked the tie of the round, in-form Feyenoord
went ahead in Stuttgart after 19 minutes through van Gastel and
doubled the lead two minutes later through Tomasson.
</P>
<P>
Fredi Bobic pulled one back for the Germans in the 31st minute
but seconds later Tomasson, who joined Feyenoord this summer
after a goal-shy season at Newcastle, outsprinted veteran
defender Thomas Berthold to make it 3-1.
</P>
<P>
The victory completed a great night for the Netherlands as
Willem II Tilburg and Vitesse Arnhem both notched up 3-0 home
wins over Dynamo Tblisi and AEK Athens respectively.
</P>
<P>
But there was more disappointment for Germany as Bremen were
embarrassed by Bergen.
</P>
<P>
Bremen are bottom of the Bundesliga with just one point from
four games and lost to goals in each half by Arne Vidar Moen and
Kjetil Lovvik.
</P>
<P>
Bayer Leverkusen, winners of this tournament in 1988, looked
on course to give the Germans some joy as they led Udinese throu
gh an early Ulf Kirsten goal.
</P>
<P>
But the Italians clinched a draw eight minutes from time
through Johan Walem.
</P>
<P>
Villa, quarter-finalists last season, were staring disaster in
the face as Anders Michelsen and Christer George had Stromsgodset
2-0 up after 23 minutes.
</P>
<P>
But Gary Charles reduced the deficit in the 83rd minute before
Vassell produced his heroics.
</P>
<P>
Parma were undone in Turkey by Romanian striker Viorel
Moldovan's 23rd minute header.
</P>
<P>
The Italians were not helped by a red card for midfielder Dino
Baggio after an hour and ended with nine men as defender Fabio
Cannavaro was sent off in injury time.
</P>
<P>
Bruno Rodriguez struck in the last minute to give Metz a vital
away goal in a 2-1 defeat against Crvena Zvezda (Red Star)
Belgrade and fellow French club Marseille needed an equaliser by
Eric Roy seven minutes from time to salvage a 2-2 draw at Sigma
Olomouc of the Czech Republic.
</P>
<P>
Monaco, however, cruised to a come-from-behind 3-1 away win
against Poland's LKS Lodz.
</P>
<P>
Bruges thumped Ujpest 5-0 in Hungary, despite having defender
Tjorven De Brul sent off in the 62nd minute.
</P>
<P>
The Belgians were already 4-0 up by then with goals by Edgaras
Jankauskas, Aleksander Ilic, Sven Vermant and Darko Anic. Elonja
Ekakia added the fifth in the last minute.
</P>
<P>
Liverpool were also in fine form in Slovakia as they
overwhelmed Kosice 3-0.
</P>
<P>
Patrik Berger, Karlheinz Riedle and Michael Owen, with a
trademark run and shot, were on target.
</P>
<P>
Fellow English side Leeds scraped an unimpressive 1-0 home win
over Maritimo of Portugal thanks to Jimmy Floyd Hasselbaink but
Blackburn lost 1-0 at home to Olympique Lyon, Pole Kacek Bak
striking a superb 25 meter goal four minutes from time.
</P>
<P>
Second half goals by Francesco Totti and Dimitry Alenichev
gave Roma a 2-0 away win over Danish side Silkeborg while
Brazilian Edmundo scored twice as Fiorentina recovered from a
goal down and the dismissal of Italian defender Moreno Torricelli
to defeat Hajduk Split 2-1 in a match played in Bari.
</P>
<P>
In a good night for Spain, only Real Betis, 1-0 losers at
Vejle of Denmark, failed to win.
</P>
<P>
Real Sociedad triumphed 4-2 at Sparta Prague, Valencia won 4-3
at Steaua Bucharest in a thriller, Celta Vigo edged Romanians
Arges Pitesti 1-0 and Atletico Madrid beat Obilic of Yugoslavia
2-0.
</P>
<P>
There was also a good win for FC Zurich, 4-0 at home over
Anorthosis Famagusta, while Schalke 04, UEFA Cup winners in 1997,
struggled to a 1-0 home win over Slavia Prague. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
