<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading Australian Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading Australian newspapers Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Australian:
</P>
<P>
-- Australia's Opposition Leader Kim Beazley Tuesday made a 900
million U.S. dollar bid to become the "education prime minister,"
linking big increases in education funding to the nation's
long-term national security.
</P>
<P>
The Sydney Morning Herald:
</P>
<P>
-- United States President Bill Clinton has endorsed a global
strategy by governments of about 20 nations or economies and the
International Monetary Fund to tackle what he calls the biggest
financial challenge facing the world in half a century.
</P>
<P>
-- The ruling Australian Liberal Party and National Party
coalition's reliance on a low-key, Goods and Services
Tax-dominated election campaign is being questioned within Liberal
ranks as opinion polls indicate their opponent the Australian
Labor Party may be performing better than expected.
</P>
<P>
The Age:
</P>
<P>
-- Australian Taxation Office staff in the state of Victoria
were investigated for more than 240 alleged incidents of
corruption, fraud, accepting bribes and unlawfully accessing
individuals' tax files between 1994 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Australian Financial Review:
</P>
<P>
-- U.S. President Bill Clinton Tuesday launched a coordinated
response to the spreading global economic crisis, calling for
joint action by the Group of Seven industrialized countries to
address "the biggest financial challenge facing the world in half
a century." 
</P>
