<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Condemns Murder of Iran's Diplomats </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council
of the United Nations Tuesday strongly condemned the murder of
Iranian diplomats in Afghanistan by Taleban combatants.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the Security Council was briefed by a U.N.
official on the situation in Afghanistan. The Taleban, a military
faction in Afghanistan, is accused of killing nine of Iranian
diplomats when it captured the town of Mazar-i-Sharif on August 8,
1998.
</P>
<P>
In its presidential statement, the Security Council said the
murder is a crime committed in flagrant violation of international
law and despite repeated assurances by the Taleban leaders
guaranteeing the safety and security of the personnel of foreign
missions in Mazar-i-Sharif.
</P>
<P>
The council expressed its deepest condolences to the families
of the Iranian diplomats and to the government of Iran, and it
believed that this criminal act should be fully investigated with
participation of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
The council demanded that the Taleban release other Iranians
detained in Afghanistan and ensure their safe and dignified
passage out of Afghanistan without further delay.
</P>
<P>
The council expressed its deep concern at the escalating
military operations in Bamyan province and at reports of mass
killings of civilians in northern Afghanistan, and demanded that
the Taleban fully respect international humanitarian law and human
rights.
</P>
<P>
The council called on all concerned to exercise the maximum
restraint and urged the parties, in particular the Taleban, to
take action in response to the strong concerns by the
international community, to stop fighting and resume negotiations
aimed at achieving a peaceful settlement of the conflict on the
basis of the relevant resolution of the General Assembly and of
the Security Council. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
