<DOCNO> XIE19980916.0346 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S., China Agree to Cooperate in Military </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The United States and
China have agreed to cooperate in military environmental
protection, realizing the importance of environmental quality.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Defense Department and China's Defense Ministry issued
here Tuesday a joint statement, saying both sides are concerned
with the quality of the ecological environment, an issue of great
significance to national stability and security.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary William S. Cohen and visiting Zhang Wannian,
vice chairman of China's Central Military Commission, put their
signatures on the paper in the Pentagon Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Both sides "recognize the importance of the military's role in
environmental protection, including monitoring the environment and
eliminating the threat posed to the nations by environmental
degradation."
</P>
<P>
They are prepared to cooperate on the matter and intend to
exchange technical representative groups to study military
environmental protection, and intend to discuss signing a
technical document on exchange of relevant information.
</P>
<P>
This is seen as another step toward closer military-to-military
ties between the two countries. When Cohen visited Beijing in
January, both sides signed an agreement to avoid sea accident
through consultation.
</P>
<P>
The signing ceremony followed a meeting between Cohen and
General Zhang. Their discussions covered bilateral relations, the
Korea Peninsula and nuclear proliferation with focus on
military-to-military relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"During our productive meetings, we covered other ways to
deepen, to broaden, and to advance our military relationship,"
Cohen told a press conference in the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources from both sides, they have agreed
to carry out sand table exercises on disaster relief and
humanitarian assistance in 1999.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese ship will visit the United States in 1999 and conduct
a seminar on sea search and rescue, while each country is going to
allow the other to observe specific military exercises and both
sides have agreed to exchange some military students, beginning
with short course programs.
</P>
<P>
Both sides have agreed that China will send a delegation to
Sandia National Laboratory's Cooperative Monitoring Center. "This
is going to allow the PLA (People's Liberation Army) delegation to
study ways to enhance measures to build security and confidence,"
Cohen said.
</P>
<P>
"These meetings allow frank dialogue on global and regional
security issues of mutual concern, and we are working together
where we can openly discuss issues of disagreement that arise as
well," he added.
</P>
<P>
General Zhang, who arrived here Monday afternoon at Cohen's
invitation and also appeared at the press conference, said that he
had come to the United States for implementation of the agreement
reached by the two presidents.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin and his American counterpart Bill Clinton
have exchanged visits in an eight-month period of time since last
October. They agreed to build a constructive strategic
relationship between the two countries on the threshold of the
next century. Military cooperation is an important part of it.
</P>
<P>
"Both China and the United States are countries that carry
considerable weight and shoulder major responsibilities in the
world. To maintain and develop a healthy and stable relationship
between our two countries is in the fundamental interests of our
two sides and conducive to peace and stability in the world,"
Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
He described his formal talks with Secretary Cohen on issues of
mutual interest as "positive, constructive and productive," adding
the newly signed joint statement is, in particular, beneficial to
the further development of state-to-state and military-to-military
relations between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
"I am also looking forward to meeting with other officials of
the U.S. government and the military, and meeting with friends,
both old and new," Zhang said.
</P>
<P>
He is scheduled to meet with President Clinton before Secretary
Cohen hosts a dinner reception Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Zhang's current visit to the United States is expected to last
about 10 days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
