<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Task Force Gives Bank Mergers Conditional </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A Canadian government task
force said Tuesday that the proposed bank mergers "can be a valid
business strategy" but that the public interest should be
protected.
</P>
<P>
"There should be no absolute ban on mergers among large banks,
insurance companies or other financial institutions," the task
force said in a report released here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
"However, no such merger should take place if it is not
consistent with the public interest," it noted.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, four of Canada's six largest banks proposed
to merge into two, which could drastically change the landscape of
Canada's banking industry and the way Canadians bank.
</P>
<P>
The task force report will surely ignite another round of
fierce debate that pit consumer activists opposing the mergers
against the banks which argue they need mergers to face global
competition.
</P>
<P>
Canada's House of Common's finance committee is scheduled to
start hearings next week on the report. The Senate banking
committee will begin its own hearing the week after next.
</P>
<P>
Later this fall, the federal Competition Bureau and the
superintendent of Financial Institutions will turn over their
separate report to the government on whether the mergers should
proceed.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Paul Martin will have the final say on the
mergers. His decision is not expected to be made until early next
year.
</P>
<P>
"This government wants to make clear that no major bank merger
would be allowed to proceed without public hearings on that
specific merger proposal," Martin said in a statement after the
releasing of the report.
</P>
<P>
"This will guarantee that the people of Canada will have every
chance to be heard, because it is the interest of all Canadians
that will determine the final decision," Martin said.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian government set up the task force 20 months ago to
study the changing face of the country's banking industry. A total
of 124 recommendations were made by the group, including:
</P>
<P>
-- direct access to the payments system for life insurance
companies, mutual funds and investment dealers so they can provide
transactions services to Canadians;
</P>
<P>
-- the ability for banks to offer insurance and leasing to
their customers through their branches;
</P>
<P>
-- adoption of legislation to allow foreign banks to operate in
Canada through branches of their foreign parent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
