<HEADLINE> Security Council Expresses Concern Over DPRK's Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council
of the United Nations on Tuesday expressed concern over the
activities by the Democratic People's Republic of Korea involving
the test launch on August 31, 1998.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after the informal consultation of the
Security Council, the current President of the Council Hans
Dahlgren of Sweden said the members of the Council were seriously
concerned over the test launch by DPRK which was carried out
without prior notification to the countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
Dahlgren said the members of the Security Council considered
such activities by DPRK pose harm to the fishing and shipping
activities in the region and run counter to the promotion of
confidence among the countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
The President said the members of the Council appealed to DPRK
to refrain from the activities which could result in such
developments, and called on all the countries concerned in the
region to show restraints and refrain from any actions that may
lead to increased tension.
</P>
<P>
He said members of the Council recognized the legitimate rights
of any states to develop space programs for peaceful purposes.
</P>
</TEXT>
