<DATE_TIME> 1998-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Views NATO Enlargement in Balkans Absolutely </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BUCHAREST, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Italy viewed NATO's
enlargement in South-Eastern Europe, and particularly in the
Balkans, as an "essential point in Europe's security prospects,"
Italian Defense Minister Beniamino Andreatta said here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
The Italian defense minister, who arrived here Monday for a
three-day official visit, made the statement after a meeting with
his Romanian counterpart, Victor Babiuc.
</P>
<P>
The ways of developing bilateral cooperation between the
Romanian and Italian armies, the outlook of NATO's enlargement in
the second "wave" as well as the aspects of European and regional
security were the main topics approached within their official
talks.
</P>
<P>
Beniamino Andreatta said that Italy would back up the Romanian
army's development in many respects, as well as assist Romania in
its integration into the NATO structures. "We consider our
friendship with Romania as a cornerstone in the creation of a
security area in the Balkans," the Italian minister said, adding
that, however, Italy would not support Romania to the detriment of
other countries.
</P>
<P>
Victor Babiuc said that as far as the Romanian-Italian military
cooperation was concerned, there was a possibility to update the
Romanian army with Italian assistance in the field of
transmission, air force, sea service and mountain corps.
</P>
<P>
Victor Babiuc also expressed his belief that Italy would back
up Romania's integration with NATO in the future because, "as
Beniamino Andreatta has lately stated, NATO's enlargement and
Romania's cooperation with the Alliance are of interest not only
to Romania but to Italy as well to an equal extent." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
